,'2023-12-14 05:10:12',NULL,'Welcome to the forever deaf show. This is a band from El Paso Texas. From F period,U period,C period,K period,Y period,O period.U period. EP. The band\'s name is Circa Arcana and they\'re from the El Paso,Texas from the F,U,C,K,Y,O periods.\n\nThere\'s something called Switch-Blains and Fist fights. Before that, an accept from Too-Mean-to-Die album. There was a thing called Not-My Problem. Connor starts off the show with Saxon from Power and Glory. Then he gets right to the news item of the week. He\'s leaving the band, Razor, Retta-Johnson,Retta-Retta Ripperson as he left. He says he wishes them well and he wishes the band well and Sharif will kill it. He then plays a song called Crossed, which is a song that was originally written by the band.\n\nIt\'s called Razor from the cycle of contempt. This song is called Scaventhsies. It was named after a fossil that was discovered in Luxembourg. It is named after Viacoma, the ancient kind of a brittle star. Then Connor plays two more songs from the album. One is from Orbit Culture and the other is from Native howl.',NULL,NULL),(62676,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/08/Viejoteca - September 8, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-08 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-10 02:49:58',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62677,132,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/08/Global Rare Grooves - September 8, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-08 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-14 04:51:10',NULL,'In this final monologue, Wilde pleads with Evesa to \"open your mind,\" and to \"be your only truth.\" He says that if he wants his freedom, he must \"die, vie.\" In the end, Wilde promises that he will do his best for Evesa and that he was \"best for either one\" of them.\n\nHe says he knows that he is \"depressed,\" but he promises to change. He promises to God, to himself, and to his family that he \"is on Feliz.\" He promises that if flavor lies, \"head cheese and cheek,\" and \"to keep your family feed.\" He resolves to \"cook the rich today.\" This is the final part of Wilde\'s final soliloquy, and he promises that \"days gonna be different.\"',NULL,NULL),(62678,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Bel Araby with CAWA - September 9, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-14 04:31:44',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62679,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/A Dog’s Breakfast - September 9, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-14 04:16:28',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the play, \"Liv and Braden\", which will be performed by the group Tragedy and Music. The play is a contemporary tragedy that focuses on the relationship between two families, the family of a murdered woman and the family who live in a small town in the Midwest.\n\nThe show ends with the announcement that the play will be presented at the small town\'s Little Theatre. A Dog\'s Breakfast is the title of the program that will be airing on the CFRU radio station this week. The program\'s host, Apostrophe, and his partner, Ajay, are at the station to discuss the upcoming Guelph Jazz Festival. The festival will take place from September 17 to September 23 and will feature many of the festival\'s well-known artists. This year, the festival will also host a five-day Colloquium that will bring together the best of the Guelph jazz scene.',NULL,NULL),(62680,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/08/Folk Roots Radio - September 8, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-08 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-14 03:09:14',NULL,'On this week\'s episode of the program, we\'re joined by Janice Hall, Ray Johnson, and Ian MacDonald. The show starts off by playing a bunch of music from the past week, including a few new releases from artists like Justin Rutledge, Skydigger\'s, and Matt Zaddy.\n\nIf you missed the previous show, you can check it out on your favorite podcasting platform. We start off this way, with Justin with Lioness, from his tenth album Something Easy. We also had a great conversation with Justin on this show, and if you missed it, you\'ll find it wherever you listen to podcasts. In the meantime, we play some music from last week, too, including songs from Bruce Coburn\'s Us All, Andy Mays\' On Come to Senses from Your Light, and six songs from Hide\'s Skydogs.\n\nThen we check out some new tracks from William Prince\'s Stand In the Joy, and from Noah McCuron\'s Point of Light. Then there\'s a Chicago-style blues group called Please Help. And finally, there is a song from Michael Brown\'s Getting Together. This song is about love, and it goes something like this: One thing I couldn\'t deny, need a love, need love to set free. Oh, oh, something is getting up, it\'s not being up. You can hear it on the program on CFRU-FM 93.3. We then hear',NULL,NULL),(62681,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Sound Magic - September 9, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-14 02:51:04',NULL,'The program begins with music by two composers who are prominent in German Romanticism. Paul Greiner, a Jewish composer, was a member of the German avant-garde who wrote a concerto for the Bush Quartet in the early 20th century. He was also a prominent composer during the period of the so-called \"Second World War\" when the Nazis occupied Germany. He wrote a piece for the Munich Philharmonic Orchestra in which he wrote a slow, fast, and rhythmically complex piece. The program ends with music from another prominent German composer, the late Boris Blachh, who lived from 1903 until 1975.\n\nBlachha did not go into \"ultra-modernism\" and lived a conservative life. He composed mostly unplayed works, including works for the orchestra. The overture to \"Hamlet\" on the program is from 1940, and it is a symphonic poem with the Symphony Radio Orchestra of Berlin conducting. The tone poem is from Hamlet, which, according to the program notes, is \"an orchestral tone poem\" .',NULL,NULL),(62682,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Sound Magic - September 9, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-14 02:29:40',NULL,'The program opens with a discussion of a composer named Max Rege who died in 1916. He was a prolific composer, but never quite got his symphony together. He also wrote some of his most difficult and difficult organ music. The program then moves on to a work by another composer named J.\n\nR. Weinberger who lived from 1896 until 1967. The program ends with an overview of the other composers on the program. The first is by a composer called Max Reger who was a very well-known organist. The second is by another well-loved composer, J. R. Weinberge. The third is a piece by another Vienna composer, Emil Biron. The group then moves to some other works by other Vienna composers, including a piece written by Ewen Linde.',NULL,NULL),(62683,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Mach Vibe Radio - September 9, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-14 01:10:26',NULL,'The show starts off by thanking everyone involved with the bike event. Then, the show moves on to a bit of music. It\'s a bit more about music and its effect on people. It starts off with a guy named Analogue, who\'s the brains behind the whole thing. He\'s also the guy who plays the drums. The guy is named Keon, and he\'s here to thank everybody for coming to the event. He also thanks everyone for supporting 93.3 FM as well. Then he gets to the heart of the matter.\n\nHe tells everyone to check out the Cfru.ca website and listen to all of their shows and stuff. Yeah, it\'s awesome. So thanks again, guys. Let\'s get started. Okay. We\'ve got some more music. This time it\'ll be a song called Ditch Ditch Ditch. The song is all about the power of the heart and mind to help us rise above these sad times. It ends with a little face-kissing. This is the first song Analogue has played in a long time. The first song is about Ditch Ditch, the power to rise above the pain.\n\nThe second song is a little bit about the Mandela Effect. The Mandela Effect is that no matter what happens in the future, people will always remember it. It doesn\'t matter what the script is, it can never be corrupted forever. Back to the main point',NULL,NULL),(62684,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Caribbean Anthology - September 9, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-14 00:49:07',NULL,'The Kidney Walk is a Canadian initiative to raise money to improve the lives of kidney patients. The event is being held in Guelph on October 1, and everyone is invited to join. The host of the program, Doug Blackwit, has been a part of the community for over 25 years. The program is a mix of old and new music, featuring interviews and news about the community. Each week, he presents great old radio shows from the 1930\'s to the 50\'s with music stories to match.\n\nThe show is now on Sundays at 2pm on the station. The narrator welcomes listeners to the program and introduces them to Tragedy Anne. They are going to perform at the Little Theatre on September 22nd at 7pm with Josh Gabriel, Harpist, and Upright Bass. Tickets are $25 and free for children under 12. For tickets go to TragedyAnne Music.com.',NULL,NULL),(62685,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Sound Magic - September 9, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-14 00:28:43',NULL,'The program opens with a three hour program of recorded classical concerts. The first concert is a German program, which consists largely of German or German-speaking works. The program begins with a symphony by a Vienna-born composer named Martin Scharber, who lived from 1907 until 1919. He is considered one of Vienna\'s great trained composers, and his first symphony was recorded in 1938. The second symphony is a work by another Vienna trained composer named Herbert Baskin, who was born in Vienna and studied at the Vienna School of Music. The third symphony is by another Austrian composer named Emil Beck, who is not well known.',NULL,NULL),(62686,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Caribbean Anthology - September 9, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-14 00:08:44',NULL,'In this edition of the Curriculumthology Show, the hosts discuss a new show that they\'re putting on today. It\'s called \"The House of Reggae 4\" and it\'s all about the music. The show is hosted by the guys from 93.3 FM and they\'ve got a special guest on the show named Tasha T, who\'s a long-time musician and singer.\n\nThe hosts also mention that they were able to get the post for the show because of a problem with the censors on CFRU. The guys have found a way to reword some of their content so that it can be heard on different platforms, like 93.3FM, the station, or on Roger\'s channel 948 . They\'re learning a lot about how to get their content out there.',NULL,NULL),(62688,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/08/Democracy Now - September 8, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-08 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-13 23:12:32',NULL,'The Democracy Now team discusses a number of recent developments in the world of sports, including a strike by players in Spain, the World Cup\'s Me Too moment in Spanish sports, decriminalization of abortion in Mexico, and the dire conditions in the Fulton County jail in Atlanta, where Trump and 18 of his co-conspirators are being held',NULL,NULL),(62689,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Beautiful Druid - September 9, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-13 22:49:24',NULL,'Beautiful Druid is a live music show that takes place at the university. It is hosted by Alden Hadwen, a Canadian singer songwriter. The show\'s theme is \"places that we long to visit.\" The first song in the program is by Ian Tyson and Sylvia, a duo of Canadian singer- songwriters.\n\nThe second song is by Kenny Chesney, from his album \"When the Sun goes Down.\" The third song is from Taj Mahal, a famous blues musician. The fourth is from Ian and Sylvia and is about a girl longing to visit the rodeos. The fifth song is about inviting someone to visit a place. Alden plays songs about longing for places. The first is from Katie Lang, from her album \"Shadowland.\n\n\" The second is from Harry Belafontes \"Essentials\" album. The third is from Sylvia and Ian, from their \"greatest hits\" album, \"Un Canadian Run.\" The fourth song is called \"Island in the Sun.\" The fifth is from Gordon Lightfoot, from \"Did She Mention my Name.\" The sixth song is a Canadian folk song called \"Uncanadian run.\" The seventh song is an English folk song about exile.',NULL,NULL),(62691,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/07/Democracy Now - September 7, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-07 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-13 22:31:31',NULL,'In this chapter, the State Department describes the humanitarian crisis that it has seen in the past eighteen months in Ukraine and in the Democratic republic of the Congo. The State Department says that in the last eighteen months, the humanitarian situation has \"deteriorated to an alarming degree. In addition, the situation in the eastern Congo has reached an alarming level.',NULL,NULL),(62693,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/08/Industry Tactics - September 8, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-08 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-13 22:07:55',NULL,'On this edition of Industry Tactics, Malvina, Ben, and Jeff discuss Disorientation Week, which is coming up at the University of G. The week will include screenings, workshops and other activities designed to engage students and community members in political, social and economic justice. OPRQ, the U. G. Graduate Coalition, and the Guelph Chamber of Commerce are all excited to participate in Disorientation week.\n\nThe three organization