Age.',NULL,NULL),(63971,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/zyc29q/Septembr_24_2023_Across_the_Universe7d3jk.mp3','2023-09-25 00:04:49',431961989,'2023-10-31 04:06:25',NULL,'The first hour of the program opens with a musical montage of the artists\' tracks. It begins with the song Christian by Blank and Jones and goes on to include the tracks of Mitch Roach, Emmethyce, Kia, Phil Diamond, Orgon, Bambino, Earth Tones and Pimienta, Buddy Miles, Arcadia, Them Changes the Butt Shaker\'s, Y. R. Y.S., Mr. Gunn, and Michael Simon.',NULL,'The first hour of the program begins with a musical montage of the artists\' tracks'),(63972,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/Wind-Down - September 24, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 06:52:18',NULL,'The show starts off with a remix of a song by the Japanese artist, Tiger Bomb. Then we hear the latest from Jungle, which comes from their latest album, Volcano.\n\nWe also hear a song from Senka, which is from their new album, Holding On. The show winds down with the Montreal group, Pouler, with their song Nouveau. We hear from No No Boy, who has developed this project for his Ph.D. at Brown University. He draws on years of field work and research on American and Asian American history, writing folk songs with bands that turn on to American music by American soldiers. He also draws on his family\'s own family history, which he left behind during the war in Vietnam. He has a 2021 album called 1975, which is described as a \"powerful and moving album\" by NPR. The group US Girls is another one of the show\'s favorite albums.\n\nThey have a song called Bless This Mess. They also have a new song from Julia Cunningham, \"Dive Deep,\" which was from her latest album. The artist Hannah Georges also has a song on her latest release, \"I\'d be lying if I said I didn\'t care with the song',NULL,NULL),(63973,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/Zombie Jamboree - September 24, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 06:31:52',NULL,'This is the first of a two-part interview with the host of the \"Zombie Jamboree,\" a weekly reanimmator of live music. The first part of the interview takes place on the 93.3 FM station, where the host and his guests dig through the latest releases to find the music they need for the evening.\n\nThe second part takes place at the \"green screen dream machine\" of the Olive Art studio at the College of the Free University of New York. The green-screen dream machine is a live-performance system that allows live performances to be recorded as well as re-watched. The program is available on the university\'s YouTube channel and on the CFRU.org web site.',NULL,NULL),(63974,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/Through the Looking Glass - September 24, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 06:12:42',NULL,'The band travels through the looking-glass and listens to music. Tonight they listen to Patrick Creepe\'s album, Bewitched, and then to Toitanian Ghosts, a collection of songs from the new album Lusitania Ghosts.\n\nThey also listen to a band named Howland Circus, which will be releasing an album called Creature. The band\'s first single is called Innocence, and the album\'s name is Creature. If you are interested in the song\'s playlist, it can be found on the lookingglass. The next band is called Sparkle Horse, and their name is Chaos. The track is from the upcoming Hayes album, Catch The Sky With Prediction. They have also been listening to a new single from Robbie Coyne called Bitter Sweet candy. They are also listening to Indifferent Monkey, who has released a new track called Sagittarius A.',NULL,NULL),(63975,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/Backtracks - September 24, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 05:52:35',NULL,'On this edition of Backtracks, host Jennifer and guest host Eileen discuss Labor Day, a holiday celebrated in many countries around the world. The day originated in Canada in 1872, when the Toronto Trades Assembly, the original trade union body, organized the countrys first significant worker\'s demonstration. The purpose of the demonstration was the release of a Toronto typographical union member who was imprisoned for striking to gain an eight-hour working day. The assembly spoke out on the behalf of workers and encouraged union organization.',NULL,NULL),(63978,171,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/b4i5ay/podbean_version88d05.mp3','2023-09-25 04:34:35',220669553,'2023-12-07 05:12:03',NULL,'It\'s the beginning of autumn, and we\'re introduced to the narrator, a young man named Brad Reed. He\'s about to start his day with a poem, but before he starts, he takes a moment to reflect on the past week.\n\nThe seasons have changed on Saturday, and now it\'s time for the fall season. He loves the fall, he\'s not into heat, and he\'d rather have a brisk autumn day than a hot summer day.\n\nHe takes a few moments to read a few poems by Carl Sandberg, Mark Doody, and others. The narrator picks one that he likes best, the one about the fall. He picks a poem by Doody called \"theory of beauty Pompeii,\" which is about a girl reading a book in a cafe line. He thinks the poem is beautiful, but he wishes it were written in a Gothic novel.',NULL,NULL),(63986,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 25, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 04:47:36',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(63987,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Here Today - September 25, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 04:34:32',NULL,'Aaron Badgley welcomes listeners to his show on CFRU\'s 93.3FM and the CFRU.com. He explains that he is hosting the show because he is a fan of music and he is always looking for new music.\n\nHe plays a lot of music from different artists, including James Clark Institute who have a new album coming out soon. Aaron also plays a new song from MeeLo, who is releasing his first album. He also plays some music from the new album by the Church of Trees who are also releasing their first album in the next few years. Aaron is also psyched to play a song by Deborah Fialco from her romantic English album. Also on the show is a new track from David Francie who is on tour with his new album. Aaron says he is glad to hear new music from David because he has been looking for a song from him.',NULL,NULL),(63988,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/This Night Wounds Time - September 25, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 04:17:43',NULL,'This week\'s program opens with the narrator talking about the new merchandise line at CFRU, and about the fact that the university is also a great resource for information on how to become a volunteer at the university. He also talks about a new program called \"This Night Wounds\" that he\'s going to play tonight on the university\'s public radio station, 93.\n\n3 FM, in Guelph, Ont. The program is all about music from the province of Corrientes, which is located in the southern part of Argentina. The music featured tonight is from the band Amboué, who have a song called \"Me paje\" and another called \"Rfpegde.\" The narrator notes that this song has a lot of mature subject-matter, and that it\'s not necessarily a celebration of political history.',NULL,NULL),(63989,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/This Night Wounds Time - September 25, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 03:10:05',NULL,'The show is now at the geographical part of the stage, and it is time for the spotlight section. It is the time when the show spotlights artists from various countries. The show starts off with the geographical spotlight of Russia, followed by Canada, China, and the United States. Next, the show goes on to Brazil, Australia, India, China and finally Argentina. The last country to be spotlighted is the smallest country on the scale, the Vatican City. The next smallest country is the Marshall Islands, which are tiny little islands in the middle of the Pacific Ocean.',NULL,NULL),(63990,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/This Night Wounds Time - September 24, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 02:48:25',NULL,'In this week\'s program, Christopher Curry discusses the philosophy behind This Night, Wounds Time, which is a live music show that usually runs for three hours. The show usually begins with music that is \"off the beaten track,\" which means that the music is not really in the center of the music world. The music on the show will be from around the world, and the program will shift after the first half of the show to focus on music from a specific region of the world.\n\nThis week, the focus will shift to the state of Argentina, so we\'ll start off with music from the University of California, San Francisco\'s \"new release collection.\" This is an amazing collection of music, and it\'s called \"Continuing.\" It\'s a collection of covers of jazz standards, which used to be very common in the jazz world back in the day.\n\nBut these days, with the rise of the \"new wave\" of avant-garde artists, there\'s no longer a need for artists to release \"albums of standards.\" Instead, they release albums of original compositions. This is the case with the new release by the \"Taishon Sori\" Trio. The trio consists of drummer/pianist/bassist/guitarist/vocalist/composer/arranger/etc., and they\'ve recorded a song by the late great Wayne Shorter. This song was actually recorded in December of last year before he died, but it worked out remarkably',NULL,NULL),(63996,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/8y483p/September_23rd_2023_Critic_s_Circle6l309.mp3','2023-09-25 14:41:32',143961989,'2023-12-07 02:30:39',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with Daniel Garber and Lynn Slotkin. The first part of the interview is about Daniel Garber going to the movies and the other part is about Lynn\'s play. The show is hosted by Phil Taylor, and it is a public radio show in Canada. The program features a variety of different guests, including Daniel at the movies, and Daniel reviews plays.\n\nThe other guests are Phil Conlon, a music critic and the founder of the Underground, and Lynn, a playgoer. They are all on the show now to discuss the latest news. The Underground has announced that the Waterloo Symphony Orchestra has gone out of business because of a lack of money.',NULL,NULL),(64001,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Breezy Breakfast Radio - September 25, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 02:12:17',NULL,'The chapter opens with a description of the city of Guelph, which is home to a number of First Nations communities. The city is hosting an open-mic with a crowd in the community. The purpose of the open mic is to hear people discuss issues that are important to them. They do not have Phil Ault to answer any questions, so they will be able to hear directly from the city. There is no direct answer to any questions that the crowd asks, so the group will try to answer them as quickly as possible.\n\nThe chapter ends with a conversation about the upcoming 200th anniversary of the first European settlement in the area. It is unclear whether any people from the community have approached the First Nations to organize a celebration, but no one has approached the Catholic Church or the government to invite King Charles to come to the area because of the last name of the First Nation.',NULL,NULL),(64002,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Volunteer Playlist - September 25, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-07 01:48:13',NULL,'This week on Democracy Now!, we learn that the Kidney Walk is a great opportunity to celebrate the strength of the kidney community.\n\nIt\'s also a great time to support the Comedy Festival, which is celebrating its 10th year. We also learn about the expanded Studio Tour and sale event that will take place on the weekend of October 14th and 15th. And finally, we hear that the Writers Guild has reached a new agreement with the Hollywood studios after 146 days of a strike. And then we hear about the Supreme Court Justice, Clarence Thomas, who is under new scrutiny after it was discovered that he participated in two right wing donor events organized by the Koch political network.',NULL,NULL),(64012,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Democracy Now - September 25, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 01:27:44',NULL,'This week, we continue our conversation with the author of the New York Times article \"The Rise of the Supreme Court as a Public Utility.\" The author discusses a number of recent Supreme Court cases, including a case called \"Chevron,\" which challenges the power of the federal government to regulate oil and gas development. The court\'s case in this case, however, is called \"Covenant.\" The court is considering adopting some kind of formal rules to govern political donations, but it\'s unclear whether they\'ll actually follow them.',NULL,NULL),(64013,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Worst Responders - September 25, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-07 01:10:40',NULL,'In this episode of Worst Responders, Host Jesse and Host Charissa discuss the importance of writing down a set before performing it. Jesse says that he has never written down his entire set before, so he has to break it down into smaller pieces to be more concise. He says he has a shorthand for the parts that he needs to remember, so that\'s how he writes down his notes. Host Jesse asks him if there\'s one skill that a comic needs to have to be good. He doesn\'t know, but he does know that a good comic should be able to be funny',NULL,NULL),(64023,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/CFRU Playlist - September 25, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-25 20:06:29',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64024,9234,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Art Not Shame Panel Discussion - September 25, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 00:55:39',NULL,'Art Not Shame hosts an event called \"Art In A Just Recovery: Unveiling\" on June 7th. This event includes a panel discussion and the introduction of the mural. The event is recorded by CFRU and is available on the organization\'s website.',NULL,NULL),(64034,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/qd6gxc/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Sept_27_2023_podcastb1fsp.mp3','2023-09-25 20:22:13',279886366,'2023-12-07 00:24:59',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64035,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - September 25, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 00:10:53',NULL,'In this chapter, the Guardian introduces his new role as guardian of the music scene. He will look at the diverse music scene from an \"inward and beyond\" perspective. He wants to pay respect to both the ancestral territories and local native communities. He also wants to acknowledge the contributions of the Black community, for their \"too often dismissed, uncredited, and/or ignored contributions to todays popular alternative.\" The first artist to be featured in this chapter is Daniel Field of Kilimeter Club, who will release his new album on September 29 th .',NULL,NULL),(64045,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/to know the land - September 25, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-30 17:22:02',NULL,'The University of Guelph\'s social media accounts have been blocked by the government\'s censorship bill, which makes it impossible for students to access their accounts on Facebook, Instagram, and Google. Students can still support the university by signing up for their newsletter, which will continue to include community updates. The University\'s public affairs manager, Byron, also addresses the censorship issue, telling listeners that the university will not be able to share its content on social media because of the bill. He encourages listeners to contact their Member of Parliament, Lloyd Longfield, to protest the censorship bill',NULL,'The University of Guelph’s social media accounts have been blocked by the government’s censorship bill'),(64046,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Big Sis Radio - September 25, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 23:08:58',NULL,'In this episode, Griffins introduces himself and his new show, Big Sis Radio. He explains that it\'s a community radio station that airs every Monday at 5pm on CFRU, 93.3 and at the University of G. He also explains that if you\'re a new student coming to the university this fall, he\'s happy to welcome you.\n\nGriffins also mentions that he wants to introduce you to the University\'s Native American community. The first song he\'ll play for you is a cover by Buffy St-Marie, who\'s known for her Anishinaabe art. Ombigazi recognized that she\'s an Anishaabe artist and wanted to wish Buffy well. The band also played a cover of Love God, Sarah Kinsley\'s song about God. The last song we\'ll hear is a song by the Beaches, called \"Edge of the Earth,\" which is about a breakup.\n\nLeandra Earl wrote the song. The narrator notes that this song might be good for letting your feelings flow after a breakup, especially if you feel like you\'ve been hanging out with someone too long. Finally, the narrator talks about the importance of beaver dams to the environment and how they make ecosystems more resilient during droughts. If you think that\'s not enough, remember that beaver dams are considered a \"Keystone Species\" because they\'re so important in the environment.',NULL,NULL),(64056,212,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/wp2xba/BFFull.mp3','2023-09-26 01:28:56',207450112,'2023-12-06 22:48:00',NULL,'In this program, Chris Durand introduces the North Carolinian band Ben Folds. Formed in the mid-90s, the band consists of Ben Fold on piano, vocals, and Robert Sledge and Darren Jesse. They performed what they called \"punk rock\" for \"sissys.\" They released three LPs before their breakup and reunited in early 2010 with a new album called \"The Sound of Life of Mind.\"',NULL,NULL),(64057,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Blues Around the Block - September 25, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 22:26:01',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64058,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Blues Around the Block - September 25, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 22:06:51',NULL,'The show opens with a live band, and they play a number of songs. The first song is by Dutch Mason, and the second is by Jim Burns, still stuck on you. The third is by Eddie Cleanhead, the fourth is by Susie Vinik and the fifth is by Bill Wharton. The food is Chicken Livers.',NULL,NULL),(64068,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/CFRU Playlist - September 26, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 06:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-26 14:06:18',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64069,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/The Deep House Project - September 25, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 21:48:00',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of the Sounds Like Old Times program, host Doug Blackwood discusses the fact that only 31% of Ontario residents have registered to donate their organ and tissue. If you\'re interested in becoming a donor, you can go to BeDonAor.ca and fill out an application.\n\nAnd if you\'d like to learn more about how to get involved with organ donation, check out the Canadian Association of Organ Sharing\'s website. The show is also a part of the 10-year-anniversary celebration of the Guelph comedy festival. There\'s also a show coming up called Clown Prov. It\'ll be hosted by Ken Hall, Isaac Kessler, and others. It will take place on October 21st at the Guelph Comedy Fest. You can register for the Clown-Prov at GuelphComedyFest.com. This week the Deep House project is broadcasting live from the university campus. They\'ve got a bunch of new and old tracks for you to listen to. They start off with Dabin and William Black\'s collaboration Black in the cold, which is perfect for the first weeks of autumn.\n\nThey also have some remixes from Kevin Glasgow and Martino\'s supernova. They are both GTA based DJs, and they\'re still in the game, but have recently been in the scene. They heard another remix from John Summit and another from The Rhythm, who is very well known as a DJ. Right now the Deep house project is listening to a Tronic track',NULL,NULL),(64070,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 26, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 21:26:21',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64071,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Back in the USSR - September 25, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 21:10:20',NULL,'Back in the Union on CFRU 92.3.3 FM. Seigfried gives an update on the recent BRICS meeting in South Africa. The BRICS is a grouping of fast-growing countries, including Russia, China, India and South Africa, that have banded together to create an alternative to the International Monetary Fund. The US and the European Union have recently placed unprecedented economic sanctions on Russia as a result of the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2022. This means that the economies of the BRICS member states are suffering from the effects of these Western sanctions.',NULL,NULL),(64072,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Ripcord Radio - September 25, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 20:48:41',NULL,'The show starts with a great mix of music from the Great Lakes and a few from overseas. The first band we\'ll hear is Mexican Power Authority, who came out of British Columbia in the early 1990s. They\'ve released a bunch of records, including some of the best punk rock of all time. They have a jazz band, a blind man band, an American band, and a French band. Next, we hear a bunch more music from overseas, including a Canadian band, two American bands, and one from France. The show ends with some more great music from Hamilton.',NULL,NULL),(64074,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Rainbow Country - September 26, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 20:29:40',NULL,'In this program, we hear about how the College of Film, Film, and Media at CFRU is looking for people to help with outreach at festivals, jazz festivals, and other community events. We also learn about the university\'s YouTube channel, where they post all of their live performances and interviews.\n\nThe host of the show, Mark Tara, is also on the show. He is a Canadian Olympian who is a leader of the Hillside Athletic Club. The show is hosted by Mark\'s friend and fellow athlete, the wrestler, Mark Tewsbury. The campus is home to the Film and Film Office, the College\'s campus community radio station, and the University\'s media center. The Film Office is looking to hire people to cover local events and to celebrate community. They also need volunteers to record public service announcements. If you\'re interested in joining them, they\'ll train you on how to use a microphone. The hosts of the Tales from the Bridges podcast, Sam and Marty, are also on this program. They\'re looking to recruit new science fiction and science fiction authors and directors to create their own science fiction.\n\nThe listeners can check out their show on CFRU. You can also check out the Tails from the Bridge website to find out more about their work. They are also looking for listeners to join their weekly show on YouTube, where you can watch all of the live performances on the Green-Screen Dream Machine. The police constable, Danielle Bot',NULL,NULL),(64075,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Rainbow Country - September 26, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 17:09:56',NULL,'This is the second part of a two part interview with the co-hosts of a new Canadian show called \"Rainbow Country.\" The first part is from Emily Saliers, a programmer from the Indigo Girls radio station in Toronto, and the second is from Carol Pope, author of \"Boy Erased,\" a memoir. They are joined by Lorraine Segato, a poet and musician, and Mark Tara, producer and host of the show. The show airs on 12 different Canadian stations, and can be found in syndication on many more.',NULL,NULL),(64085,296,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/5wz85s/utopia_review_filebhnhm.mp3','2023-09-26 15:58:35',85101366,'2023-12-06 16:47:53',NULL,'From the roots down CIUT 89.6 FM . From',NULL,NULL),(64086,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Solipsistic Retreat - September 26, 2023 at 10:19 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 10:19:00',1508,'2023-12-06 16:27:24',NULL,'This is the first half of the show, where the listeners are about to hear a song called \"Formless\" by Orgon. The narrator asks if this is a \"breathtaking exercise\" in female folk. Or is he a \"rascal for questioning\" the teacher? Or is it just a \"magic realism\" thing to do? The narrator then goes through a list of songs that he\'s listened to in the past five years.\n\nFirst, he goes through \"Olsen Twins Eternal Water,\" which was released in 2018. And then he goes over \"Sonic Use Sister\" which was first released in 1987. And finally, he talks about \"In A Moment Divine\" which is a song by a female vocalist named Cindy Lee. He feels like music is \"helping to corrupt youth of America\" .',NULL,NULL),(64087,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Solipsistic Retreat - September 26, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 16:07:19',NULL,'This is the second part of the \"formless\" section of the show. We find out that the voice of Oricogon is very interesting, and that everything in the world has a \"form aura\" . We\'ll get to that in a bit. But first, we have to listen to some of the music we\'ve heard on the program. First, we listen to the first two songs from the Quarry, which is where the Orcogon album was released. It\'s called \"Eternal Water Falling\" by the Olsen Twins and \"Sonic Use Sister\" by Kim Gordon. Next, we\'re listening to \"Freight Heak Waves\" and \"In A Moment Divine\" by Cindy Lee. And then we\'ll check in on our friend, the \"musicist\" who\'s been trying to corrupt American youth.',NULL,NULL),(64090,167,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/enjsff/September_22nd_2023_Funky_Fridaysarenp.mp3','2023-09-26 17:12:23',431961989,'2023-12-06 15:50:51',NULL,'The show starts off with a track from Norman Whitfield\'s 1975 album, Cosmic Truth, which was produced by the man himself. Next up is Milton Wright, who had been a successful musician in his own right. Next is Mel and Tim, who released a hit record in the early 60s with Backfield In Motion.\n\nThen they went to Stax and had a big hit with Making Love Is My Thing. Mr. Pete and the Funky Friday crew start off by playing some of their favorite tracks from the 70s and 80s. They include Arthur Lee Reeves who played blues and then switched to funk, Arthur Adams who played the blues but then switched over to jazz, and finally the band The Natural Yogurt Band who were married and played on the Gong Show.',NULL,NULL),(64093,175,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ytjn4r/September_21st_2023_No_Man_s_Land9j7qs.mp3','2023-09-26 17:09:32',287962512,'2023-12-06 15:06:14',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64094,178,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/pxpi9v/September_24th_2023_EqualizingXDistortb84ht.mp3','2023-09-26 16:47:03',287962512,'2023-12-06 14:53:29',NULL,'This is the second in a two part interview with Neon Andre, the host of the music show, \"Caut Equalizing to Store.\" In this interview, he discusses the history of his band, Neon Taste, which was the first label to release punk music. He also discusses his bandmates, including Josh Nickel, who is the vocalist in the band, \"Chain Whip,\" and the guitar player in \"Bootlicker.\" The second part of the interview will focus on Josh\'s time at \"Neon Taste,\" and he explains how the label came to be.',NULL,NULL),(64095,178,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/bdujru/September_17th_2023_EqualizingXDistortbad2k.mp3','2023-09-26 16:46:27',287962512,'2023-12-06 14:33:12',NULL,'This week on the program, the host of the community radio station, CIUT FM, is joined by his co-host, Chris Heffernan, who is also a member of the punk band, Equalizing XDistort. The program begins with a song called \"I\'m Angry,\" which is from the 1978 recording of Richard Helen, the Voidoids . The show will also include a live performance by the band, and a feature on the guitarist, Ivan Julien, who played in the band. He also introduces the guest, a musician, producer, and style innovator who will be playing a show in Toronto on September 22 and 23.',NULL,NULL),(64096,178,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/t64cjc/September_10th_2023_EqualizingXDistortaqkig.mp3','2023-09-26 16:45:32',287962512,'2023-12-06 14:12:54',NULL,'EqualizingXtort is a new music show from Counterpoint. They have a lot of music on the show, including a bunch of new releases and some classics like One Way System, Subhumans, and the polls. They also have an interview with the lead singer of the polls, Michael Jordana. The show also has some new releases like Psychwar and Fake Armored Tashme FM.\n\nThe band Front Eyes from Edmonton is also in the mix. They\'re also going to have a band called The Chats, which is a punk band from Toronto. Next up on the program is the interview with Michael. He\'s the guy who wrote the song, \"Primetime,\" which is also on the single. The interview is a bit of an odyssey. It\'s a bit about the idea of starting a band, and it\'s kind of like a letter to the creator of the band. It seems like the artist is well known for his art. He says he was involved in many different kinds of art, and that he started the band because of that.\n\nHe also says he came back from the Arctic with the idea that the polls would start up. The idea of the poll was very moving. We learn that the first time the polls played was at the New York City club A-Space in 1977. The interview ends with a discussion about the early days of the punk scene.',NULL,NULL),(64097,178,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/d397ja/September_3rd_2023_EqualizingXDistortb2buh.mp3','2023-09-26 16:44:01',287962512,'2023-12-06 13:51:28',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the music on the air. It\'s all about loud music that you can listen to when you are angry.\n\nThe music starts with a song called Gizm by a band called Endless Blockade For The PussyFooter. The song is about a guy named Sukevi who was a member of the band. The band is going to do some music reviews and a profile on a label called Efira Records from Connecticut. The first track in the set is a new release by Chain Whip called \"Call of the Knife. The second track is a teaser for their upcoming Neon Punk LP on Taste. The third track is by two balloys. The fourth track is called Jubilee. The fifth track is from another band called Katarsi.\n\nThe sixth track is another synth punk called \"Ezzod Lagoon. The seventh track is an amazing track from a band named Flash. The last track is \"Desarmonle\" by a French band called Camellia Sinensis, who released a demo in 2023. This is their first C-a-t equalized distro, which is basically a music store with all the music and lyrics from all the different music stores in one place',NULL,NULL),(64101,186,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/pya5xi/September_21st_2023_Higher_Ground8u80h.mp3','2023-09-26 17:10:20',287962512,'2023-12-06 13:08:41',NULL,'The program opens with a tribute to Matthew Halsted, who has recently released a new album titled \"Afro Train Volume 2: Song of the Forefathers.\" It is the first release from the new Nat Virtual Afro Train, a series of Afro-Cuban instrumentals. The program ends with a shout-out to the University of South Florida\'s Afro-Latino Day, which is taking place in Detroit in the next few weeks. The show closes with a mix of new music from Lorenzo Horic and La Esso.',NULL,NULL),(64104,191,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/3nh36s/September_23rd_2023_Frisson_Radio8xg1j.mp3','2023-09-26 17:32:48',287962512,'2023-12-06 12:46:53',NULL,'This is a trip into sound! A journey which will bring you a new color, new dimension and new values. Welcome to Frison Radio! The show is hosted by Nabeel Pervadiz and it\'s all about music. He\'s got some great tracks to choose from, so check it out. The first track is by Diddy, who has teamed up with Justin Bieber. Sounds great.',NULL,NULL),(64105,191,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/88bp4u/September_9th_2023_Frisson_Radiobni71.mp3','2023-09-26 17:31:58',287962512,'2023-12-06 12:28:20',NULL,'This is the first time that we\'ve heard the name \"Nabeel\" on the program, which means \"Host\" in Arabic. The first hour is all about music. We\'ll hear some new music from some of the hottest artists in the city, including Charlotte Cardin , Govee , Safe , Jock Green , and more. And this isn\'t just any music. This is a music show, and we\'re talking the best of Canadian music. So, yeah, this is the best music you\'ve ever heard. And it\'s from the hottest music scene in the world: the world of Canadian artists.\n\nIt starts off with a new song by Amalou, who\'s just released her new album, \"I Came Home Late\" . Next, there\'s a new track from another Canadian singer, Tay Iwar , who just came out with her debut album. And finally, there is a new single from a new artist named Kiebra, who was playing in a festival in the park last weekend.',NULL,NULL),(64106,191,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/zaj4c6/September_2nd_2023_Frisson_Radio9crfe.mp3','2023-09-26 17:27:00',287962512,'2023-12-06 12:10:26',NULL,'In this episode, the guys at CIUT FM thank everyone who gave during their fall campaign. If you didn\'t donate yet, they still need your support to reach their goal of $100K.\n\nCheck it out: CIUTFM.org/donate. The guys at Frisson Radio bring you a new music show this week called \"One-Word: Love.\" It\'s all about love and music. In the first hour, we hear some of the best new music from the city, including a new track from Taku and his partner in crime, Panama. The two of them are back with another new song from their new project, \"Songs to Come Home.\" The new song is also produced by Taku.',NULL,NULL),(64107,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/wup8pv/Karibuni_Show_September_24_20235yj1r.mp3','2023-09-26 17:19:31',287962512,'2023-12-06 11:50:50',NULL,'The show starts off with a thank you note from CIUT FM for all the financial support they\'ve received. They still need to raise more money to reach their goal of $100,000, so they invite listeners to give them a little extra cash. The program continues with a song from Africa by one of the station\'s favorite artists, Papawimba, and then they head over to hear some more music from other artists from West and Central Africa. The first song is from a group called Benin International Music, and the second is from Eddie Kanfro. The third song is also from Benin International, and this is by the late Papawamba.',NULL,NULL),(64108,206,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/wq5wgw/September_23rd_2023_The_Minx_Sessions7m7eg.mp3','2023-09-26 16:58:20',287962512,'2023-12-06 11:26:40',NULL,'The Minx Sessions is a weekly independent music show hosted by Binny. In this program, Binny takes listeners on an eclectic journey through the world of independent music. Throughout the program, he describes the music that he will be playing, including new releases from various artists, remixes, and mixes. He also gives a shout-out to the various artists that have appeared on the show, and he encourages listeners to follow his social media accounts.',NULL,NULL),(64109,247,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/u5r5i8/September_23rd_2023_Calling_All_Bluesbtuyj.mp3','2023-09-26 16:55:02',143961989,'2023-12-06 11:07:39',NULL,'The Calling All Blues Show begins with the announcement that the show will be playing blues music by Bob Dylan. The show will also include some of Dylan\'s classic songs, along with some of his greatest hits. The first song is \"Bringing it all back\" from his album \"Bring It All Back.\n\n\" The second song is Bullcalf Blues from Paul James\'s Lost in the blues album. The third song is from Dylans \"Highway 61 Revisited.\" The fourth song is Bo Diddley\'s \"Bring it to Jerome.\" The fifth song is the \"Subterranean homesick blues\" from the album \"Homesick Blues.\" The sixth song is Blind Willie Mctell\'s blues from his \"Buleseries Tombstone Volumes 1-3.\" The seventh song is Howlin\' wolf\'s version of \"I Ain\'t superstitious.\" The eighth song is Bob Dylans dirt road blues. The ninth song is a blues song by the legendary singer Lonnie Johnson. The song is called \"Tomorrow night by Lonnie Johnson/Muddy Waters I just want to make love to you.\" The show closes with a song by Dylan himself, \"My wife\'s hometown.\"',NULL,NULL),(64110,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Bridging The Social Distance - September 26, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 10:47:15',NULL,'The narrator\'s name is Fei Mei, which means \"I was born in the land of the rising sun\" . The narrator tells us that he and his family moved to Shanghai when he was a baby, and that his father was a journalist. He was born during the war, and his mother and father returned to America. The war ended, and the family moved back to North Dakota, where they lived with their grandparents and their grandfather was a Lutheran minister. The family lived there for a while, and then moved to Northwood, where the narrator and his father went to work.',NULL,NULL),(64111,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Democracy Now - September 26, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 10:29:55',NULL,'A deadly explosion at a fuel depot in the disputed South Caucasus territory has killed at least 20 people and wounded nearly 300 others. Thousands of Armenians have fled to neighboring Armenia. On Monday representatives of the region\'s ethnic Armenians held another round of talks with Azerbaijani officials, but no details were made public about the meeting. Azerbaijan\'s President, Elam al-Aleyev, has pledged his government will ensure the safety of everyone in the region.',NULL,NULL),(64121,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - September 26, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 10:08:24',NULL,'This is the third hour of Power Up!, and it\'s all about the death of Dubay. He was 43 years old when he died in a hijacking attempt.\n\nBefore that, the show heard songs from Spring, Lucky Dubay\'s son, and The Delays. The band formed in 2001, but they never made much of a name for themselves in Canada. Twelve years have passed since the band played their first show, and they\'ve had a singer named Greg Gilbert diagnosed with stage four bowel cancer. He passed away on September 30, 2011 at age 44. So, this is all about Greg Gilbert, who was the lead singer of the band.\n\nNow we\'re back to Canadian music, this time with Rock Voisin. He\'s a singer-songwriter who\'s been recorded in both French and English. He has a huge following in Quebec and has lots of success in Europe. In this set, we hear songs from Wild Strawberries, a band that formed in 1988, and from the Super Jesus. The Super Jesus were an Australian band that disbanded in 1994 and reformed in 2013. They\'re called Dream Spirit. The song they just heard is called Shut my Eyes.',NULL,NULL),(64122,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Under the Needle - September 26, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 09:51:13',NULL,'On this episode of Live on K.EXP, the CFRU co-host, Renee, chats with the comedians from the Do-It-Yourself Comedy Tour. The tour is coming to Marathon, Wawa and other places in the north for the next few nights. So, why don\'t you send a message to all of your friends in the area to catch this comedy train.\n\nThe comedians are in town, but Scott Porchess couldn\'t join them. The show ends with a Q&A with Frank Russo and Mike Payne. Frank and Mike talk about how the tour is doing, and how it\'s going. They talk about the beautiful nature of the area they\'re in.',NULL,NULL),(64127,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/8mvf9n/DrMouth_CIUTshow_sept26_2023_fullshow.mp3','2023-09-26 20:42:45',288726848,'2023-12-06 09:32:49',NULL,'Dr. Mouse returns to the program with a new song, this time called \"The End of Man.\" The song is a tribute to Porcupine tree, one of Brown\'s favorite bands. The song was originally released in the early 90s and is one of his favorites. The other songs include \"Up to Down Stair,\" \"The Sky Moves Sideway,\" \"Porcupine Tree,\" and \"The Delirium Years,\" a compilation of early Porcupines. He also shares a few of his favorite albums, including \"Stars Die,\" which was released in 1997.',NULL,NULL),(64133,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Silver Screen Dream Machine - September 26, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 09:11:00',NULL,'This week on Silver Dream Machine, we hear music from three different films: Doctor Strange, the sequel to the Marvel Cinematic Universe; the 1994 video Need for Speed; and the 2018 Marvel Cinematic universe feature, Doctor Strange. We also hear from a Canadian animated short film, Caterpillar Plasti. The music is from a song by David Usher, a lead singer in the Canadian rock band, Moist. The song was inspired by a binge on Tarantino films. The songs from the films also inspire us to sing.',NULL,NULL),(64134,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/A Multilingual Affair - September 26, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 08:52:38',NULL,'The song opens with the Latin pop star, Stasis, singing \"Merveyous,\" a song about love and passion. He tells us that he\'s just come from a long journey to the university and that it was a beautiful day. He describes his journey as \"the perfect detour\" and says that he just went with \"the flow\" . He\'s also joined by his friend, the artist, T\'Chase. They\'re all going to be on the road together, so it\'ll be fun. We\'ll hear more about that later.',NULL,NULL),(64144,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Tuesday at 5 - September 26, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 08:26:23',NULL,'Mac Dee starts off another edition of his show, this time on CFRU 93.3. He\'s got a bunch of songs to choose from. He starts off with a collection of songs from the Edgar Winter group and then he goes through some of his own songs. There\'s a song by George Cooper called \"The Wind and the leaves\" and another by Ian Tyson called \"Summer is Gone and The Sharecroppers\" . Then there\'s some new stuff from Bonnie Dune, Rodney Crowell, and David Wilcox. Mac Dee is doing the show all around the Guelph area.',NULL,NULL),(64145,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Down the Rabbit Hole - September 26, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 08:04:38',NULL,'We\'re always looking for people to help us out with our media projects. For example, if you\'re interested in music production, we\'d love to hire you as a music editor. Or if you just want to help out with live events or public service announcements or whatever else we\'re doing, we might need you as an engineering guy.',NULL,NULL),(64155,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Let’s Get Lost - September 26, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 07:07:41',NULL,'Scott opens the program by introducing us to the host of the program, Scott. He\'s a regular on the program and we\'re always on the lookout for new music releases.\n\nThis week, the program is looking back at some of the artists that have been part of the music scene in the area. We start out with the Glint album by Nick Frazier, who played drums. The band is composed of Eric Chenot, Douglas T. Heller, Brody West, Rob Clutton, and all the people that have played in other bands and in other projects. They\'ve all played in Drum Heller, which is a band that Scott used to play in. They hear the track Knifex 63 from Drum Heller and it\'s about seven years since it came out. Ken Oldcroft, a friend of Scott\'s who played guitar in the Ken Old Croft Convergence Ensemble, passed away recently.\n\nScott was able to host Ken on this program several times, and enjoyed every time he played live. The program is going to hear music from the Tangent section of the album by Wes Neal. The Tangent section is comprised of Wes, Big Time, Felter, and a guy named Gord Gurdina who is also from Vancouver. The group is also comprised of Mark Halias, Jerry, and Gurdina. The album is called Recoder, and it features the guys from the Convergence Ensemble. They also have a track from Joe Sorberas album My Misshape And Ear.',NULL,NULL),(64156,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/New or Never - September 26, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 06:46:18',NULL,'The show starts off with a bang as the host, Adrian Hodritik, introduces eleven new tracks. The first is Thirson\'s music, which he describes as a mixture of studio recordings, film soundtracks, and collaborations.\n\nThe band he\'s playing with is called the Chanters, and it\'s based in Vancouver, British Columbia. They\'ve got a new label called Slash Off, and they\'ve just released their second album. The other tracks on the show are by Montauban , Matthew Halsand , As Japans Girls , Patrick Creif , Low Cut Connie , and Run With the Kittens . The show ends with the newest release by Run With The Kittens.',NULL,NULL),(64166,217,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/yaykfe/CIUTSept26.mp3','2023-09-27 03:46:23',143961989,'2023-12-06 06:25:50',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64167,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Let’s Get Lost - September 26, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 05:06:15',NULL,'This week\'s program is called \"Let\'s get lost\" and it\'s from the \"Thunderbird Plays Long\" album by the Zubat brothers. The program ends with a track from Colin Fisher\'s album \"Reflections of the invisible world.\" The program also includes a link to the archives of the university\'s website, where listeners can find old episodes of the program.\n\nAlan also introduces a new line of clothing from the university. The university also has a partnership with Ed Video, a Guelph-based company that offers training in video production. If you\'re interested in learning more about the company, check out their website.',NULL,NULL),(64168,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Humanoid Radio - September 26, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 04:46:20',NULL,'The first part of the Humanoid Radio show begins with a track by the Malleus Trio, titled On Off. The second half of the show starts with tracks from Mauricio Polley, Eve Egoian, Jayzone, Ninoar, Eyal Robb, Afex Twin, Black Dog, and Ford. They continue with a signal from outer space that is believed to be an alien signal. Since they first tried to communicate with them by radio, they have developed a language that can be used by humans. The show ends with the Nick Quartet\'s track, Dolphin Dance.',NULL,NULL),(64178,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - September 26, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 04:25:16',NULL,'This is the third and final episode of the \"I, the Cyber-Lich,\" a new music program from Guelph, Ontario. It\'s an hour-long, hour-and-a-half-long live show from the underground punk band. The show starts with a description of the music, which consists of four tracks from Magna Vault\'s new album, Stellar Gun.\n\nThe first track is \"Shell Stellar Gun,\" followed by \"5 AM,\" \"Deckhead,\" and \"Bullet Hell or Bullet.\" The second track is called \"I Am The Night,\" and it\'s a dark, dark, scary track. The third track is a \"classic perturbator,\" which is a joke about the fact that \"I am the night.\" The fourth track is the last track of the show, and it will be all you can hear from the band until next week.',NULL,NULL),(64179,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/Radia - September 27, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 04:03:50',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64217,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 27, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 03:06:44',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64218,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/CFRU Playlist - September 27, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-27 14:06:27',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64220,159,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/g3rj36/CAREER_-_CareerBuzzCIUTfinalseptember2720236tj5u.mp3','2023-09-27 15:30:00',86370275,'2023-12-06 02:50:22',NULL,'In this episode, Maria shares her story of how she got into non-profit management. She started out as a sales associate in an art gallery and then went on to open her own art-consulting business.\n\nAfter discovering that she loved helping others, she made a career shift to helping non-profits raise money. Her first job was as the giving manager at a non-for-profit called the Children\'s Hospital. She then moved on to the assistant director position at a domestic violence shelter called the Reach Beyond Violence. Her last job was the director of development for the local chapter of the Domestic Violence Resource Center.',NULL,NULL),(64222,174,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/umvti9/September_27_2023_Global_Rhythmsbtnlg.mp3','2023-09-27 14:54:42',431961989,'2023-12-06 02:29:49',NULL,'The first hour of Ken Stowar\'s program is dedicated to the theme of \"Global Rhythms.\" Ken tells us that he\'s here to tell us about the music of the future. Every day, he hears his people fail. He hopes that someday, he\'ll be able to hear them all fail.',NULL,NULL),(64230,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/The Stillness & The Dancing - September 27, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 02:10:24',NULL,'The show starts off with a bunch of new music from Lost Tribe Sound, Glassbird, Skyphone, Tape Loop Orchestra, and more. Then we hear a little bit of music from Prairie Lines. This is one of his all-time favorites White Lab Recordings releases. The show is an eight-year anniversary show, and the show is all about music. He doesn\'t have the time to celebrate, but he does enjoy the music.\n\nThe tracks on the show are all from White Lab recordings. The album Eyes Down, Seaside Down is a favorite. The track Calm Landing is from another White Lab release, one of Caleb R. K. Williams\'s. Finally, there\'s a track from Eagle Stone Collective called Hindons. It seems like the band has been releasing a lot of music lately. The band has put out an insane amount of releases, but each one seems to have a different vibe.\n\nSo much good music in there. He hopes in some way he\'s been part of it. He\'s also got a little miniature of Lo-fi Melancholy on a track called Sweet Love that he put on tape. He hasn\'t heard from it in a while.',NULL,'Keep Hope Alive Music Festival takes place in Guelph from September 28 to October 1st'),(64231,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/The Stillness & The Dancing - September 27, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 01:07:00',NULL,'This is a very long and very emotional show, and the narrator is very weary. He tells us that he\'s doing a lot of traveling and is trying to wrap up all of his inner life.\n\nHe says he\'ll start off this show with a bunch of the music he heard from the show, which he calls a \"bunch of music\" that he has loved since he first heard it eight years ago. The first track is Sonori Halgramen\'s \"Weary, don\'t let Me rest\" , followed by \"Blessed are the hearts that bend called Sadness be damned\" . Then it\'s Glaceus and Adrian Lane with \"Distances,\" \"The Flower to the mind\" ; and \"Illumina\" with \"It\'s all right.\" The last track is from Veliska with \"Of Water.\" The narrator says that he played this one on one of his first shows, but that\'s not possible. Then there\'s Sarah Paje\'s release, \"Dose curves.\" The show ends with some piano music from an artist called \"Number one dados,\" who has been playing mostly instrumental piano pieces.',NULL,'Joel Cuthbert is diagnosed with a fairly rare form of cancer'),(64241,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - September 27, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 00:57:10',NULL,'The students talk about avocados and how they\'re so good without the salt. They say they taste like soap without any salt, and they just taste like raw dog avocados with no salt. What if they feel that taste is somehow related to manipulation practices? Well, we\'re back to the discussion of avocados. The students say they still are cool, because they are so relevant to the country where they live. They even say that they don\'t like avocados because they taste so bad. They recommend going to the market to buy them.',NULL,NULL),(64242,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/Democracy Now - September 27, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 23:10:11',NULL,'Amy Goodman opens the program by saying, \"It\'s democracy now! stick with it. Because you deserve a significant raise and other benefits.\" She then launches into a long speech about the importance of workers getting a raise. She then tells us that President Trump will arrive in Detroit today to visit an auto parts factory.\n\nThen she launches into the latest on a strike by autoworkers. She tells us about the president\'s visit to the border with Mexico and the mayor of El Paso\'s lack of resources to deal with the influx of immigrant workers. Finally, Amy tells us the government\'s lawsuit against Amazon, and the growing call for New Jersey\'s Senator Bob Menendez\'s resignation.',NULL,NULL),(64262,195,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ierf8p/Dementia13Radio_23_09_26.mp3','2023-09-27 20:40:32',287962512,'2023-12-05 22:27:46',NULL,'The narrator opens the show by saying that he\'s happy to be at the show, which is called Dementia 13. He thinks it\'s the most beautiful time of the year and that it brings with it its own stirred-up feelings.\n\nHe also says that he feels like the show will reflect on a lot of music in the first hour. He adds that there is one local business that he wants to talk about tonight, so he\'ll be giving away a brass pipe to one lucky winner. The winner will have to follow the club on Instagram to win the pipe. The narrator also talks about the passing of Terry Kirkman, the singer of Mary and Windy, a band that he likes very much. He says that when he was growing up in California, there was something very special about the music that Terry played. The song that he starts the program with is from the association, which he says was kind of a \"sunny, shimmery, kind of memory\" that he hopes will never be forgotten',NULL,NULL),(64263,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/End Credits - September 27, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 22:11:58',NULL,'This is the first episode of the new web series \"End Credits\" hosted by Adam Donaldson. It\'ll be a comedy show about local movies. It starts off by asking Tim Phillips, who\'s a regular host of the show, about the many people he knocked out during homecoming weekend.\n\nAdam says it\'s cool that he got some laughs out of it, but he\'s not sure about the whole \"internet comedy\" thing. After all, he says, his own \"computer was malfunctioning\" . Tim says he\'ll do a show called \"Zoom\" , which will be a kind of local version of \"Netflix for movies\" ; that\'s right, they\'re going to stream a lot of the latest movies. The first half of this show will be \"El Conde,\" a',NULL,NULL),(64264,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - September 27, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 21:12:59',NULL,'The show starts off with a couple of songs. The first song is a song called \"Again and Another Pool\" from the band\'s first album Troubles. The second song is \"The Hand That Fits The Glove\" from their upcoming album The Hand that Fits the Glove coming out October 13.\n\nThe Griffins beat York 8-7 in a \"very one-sided\" game. Prison was named the \"only wave player\" of the week and the Griffins will be taking on the Warriors on Saturday. The three Griffin sports are ranked naturally and Sabrina Spano and Kobe Smith are the \"greatest locker\" of this week. Back to the program. The show then turns to another song, this time from the vinyl archives, called \"Gone Away from the  offspring.\n\n\" The listeners did not expect to hear the song coming out of the show, but Taylor went through the vinyl library to find the song. He found the song and played it. The song is cool and the show takes it away with a variety of games. The Grel Storm opened the season on Friday against the \"OSR attack\" and they have season tickets for this year.',NULL,NULL),(64283,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/B Siide Radio - September 27, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 20:45:14',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64284,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/Trail Mix - September 27, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 20:25:38',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64285,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/11/23/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - November 23, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-11-23 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 20:04:55',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64286,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/11/16/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - November 16, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-11-16 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 19:08:34',NULL,'This is a short program about the wealth film festival. It\'s hosted by a guy named Maheen. He\'s a fan of the festival and he\'s been listening to it on the CFRU 98.\n\n3 FM station. We find out a lot about him and his show. Mac D is the guy who runs the show. He talks about how he started out as a student at the university and how he now runs his own show. This is just the beginning of his involvement with the university. He introduces himself as Mac D and tells us a little about himself. He describes himself as a \"long-time\" student at CFRU and has been hanging around the university for a long time. He started off working on the equipment and then moved on to doing his own shows. He also tells us that he has learned a lot from the university about local music and artists and that he\'d never heard of them before.\n\nIf you\'re looking for something to do at the school, check out Mac D\'s show. We also learn that the university is hosting the wealth festival this year. This year, the festival will be a little different from the previous year. It will be presented in October. There will be all kinds of festival passes available starting at $35. You can purchase passes to all of the films in the festival. There\'ll also be live streaming events and panel discussions. We\'ll tell you more about the festival in a second. The wealth',NULL,NULL),(64287,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/11/09/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - November 9, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-11-09 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 17:05:07',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64288,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/11/02/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - November 2, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-11-02 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 16:45:59',NULL,'The narrator introduces the listeners to a new program from the War Against the Machine. It\'s called \"Play Safe,\" and it\'s all about kids and accidents. The narrator says that accidents can happen anywhere, and the program helps kids to play safely. He also introduces listeners to his own program, called \"Beautiful Druid,\" which is a Sunday morning talk show at the University of the Guelph.\n\nHe says he hopes listeners will tune in and listen to his program, which is about saving lives. According to the Canadian Medical Association, one person dies every three days in the province because of a lack of an available organ. If people were willing to donate their body parts, there would be as many as 8 people who would be saved. If you\'re interested in becoming a donor, you should go to the BeAdonor.ca website and sign up for the donor list.',NULL,NULL),(64289,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/10/26/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - October 26, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-10-26 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 16:27:01',NULL,'In this song, the Underground Railroad\'s founder explains that he is grateful for everything he has been given, and that he believes that he will be able to make a better life for himself and his family. He believes that the 13th Amendment to the Constitution of the United States of America, passed in 1865, abolishes slavery. He also believes that there is no reason for people to associate with people who have committed crimes against them. He argues that the things that were made illegal by the government are things that Black people associate with them.',NULL,NULL),(64290,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/10/19/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - October 19, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-10-19 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 16:08:13',NULL,'This week\'s program is from the War Amplifiers, a program that helps kids to play safely after accidents. This is an important program, because it helps people learn about the dangers of boating accidents. It\'s also a great way for kids to learn about other kinds of accidents, like drowning, and how they can save lives.\n\nThe program also has a new program called Clan of Gale, which is a Celtic music show on the FM. It also hosts John Fahey, who plays the bagpipe on the show. The Gryphon Tool Library is also a part of the program, offering a wide variety of tools and services to the community. They also have a new podcast, The Crows Nest: An Earbuds Human Library, which focuses on the importance of human contact in community outreach.',NULL,NULL),(64291,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/10/12/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - October 12, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-10-12 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 15:45:59',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64292,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/10/05/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - October 5, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-10-05 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 15:06:22',NULL,'The next time you\'re on the road, you might want to check out CFRU.com, a great little community radio station in Guelph. The station is owned and operated by a bunch of awesome people, and it airs a lot of great music from all over the world.\n\nIt\'s also got a great live streaming service, which is great because you can listen to it right from your phone. It also has a ton of other cool features like a weekly program guide and music charts, as well as a second stream of music that\'s exclusive to local music. You can also donate to the station if you want.',NULL,NULL),(64293,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/09/28/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - September 28, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-09-28 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 14:50:26',NULL,'The host and his gang discuss the violence and destructive power of the guillotine and how one can destroy it without losing his sanity. This is the host\'s weekly show on CFRU\'s 93.3 FM, which airs Thursday nights after the PDC. This program is all about the violent outbursts and the violent urges to destroy things inside. It\'s all about being able to destroy the things you\'re not able to physically destroy.\n\nThe program also includes a description of the Guelph Tool Library, which is a great resource for people wanting to learn how to use a tool. They\'ve also added a new podcast called The Crows Nest, which features people from the community sharing their experiences and tips.',NULL,NULL),(64294,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/09/21/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - September 21, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-09-21 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 14:31:29',NULL,'The next morning, Josh and Sarah chat about the events of the day. Josh says that they had fun making and witnessing dances. Sarah says that he did a lot of the cooking and cleaning up after the dances. Josh tells Sarah that he had a very hard day at the gym. Sarah is impressed that Josh is a hard worker. Josh goes on to say that his day was filled with ideas and that he was able to do a lot. Sarah asks Josh what his duties are and he tells her that he does the cooking, the cleaning, and the dancing',NULL,NULL),(64295,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/09/14/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - September 14, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-09-14 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 14:14:30',NULL,'This episode is all about Josh and his friends at the Community of Hearts Learning Center. The program is a bit of a jamboree, with a lot of questions and answers about what\'s going on at the school and what they\'re up to.\n\nJosh is super chatty, and he\'s super excited to be hanging out with his family. He even has some fun playing with his brother and his dog. They\'ve been doing a Harry Potter book together, and they\'ve also been doing Harry Potter-related tasks. Josh\'s a little excited to tell us that he\'ll be going to the theater to play a concert.',NULL,NULL),(64296,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/09/07/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - September 7, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-09-07 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 13:47:17',NULL,'This week\'s guest on the Blenders Public show is a man named Jean. He\'s a self-made millionaire who works for a charity called the Community of Hearts. He listens to community radio every day. This week, he listens to a show called \"Community of Hearts\" with Josh, Duncan, and Amanda.\n\nThe first segment of the show is devoted to a song called \"Noya\" by Shania Twain. Josh and Duncan talk about the singer, who is well-known for her big voice. Duncan says he likes her music, too, and that he likes Shania\'s concerts. Josh asks Duncan what he likes to do while he\'s at home. Duncan likes puzzles, reading, and movies. Josh likes to play with animals, like snakes.',NULL,NULL),(64297,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/08/31/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - August 31, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-08-31 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 13:28:02',NULL,'This week on the CFRU 93.1 FM community radio show, the Host and Host\'s friends Duncan and Josh discuss their favorite songs, the music they listen to, and all the other things they do. The Host goes back to the Community of Hearts to talk to Josh, who is planning to go to a movie tonight. He also asks if he can stay home on Sunday because his brother is going to be bad. Josh says he can\'t because he\'s going to watch a movie.',NULL,NULL),(64298,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/08/24/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - August 24, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-08-24 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 13:14:53',NULL,'The Merry Mask Makers is a project started by the Guelph tool library to create free masks for people in need. Since the project began, over 1,100 masks have been made and 1,000 have been redistributed. If you would like to help, please contact the tool library at garduel.\n\ntoollibrary@gmail.com. The narrator welcomes listeners to the Community of Hearts Learning Center, which is located downtown. The program begins with an introduction to the listeners, and then the program moves to the recording studio. The listeners are greeted by the narrator, who introduces the listeners to a group of adults who are learning together. The adults are Duncan and Amanda, who are parents of two children. Duncan\'s children are in school, and they are in grades 3 and 6.\n\nTheir school is in Smithville, so they will probably not be there today. They will probably have to go to the school in Fergus, which will be a long drive. Duncan tells the listeners about his trip to Toronto. He was stuck in traffic jam, so he had to play music to get out of the jam. He then went to Wakefield and stayed at a house that was \"full of art\" .',NULL,NULL),(64299,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/08/17/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - August 17, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-08-17 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 12:51:45',NULL,'The Mobile Community Show starts over at the Community of Hearts. Sarah asks Josh how his day went. Josh says it was a good one. He went to the gym and played with his friends. Sarah tells him that her mom is going to go out with her friends tonight and then her dad is going out with Sarah and her dad tonight.\n\nSarah says that she is having fun with her uncle and aunt and that she saw a play called \"The Harmony\" and saw a movie called \"Hard Hard the Wild\". Sarah says she hopes spring comes soon. She says that the clocks spring forward so that she gets an extra hour of sleep but she loses an hour of it.\n\nShe does not know if her baby is having any fun. Josh asks if he can tell him about the Storm game after the play. He says he will when he comes to the day program the next Friday. Sarah comments that her day at the center was good. She also likes making the icing for the morning program and making the gingerbread for the afternoon program. Josh also says that he enjoyed making the cake for lunch. Sarah also says she enjoyed making icing for breakfast and making gingerbread for lunch the next day. Josh adds that he will be returning to work.',NULL,NULL),(64300,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/08/10/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - August 10, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-08-10 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 12:27:30',NULL,'The gang gets back to the game, which is to say, they\'re playing board games. This time, it\'s a different game, but the same game.\n\nSo who\'s here today? It turns out that it was Nora, Adam, Holland, Talya, and Shelly. Sarah\'s off swimming with her mom, and she\'s going to play some board games with the gang. Sarah tells us that the last time she was at the park, she played a Harry Potter board game. But this time, she\'ll play a different board game, so it\'ll be Snakes and Nerves, Story and Trouble, and maybe a game called Operation. Okay, so what are your favorite board games? They\'re all different, but they all have the same thing in common: they\'ve got to play the same board game for a bunch of different reasons. One of them is that the game on her iPad is dying, so she needs to get a new one. She also tells us she likes to listen to music on her tablet, but she doesn\'t know which one.\n\nThen she asks if she can join in on the game. She\'ll kill the guy if he says anything. But she also asks if he\'s there when she gets back. And then she asks when he got back from the show.',NULL,NULL),(64301,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/08/03/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - August 3, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-08-03 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 12:11:49',NULL,'On this episode, the Host returns to the Community of Hearts, where he is teaching a fitness class. He asks the students about their day-to-day activities, and Josh is one of them. He is doing a Valentine\'s movie for his dad, and he is going to hang out with his family over the weekend. The Host asks Josh about Harry Potter, and the students discuss the books they are reading. Josh says he is doing the book, which is a phase of the novel. The students discuss their favorite characters in the book.',NULL,NULL),(64302,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/07/27/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - July 27, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-07-27 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 11:46:01',NULL,'This is a great show and it is a very fun show to watch. It starts off with a conversation between Sarah and Josh. They are on a family day , and Sarah\'s mom gives her a chocolate for Valentine\'s day. Sarah tells Josh that her family will be busy on that day, and Josh says that his house will be a busy place that day. They talk about Josh\'s family and how they will be celebrating the day together, like having dinner with them.',NULL,NULL),(64303,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/07/20/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - July 20, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-07-20 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 11:30:35',NULL,'In this episode, the listeners are introduced to two new members of the CFRU community: Handel and Jeff. Handel is a volunteer at the university and he loves working with people and contributing to the community.\n\nHe also loves music and the university has a great music vending machine. The community radio show is a weekly program on CFRU. This program airs every Saturday morning at 9am. The program is hosted by the host, Josh, who is a student at the University of Guelph, and he is a friend of the listeners. He is also a fan of the Guelph Storm, a professional men\'s ice hockey team. The listeners are also introduced to the program\'s host, and they learn that the show is produced by the community radio station.',NULL,NULL),(64305,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/07/13/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - July 13, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-07-13 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 11:12:30',NULL,'When he was younger, he was thinking that these men were supporting these white women because they were slaves. So when he got into the suffragette movement, he realized that these women were brave enough to stand up and demand their rights.\n\nThat is exactly what happened, he says. He thanks everyone in the city for inviting him to the show. He just wants to leave everybody downtown with one thing: take a look at our future. That\'s what the future is going to look like. It\'s going to require unity to move forward. He says he loves his brother. He also says he\'s sad to see Martin, Bland, and Eric all dead.\n\nHe wishes he could breathe easier. They\'re all listening to the Mobile Community FM Show, hosted by Wayne. He goes to the Community of Hearts where he recorded Sarah, Josh, and Amanda back on Valentine Day. Sarah tells her story. She says she had a good day, which included watching a couple of shows and then coming to the center to watch a Valentine\'s Show. The show is about three girls who go out with boyfriends, and Lola is no longer married because she thinks Lola is moving away to the house of her parents. She then has cancer, and she\'s not going to be able to do anything about it. Sarah says she\'ll go home and hang out with her family and her dog, and then go to bed. Wow, sounds like a great day. Sarah',NULL,NULL),(64307,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/07/06/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - July 6, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-07-06 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 10:53:50',NULL,'This is the first part of the show, and it\'s all about the freedom of people. It\'s about the tradition of Black people, and how this tradition has led to people being freed. It was a very important part of their history, and they\'re just grateful to be able to do this work. The program ends with a conversation between Mayebuye and Aweitu, who are grateful for the opportunity to be on the show.\n\nThey say that they\'d like to do a little more advertising on the station, since there are so many great things happening in the community. If you\'re looking for a local business or event to promote, they have a few options: free public service announcements, for-profit ad packages, and the option to run a PSA on the air. If your idea is cool, contact outreach at . . for more info. Every Wednesday at 9am on CFRU., the stillness of the dance brings you sound local to. The stillness in the dance has you searching in the simple, giving you some solace.\n\nThis is a quiet corner of comfort food in an introverted world, soon to be your fave musical retreat. Ad Video is the hub for creating video art, video film, and documentaries in Guelph. Get started or advance your skills, find creative challenges, and develop a community of collaborators through their year-round course of workshops and education programs. Apply yourself with access to high-quality equipment in an environment',NULL,NULL),(64309,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/06/29/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - June 29, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-06-29 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 10:34:35',NULL,'This is the first part of a two-part interview with Jim Fahey. The first part is dedicated to discussing the various services provided by CFRU, including free public service announcements and the option to purchase a PSA.\n\nThe second part is devoted to discussing Clannagale, a program that is a staple on the station. It features two hours of Celtic music from all over the world. This program is also a favorite of many listeners because it\'s a great way to learn about music and culture from around the globe. You can also listen to the program on your iPod, iPhone, or any other device that has a good internet connection. This show also features the Mobile Community Show, a weekly program that airs on the air in Guelph.\n\nIt\'s hosted by Jim Fahey and is produced by the Guelph branch of the Canadian Free Press. The program starts with a conversation between Duncan and Amanda, a couple who live in the city of Guelph. Duncan is a musician and his two kids are in school. They were born in the same year, so they haven\'t been to school for a long time. They are very excited about the upcoming school year.',NULL,NULL),(64319,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/27/Tone Zone - September 27, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-27 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 10:09:23',NULL,'The show starts off with a little intro by Matt, the host of the local music station. He introduces himself as Matt, and he\'s here to tell us that this is the week of \"So Can Week\" at the university, so all the artists who perform there will get paid.\n\nHe wants to support Julianna Hatfield, who is releasing an album in the coming weeks dedicated to the late ELO. He\'s going to play one of her songs called \"Get In Line\" from her first album, In Exile, which was released in 2004. The show opens with Talley\'s & Midnight, a band from Toronto. This is a band that\'s been around for a long time. They\'re called the \"Reds, Pinks, and Purples\" and they just released their latest album, Modern Fiction, in 2021. The other bands on the show are: Joan of Arc , Owls , Make Believe , Cap\'N Jazz , Dead Friends , and Shane Ghostkeeper , who\'s releasing his latest album Songs for my People.',NULL,NULL),(64329,219,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/q7fm2d/ES230927.mp3','2023-09-28 05:30:05',138640284,'2023-10-28 11:13:08',NULL,'James Bailey, host of CIUT 89.5 FM\'s Electric Sense, begins the show with a track from Nicole Rompersod\'s upcoming release. Serge Boulat will then take us out from a recent note type release. Geyshes will then be taking us out to a piece by the group Ugly Beauties.',NULL,'Electric Sense is a weekly music show on CIUT 89.5 FM. This week'),(64330,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Wild Combination - September 28, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 09:44:40',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64340,289,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/kexezb/The_Next_Stop_118a1len.mp3','2023-09-28 06:06:11',272575234,'2023-12-05 09:06:54',NULL,'This is the 118th episode of the next stop on cinit 89.5 FM, hosted by Sage Ranaldo, and it\'s all about the music from the movie Bottoms, which was released in 2023. The music comes from the soundtrack, composed by Charlie XCX and Leo Burenberg. You can listen to the entire program back at the next-stop.\n\npodbeans.com. To get things started, Leo and Charlie are joined by Tiersa, Kali Uchi, and Vayacondios. After that, Enjoy with I-ve Wasted so Much Time on, Sweetbindness, and After Enjoy with... After Enjoy, I-have-Wasted so much Time was Sweetbunch with Quebec. From there, there\'s a bunch of new music. Next up is Home with Harry Nilsson, followed by Everyday Fires with Kathy Arad, and Home with the Moonbeam Song',NULL,NULL),(64341,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Wild Combination - September 28, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 08:45:28',NULL,'This is the first episode of a new series called \"Cyberliches Gothic\" which takes place on CFRU\'s 93.3FM every Tuesday night. This is a dark comedy about a guy named Hendel who is a volunteer at the university. He\'s also a fan of the underground world of the Gothic Castle.',NULL,NULL),(64370,280,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/u9f72v/TFA_Full_Episode_Greece_Edited8t8yh.mp3','2023-09-28 13:39:41',84376611,'2023-12-05 08:33:57',NULL,'Seth Martosh is one of the show\'s co-hosts. He is a fourth-year architecture student and loves discovering music from all over the world. He also loves to share the diverse cultures on campus with students. Seth tells us that next week he and Tranxle will be hosting the show.\n\nThis week, they\'re heading to Greece to hear music. Next week they\'ll be talking to Fedra about Greek culture and how her experience has informed her studies. They\'ll also be talking about Andromeda, a song by a famous Italian musician. Seth is half-Greek, so he can\'t say the name of the song. The last thing that they want to mention is that last weekend Seth, Isabella, and another volunteer joined them on a trip to the Golden Gate to speak at a Global Jazz Conference. They spoke to a Toronto artist named Monika. He was very talented, and Seth says that he\'s been involved with lots of different people in the city.\n\nHe suggests that listeners follow the show on Soundcloud and listen to all of the interviews. Seth and Phaedra are also on the show, and they\'ve been talking to Phaedras from Greece. She\'s doing a performance class and a morning class. She says that one of her friends bought her and her sister a show to watch at the end the year.',NULL,NULL),(64371,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 28, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 08:07:47',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64372,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Here Today - September 28, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 07:10:54',NULL,'This is the first hour of the show, and it\'s all about new music. The first act is a Swedish band called Retro-Graaf, who are playing new music from their upcoming EP, Coercion, as well as a song called \"The Divine\" from the recently released Romantic England. The band is touring and releasing new music all the time. The second act is an American band called Dance Electronica, who have just released their new album called \"I Am Not Myself\" . The third act is another American band, called Hotel Myra, who\'ve just released an album. The show ends with some new music by a Canadian artist named David Francie, who is on a tour.',NULL,NULL),(64382,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/FoodFarm Talk - September 28, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 06:48:10',NULL,'The second episode of the six-a-gates to tipie or blackfoot agriculture project opens with a conversation between Lancefeathers of blood tribe or Kainai first nation and Mike Bruised head, a long-time rancher at Kainai.\n\nThe purpose of the treaty is to \"honour and revitalize the traditional relationship we have\" with Buffalo. The Blackfoot nations have signed the treaty since day one, and there are now 31 signatories. Another organization that Mike mentions is the Kainai Ecosystem Protection Association, or KIPA. KIPA was a cool organization that used to organize a summit for people off the reserve to attend, but it\'s become a really cool way to learn about the reserve and connect with other people. Just before he hands things over to Mike and Lance, Lahey gives us an update on the Sixakate-Satipii agriculture project. It\'s more than just a podcast. It is a project that\'s trying to connect Blackfoot nation members with each other and learn best practices from each other.',NULL,NULL),(64383,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Tales from the Bridge - September 28, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 06:33:01',NULL,'We start off this episode by saying that we\'re psyched to have a guest on our show today. It\'s none other than New York Times best-selling science fiction author, Andy Weir.\n\nHe joins us on the bridge and tells us all about his life. He started out as a Software Engineer and then became a full-blown science fiction writer. His first novel, \"The Martian,\" was made into a movie starring Matt Damon, and his latest book, \"Project Hail Mary,\" is being adapted into a feature film starring Ryan Gosling. The book is a Hugo Award-finalist and is one of his favorite science fiction novels.',NULL,NULL),(64393,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Democracy Now - September 28, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 01:07:39',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64394,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - September 28, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 00:48:25',NULL,'Jenny Mitchell, a volunteer and studio coordinator for Community Radio Guelph, is here to tell us about the North-End Harvest Market, an initiative of the Guelph Neighbourhood Support Coalition. The market is a place where people can meet with other people in the community to get fresh produce. Jenny is surprised to find that she has a recorder with her at the market.',NULL,NULL),(64399,180,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/y736p4/HOWL_SEPT_29_20239pmib.mp3','2023-09-28 20:02:34',56693156,'2023-12-05 00:26:48',NULL,'This is the second part of a three part interview with the co-hosts of CIUT FM. The first part is a thank you note to the listeners for their financial support. The second part is about the upcoming October 31st Howl-o-ween Open Mic. The third part is the announcement of the Halloween Open Mic in 2023. The co-host tells the listeners that he will be starting off the show with a friend from his poetry community from Toronto. Before he reveals her name, he tells them about a poem he wrote for the show.',NULL,NULL),(64405,205,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/bepj4e/September_28th_2023_Music_At_High_Noonaxfsg.mp3','2023-09-28 18:14:44',287962512,'2023-12-05 00:05:14',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64406,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Android’s Dungeon - September 28, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 23:46:57',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64407,13307,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Eclectic Selections - September 28, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 23:06:05',NULL,'The show\'s new name is \"Eclectic Selections\" and it\'s going to be all about exploring music beyond the boundaries of one genre. We\'re starting with free jazz. The music is from the past. It was recorded in the early 2000s.\n\nIt sounds like there\'s a lot of soul in this music, even though it sounds like it was recorded by free jazz artists like Grover Washington Jr and Bill Withers. It also sounds like this music was recorded on Bob Dylan\'s \"Pretty Woman\" album. We also find out that Michael Kewanuku wrote a song called \"Love and Hate\" that sounds a lot like this one. It has a spiritual vibe to it. The show ends with a song about freedom.',NULL,NULL),(64417,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/RadiOPIRG - September 28, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 22:50:36',NULL,'The 10 year anniversary is fast approaching. The Comedy Festival is bringing in some of the best comedians in the province. This is a great opportunity for us to get together and talk about the festival. On this particular day, the festival decided to celebrate by hosting a march.\n\nThe march was organized by five northern Ontario First Nations. They came together to call on the Ford government to stop mining activities on their lands. The festival worked with the Wellington water watchers and the Guelph students for environmental change to organize a bus to the march. On the way back, they ran into Chief Rudy Turtle, the leader of the Grassy-Narrows First Nation. He\'s just gotten back from the march, so he doesn\'t have a watch with him.\n\nHe thanks the festival for coming out and thanking him for coming to listen to them. He says that for 50 years, the First Nation has been suffering from mercury poisoning. The First Nation used to have a paper mill. The government dumped a lot of mercury into the river, but the government hasn\'t done anything about it. Now that the government has a plan, they\'re going to have to pay the First Nations for it. One of the former advisors to the government came up to him and said that he used to work for the government.\n\nHe told him that they were going to the mill. He also told the minister not to worry about it, it\'ll all be all right.',NULL,NULL),(64418,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/T.K.O. - September 28, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 22:31:08',NULL,'This is the first in a series of interviews with the Host of the Combat Sports Podcast, Tim Killam, or \"TKO.\" He tells his listeners about his show, which he calls \"Mixed Martial Arts\" or \"MMA.\" He explains that it\'s all about combat sports and \"issues that surround the universe with fighting.\n\n\" The show has been going strong for the past week, and he says that he couldn\'t be happier. He asks the listeners to tell him what\'s up with them. He says that this week has been a \"phenomenal week\" and that he hopes everyone had a good day. He tells the listeners that he\'s glad that the show is celebrating episode 340. He adds that he doesn\'t like to celebrate the milestone by baking a cake, but he does like to acknowledge how far the show has come since it started. He compares the amount of time that it would take him to record all of the episodes to the hours he\'d have to talk to the void on his personal phone.\n\nIt\'s hard for him to believe that he could have recorded every single episode of the show, but that\'s what he does. He thanks his listeners for their support and says that even if he could not have done it without them, he wouldn\'t have made it to this point. He also thanks the listeners for being such a huge part of his success. He admits that it makes him feel proud and humbled.',NULL,NULL),(64423,182,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dkphsi/Sept_27_2023bbghl.mp3','2023-09-28 22:19:17',142703803,'2023-12-04 22:09:12',NULL,'In this week\'s edition of No Beat, the host of the show, Suresh, thanks listeners for their financial support. He\'s been listening to new music from all over the city, and the first song he plays is from a band called \"Grave Desecrator,\" which is an abstract project by a Canadian artist named Bradley Davis.\n\nThe second song is from another Canadian band called Science Furric, which is celebrating its 25th anniversary. The third track is from the band \"Office Album,\" which sounds like it\'s going to be a hidden track. The fourth track is a song called \"Song Number 4,\" from an album called \"Crossing Field,\" by a band named Mono Negatives. The fifth track is an album from \"Lon Redhead,\" an early punk band from London. The sixth track is one of my favorites, from \"Repress and Curl,\" an album by \"Shabbo Palace, Black up.\" The seventh track is \"End of the World,\" from \"Dr. Systems,\" a psychedelic music collective from Toronto.',NULL,NULL),(64429,257,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/xpmm6w/September_28_2023_Psychedelic_Stoner_Rock72dhy.mp3','2023-09-28 22:23:33',287962512,'2023-12-04 21:45:04',NULL,'On this edition of Psychedelic And Stoner Rock, Ken Stauer delivers the first hour\'s program from a diverse group of artists, including Middle Mist Red, Kaiser Moon, El Caco, Egypt, Stoned Jesus, The Hazy tones, and the Black cat\'s eye. The program\'s title is Multicolored Drive and the first two hours of the program will begin with Middle Mist red.',NULL,NULL),(64430,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Open Sources Guelph - September 28, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 19:30:35',NULL,'On this week\'s episode of Open-Source\'s Guelph, the host of the political and current affairs show at the University of Guelph, Adam Donaldson, takes a look back at some of the recent events in the city. The show opens with a quick introduction to the program, and the host introduces himself as Adam Donaldson. Adam is a professor of political science at the university. He is also a co-host of the Open Source Discussion Show, a weekly program on the university\'s campus. The program is hosted by Adam, who is also the co-editor of the Political and Current affairs section of the university newspaper, the Guelph Politico. Adam describes the program as a public affairs show. It is produced by a group of students and faculty members who work together to discuss issues of public concern. It airs every Thursday evening at 5pm on CFRU. This program is a mix of current affairs, news, and entertainment from around the world. This week, the program will be covering elections in Manitoba, politics in Parliament, and a number of other topics. The first topic of the show is the Green Belt, which the province\'s premier, Doug Ford, broke his promise not to open it. He apologizes for breaking his promise. He says it was a mistake, and one that left too much space for people to benefit from it. It also left people to question the motives of the government. He also says that he will not make any changes in the',NULL,'Open-Source’s Adam Donaldson is the host of the political and current affairs show in Guelph'),(64431,119,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Turtle Island Underground - September 28, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 21:09:32',NULL,'The show opens with an interlude from a new record by the Tewa titled \"Gum Chum With an Indian Bum\". It can be found on the archives at the CFRU.com as well as a special interview with the band a few weeks before.\n\nDoro