L),(64690,216,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dqhkfd/RAW092923mp3.mp3','2023-10-01 21:51:31',159275312,'2023-12-03 22:28:28',NULL,'This is the second in a series of short, one-minute commercials for Great Lakes Lager, a beer brewed by the Great Lakes Brewery in Toronto. In this program, Peter and Isabelle introduce the beer, and then introduce Metal Supermarkets, a distributor of metal products. They tell us that they are bringing the beer to all the GTA locations of the company, and that they have over 8,000 products to choose from.\n\nPeter also explains that he is joined in the booth by DJ Cher, who has a number of upcoming events. She will be playing at Hound\'s Tooth on October 7 th , with Gremara, and at Basement 254 on October 14 th with John Kong. She also has a party on October 28 th from Sister Cities soul club collective, Debbie, and Fiona. If you would like to learn more about these upcoming events, you can call in to the booth.',NULL,NULL),(64691,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/01/Seems Like Old Times - October 1, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-01 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 22:11:12',NULL,'The young man tells his mother that what he\'s about to tell her is a \"tissue of lies\" . He tells her that he heard voices behind him in the dining hall and that he didn\'t care what they were saying.\n\nHe asks Mrs. Lex to stop him, but she interrupts him and asks him to finish. He says that he never remembers whether he is knitting or curling, but that he has noticed that the young man leaning on the edge of the dining room looks \"kind of peaky.\" He tells Mrs. Liss that the jelly sandwiches are good, but he doesn\'t feel well. He wants to help himself with some quince preserves, but Mrs.\n\nand Mrs. Loukas look at him very good, and he says that the doctor ordered him to do so. He also tells them that he is just about the age of his son in Japan. He introduces himself as a newspaperman and says that his name is Craig and that his father is an uncle of his late husband\'. He adds that he was born in New York.',NULL,NULL),(64692,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/01/La Buena Onda - October 1, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-01 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-01 22:08:25',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64702,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/4dwrhk/October_1_2023_Across_the_Universeavyte.mp3','2023-10-02 00:03:56',431961989,'2023-10-31 03:53:10',NULL,'Ken Stower welcomes the listeners to his weekly show, which is called \"Across the Universe\" and airs on CIUT 99.5 FM every Sunday from 5pm until 8pm. The theme for the show is \"Phaedra\" and the band Tangerine Dream provides the music. Ken says that there are still some tickets left for the upcoming show. He hopes listeners have enjoyed their weekend so far and continue to enjoy the show before it all ends up. Ken begins with a big funk outfit and goes on to play a song called \"Everything\'s Gonna be Alright\" and then he begins his weekly musical trip with \"strings broken threads and springs broken heads\". He says that the streets are filled with broken people and that he is \"a sing-looking flame\" and that is why he is so big. He says he is a \"bunch of turnips\" and says that he can play the keys but that he does not play any other things. He also says that if he needs to call heaven, he will stop his feet. Then he says he has \"engine trouble\" and someone is riding in his car and he is afraid that someone else is driving it. Ken asks how he can drive his car, and he',NULL,'Ken Stower says he is a \"sing-looking flame\" and he has \"engine trouble\"'),(64703,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/01/La Buena Onda - October 1, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-01 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-02 00:07:13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64704,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/01/Zombie Jamboree - October 1, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-01 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 21:12:35',NULL,'On this edition of the weekly Fix, the host, Bruce, introduces a new set of music for the festival. The first set is a mix of tracks from two producers from Montreal named Boogie Man, and Samito. The second set includes tracks from Umeko and others. The third set includes some of the most popular tracks of the festival, such as Over the Moon, Gotopo, and Fuerza Nata. The last set includes a song called Hakka Di-Pichiyoto, which the host thinks is a good song.',NULL,NULL),(64708,170,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/itz7gv/Ruby_Slippers_Sept_29_mp3_-_2023-09-25_818_PM9o7vc.mp3','2023-10-02 01:20:01',111378520,'2023-12-03 20:53:23',NULL,'The narrator opens the show by saying that he\'s getting ready for the end of summer and the beginning of autumn. He\'s been listening to lots of music, and he has a few new songs for you tonight. The first song is from a band called Boy Wolves, who are out of Wealth and have a new track called Retrograth.\n\nThe second song is a Canadian band called Altered by Mom, who have an EP called Ahem and a new single called Gwendolyn. The third song is one from a German band called Karl Karlten, who used to play in Peter Mafeis band and is now a member of his band the Dogs. The narrator says that the band\'s song from the new album is called Glory of Love. The show will be up on Mixcloud and on CIUT\'s website via Mira Soy Radio. The next song is by Hotel, who is out of Fever Pitch and has a new song called Sword. The last song is Pete International, who has an album called The Watermark.',NULL,NULL),(64715,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/01/Wind-Down - October 1, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-01 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 20:36:43',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part program on the CFRU.com website. The first part of the program is a look at the music that\'s been played on the show tonight. It\'s all about human rights, and it\'s in Spanish. The second part is a program called \"To the Wind Down.\n\n\" It starts off by playing some of the most popular songs from the US with \"So Typically Now\" and \"Bless this mess\" and then moves on to Lee Paradise\'s \"The Thing,\" \"New Chance with that\'t What Happened\" and Bernice\'s song \"Saint Lucia.\" The program ends with a Canadian band called \"Le Couleur,\" followed by a group called \"Stratz,\" and then \"Jardine\" and his song \"Learning to love\" from his EP.',NULL,NULL),(64716,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/01/Zombie Jamboree - October 1, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-01 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 20:11:16',NULL,'The second hour at the Zombie Jamboree is a mix of new music and old favorites. The first piece is by the Saltons of String from Walking Through Fire.\n\nThe second is by Selena Martin and her band, followed by a story from Nora Kelly\'s band. The third piece is a song by Elke Khan and B. A. Johnston called On Babe or Zombie. The music is all about the harvest, and Elke gives us a metaphor for the music: if you grow anything, it\'s going to go away soon. The weather is coming, and if it hasnt already hit, there\'s a frost. So the music is celebrating the harvest. It\'s also about appreciating the hard workers who have been working all season. The song that sticks out the most is by Havana meets Kingston. The track is old, but it has new lyrics. It was named after the song\'s title. You can listen to the music on the web and on the radio.',NULL,NULL),(64726,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/u3uipq/Karibuni_Oct_1-20238r01f.mp3','2023-10-02 02:37:22',287962512,'2023-12-03 19:54:16',NULL,'In this episode, we learn that Jesse McDougall has been attending a fair in downtown Toronto to learn about all the different ways that students can go abroad to study. One of the students is from Curacao, and he is the chancellor of a school called the Avalon University of Medicine in Toronto.',NULL,NULL),(64727,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/01/Backtracks - October 1, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-01 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 19:13:14',NULL,'This is the second episode of the Backtracks program, hosted by Host Jennifer. The program is dedicated to reviving \"lost tracks\" from the 60s, 70s, and 80s. The theme for this show is \"Flight.\" The program opens with a song from a San Francisco band called \"Fly to New York.\n\n\" The song was recorded in the late 60s and is one of the most popular unsigned bands of the time. Host Jennifer explains that he\'s going through \"passport hell\" at the moment, wanting to get to the island of Ireland to see where his mother\'s remains are scattered. He was married for five minutes, \"many, many years\" ago. He says he was a communist when he was younger, so he couldn\'t get into the army because he was an \"organizational communist.\" He\'s trying to get a passport for the first time ever, but he has to go to Toronto tomorrow to get it.\n\nThe first track on the program is from a Scottish band called Nazareth in 1973. It\'s known for its cover by the name of \"Nazareth.\" The second track is from Canadian singer Jack Landron, who is now known as \"Jackie Washington.\" The third track is a folk song called \"Let Me Fly.\" The track was originally recorded in 1961 and was a project called \"Maureene Wishful.\" It was a group of musicians that included Jimmy Page, Burn Williams, Vic Flick, and Big Jim Sullivan.',NULL,NULL),(64728,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/01/Through the Looking Glass - October 1, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-01 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 18:50:16',NULL,'This is the second in a series of three parts in which the host interviews a new artist. The first part is about P.\n\nMad, a musician from Ireland who has a new EP out called Sword. The second part of the show is about Renee, an artist from the University of Guelph who has an EP called Metamorphosis. The third part is a little bit about Ed Video, a local arts and culture hub. Ed Video offers a wide variety of opportunities for students to develop their skills through workshops, educational programs, and hands-on experience. The host is also a member of the CFRU community and can be heard on the 93.3 campus.',NULL,NULL),(64738,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/This Night Wounds Time - October 2, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 18:29:43',NULL,'The show returns to active duty and begins with a review of the latest releases. This week, they are not doing a \"Geographic Spotlight\" series, but instead, they will be hearing folk jazz from Audrey Ochoa. They will also be hearing a new guitar concerto from Pascal Valois, and they will also hear a new track from Chloe Lum. They conclude with Jessica Moss from the MusicWorks 143 recording studio, who studies \"Uncanny Being.\"',NULL,NULL),(64739,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/01/This Night Wounds Time - October 1, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-01 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 18:10:47',NULL,'This week on This Night Wound\'s Time, the host, Christopher Curry, begins the show by announcing that he\'s a Socan Audit week, which means that he can legally play music from Canada after midnight, but he wants to make sure that the music he plays is Canadian-centric.\n\nHe starts off the show with a new track from the Peripheral Vision group, which is comprised of Trevor Hoag, Don Scott, Michael Herring and Nick Frazier. The show will be heard by listeners all over the world. They\'ll also be hearing a lot of calls from listeners to the 93.3 FM station in Guelph, where they\'re located. The group\'s new album is called Portrait de la artiste, or Portrait of the artist.\n\nThey also have a track called Battle of Santiago from their latest release, Los Santos y pecados. Finally, the show will return to the music of jazz, this time with music from the Atlantis jazz ensemble. They have just released their latest album, Celestial suite, and they\'ve got a track named Transcendence in the mix. This is going to be one of the most important jazz tracks of all time.',NULL,NULL),(64749,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/This Night Wounds Time - October 2, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 17:05:07',NULL,'The third hour of this show is dedicated to music. The show starts off with a reminder that this show will be back in \"active duty\" for the next week. After that, the show will return to its geographical spotlight section, but it will not be rebroadcast for the time being.\n\nNext, they\'ll hear music from the \"Paramorph Collective\" . They\'re going to listen to a song called \"Fruiting Bodies\" from the album \"All We Are Made of.\" That\'s followed by a song from \"Selected Works 1 and 2\" . Then it\'s \"NoiStat\" , followed by \"NuStat\" and finally \"Woodland Meditation\" from \"The Woodland Project.\" We\'re about to say good-bye to this show,',NULL,NULL),(64777,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 2, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 16:46:32',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64778,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Here Today - October 2, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 07:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 16:31:18',NULL,'In this second part of the show, Aaron Badgley discusses some of the new music that he\'s heard in Hamilton, Ontario. The first band he listens to is called the Crowley\'S and its debut album is called Strange Seasons, and the second is called Lampshade.\n\nHe likes the sound of the two bands, and he remembers when AM and FM were all \"bubble gum pop\" and all the \"psychedelic or prog rock\" . The next band he hears is called \"Apollo Suns\" and its album is Departures. It sounds like it\'s a jazz rock band. And the third band he thinks is cool is called Peace Flag Ensemble and its second album is The Work.',NULL,NULL),(64788,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 2, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-09 06:32:42',NULL,'The discussion shifts to the role of the school in terms of the health and welfare of students. The psychologist explains that the role is to protect the rights of the student and to provide them with the resources they need to navigate the system. He also discusses eating disorder and how it can impact the student\'s health.',NULL,'The School\'s Role in the Health and Welfare of Students (13 minute read)'),(64789,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 2, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-09 06:18:01',NULL,'The following morning, a group of prominent people gather for a breakfast to discuss human rights in education. The topic of this morning\'s breakfast is \"human rights and equity\" and it\'s hosted by the Upper Grand District School Board. We\'re introduced to our guest, Alicia Ralph, who is a \"dedicated advocate\" for human rights. She\'s also a \"passionate supporter\" of the Canadian charter of rights and freedoms. She addresses topics like gender and sexuality equality and equity and the concerns parents have regarding school curriculum, and she uses her personal experience as a parent as well as her passion for the Charter to inform the discussion. Phil Ault is the host of the breakfast and he\'s a city councillor from the city of Buffalo. He\'s been bringing the Breezy Breakfasts to the city for six years now. He introduces his guests and then turns it over to \"Margaret\" to introduce them. Alicia is the new human rights advisor for the Upper grand district board and she\'s going to be responsible for addressing human rights for all students and staff. She also has a doctorate degree from the university. She is excited to get to know the community of Walth. She looks forward to meeting the people there',NULL,'The Breezy Breakfast in Buffalo, NY (11 minute read): Meet the New Human Rights Advisor for the Upper Grand District School Board '),(64799,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Democracy Now - October 2, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 16:10:04',NULL,'The U. S. Congress narrowly avoided a government shutdown over the weekend. House Speaker John Boehner agreed to a deal with Democrats and Republicans that would keep the government open through November 17. The bill doesn\'t include funding for Ukraine, though, and it does include money for disaster relief. The bill quickly passes the Senate and is signed by the president late Saturday. Vice President Joe Biden blasted Republicans for again making a crisis over the funding of the government. He said, \"There should be another crisis, there shouldn\'t have been another crisis.\"',NULL,NULL),(64800,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Worst Responders - October 2, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 15:50:04',NULL,'The second year students Charissa and Renee host a show called Worst Responders where they are the first and worst comedians to respond to problems posted on the internet. They are improvisable and they do not reflect the opinion of the university. The students discuss their first year of college and their show. They say that their show was the end for them because they were too free spirited.',NULL,NULL),(64810,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/CFRU Playlist - October 2, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-02 20:06:33',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64820,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - October 2, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 15:12:43',NULL,'In this episode, we hear from Nicholas Cooper, the guardian of the Sentinel, about the music that he will curate for the show. He explains that he wants to acknowledge the Native American and First Nations communities that have been listeners to the show, as well as the Black community that has contributed to the music.\n\nHe also thanks the BIPOC people for their contributions to the popular, alternative and experimental music sphere. The show begins with a Canadian content session featuring Jaywood, who has just released a music EP called Grow On. We hear the first track Heavy Eyes, an instrumental piece. The EP is called Grow on by Jaywood and it is released on a record called Royal Mountain Records, which is owned by one of the most prominent labels in the music business, Royal Mountain. We also hear Raphael Khan, who released a new track called Kilometre Club. The second track is an ambient piece, and the third track is a new age contemporary piece from a legend named Rob.\n\nThe first track on Rob\'s new album, Astral Mansion, is called Ruined By Pastels. The music video for this track is also available on Robs YouTube channel. It is called \"Remedy by Pastels\" and it was shot by Ryan Masters, who directed the music video. The song is one of Robs favorite moves on his new album. He takes a recording of the song and chops it into a melody. He then turns the melody into a loop.',NULL,NULL),(64830,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Big Sis Radio - October 2, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 14:50:50',NULL,'Cece opens the show by welcoming the listeners to a new kind of music station, called Big Sis Radio. It\'s hosted by Cece, a guy named Cece who curates and hosts the show on a local station called CFRU. The show begins with a psych rock band called The Closed Eyes. The band\'s latest album is called Strange Seasons and is currently the top selling album on the station.\n\nCece then tells the listeners that he\'ll be revealing to them the artist currently on top of the station\'s charts. He\'ll tell them the name of the artist and then he\'s going to reveal to you that this artist is named Autobahn. The other artist Cece is going to show you is Le Couleur, a Montreal synthpop band.',NULL,NULL),(64831,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/to know the land - October 2, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-30 16:52:24',NULL,'The narrator of this program is Byron, the host of CFRU\'s Big Sis Radio. He tells us that he\'s on the lookout for volunteers to participate in a study about the effects of COVID-19 on young and older adults. The narrator also tells us about Silence, a non-profit organization that works to preserve silence. They need your support to continue their work, so they\'re asking you to pledge to silence for a month. If you can\'t commit $10 a month but want to support the cause, you can pledge to support Silence for a year. You can support Silence by signing up for their pledge of silence. Byron tells us his name is Cece, and he is a producer on the CFRU program, To Know the land. Byron introduces himself as Dr Troy McMullen, a research scientist at the Canadian museum of nature. He says he started his career as a high school biology teacher. He was interested in studying lichens because he was involved in protecting old growth forest in Nova Scotia. He wanted to get his master\'s degree, so he went to different universities to find out what other scientists were studying. He found there weren\'t many people who studied lichens. He ended up spending most of his time learning about lichens from other scientists. He\'s published two books, one on lichens and the other on the common lichens of the Great Lakes. Byron wants to know what\'s different about the new book, Macro',NULL,'Big Sis Radio narrator asks you to pledge to silence for a month'),(64841,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Blues Around the Block - October 2, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 14:29:22',NULL,'The second part of the show is titled \"Mac D.\" The program is called \"Blues Around the Block.\" The host says that if you enjoyed the previous edition of the program, you can now stream it or download it from the university\'s website.\n\nIf you have comments about the program or previous editions, you may contact him by email at macdee@calf.ca. He also says that he\'s going to finish off the hour with The Maple Blues Band and he\'ll keep the program locked on the university for more music. He\'s also going to play some music with The Bakers Groove and Charliewhite. The show is celebrating the 10th anniversary of the festival and it\'s a good time for people to get into the comedy game. The festival is also celebrating the release of a band called the Fog Blues and brass band\'s self-titled album from May 2023. The band will perform a show called \"Clutter Prove with Ken and Isaac Kessler\" on October 21st . The music on the program is also a great selection of blues music from the past.\n\nThe first set is by Diana Brathwaite, Chris Whiteley, Jim Burns, and Hamilton. The second set is from David Deacon, Matt Anderson, and Little Magic Sam. The third set is a great collection of songs by the West Coast blues artists. From Vancouver to Vancouver, Uncle Wiggly is on the road. You can tune into the program on CFRU, the',NULL,NULL),(64842,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Blues Around the Block - October 2, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 14:07:22',NULL,'Mac Dee welcomes his listeners to his weekly show, \"Blues Around the Block,\" which is streamed live from the University\'s website. If you liked the show or enjoyed any previous editions, you can now stream or download the show from the university\'s archives. Mac Dee also lets us know that he\'s been in love with a woman named Sylvia Dee from \"Water Street Blues Band.\" He tells us that he and Sylvia set off together on a road trip from Seattle to Chicago. Sylvia Dee says that it\'s hard being \"blue\" when',NULL,NULL),(64852,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/The Deep House Project - October 2, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-31 05:46:41',NULL,'This week on the Deep House project, Aaron Badgley and the band play a selection of new and older tracks. The first track is by Dabin, who has teamed up with William Black on a song called \"Black in the Cold.\" The band also plays a song by the legendary DJ, Kevin Glasko, \"The Rhythm.\"',NULL,'Aaron Badgley and the band play new and older tracks on Deep House'),(64853,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Ripcord Radio - October 2, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 13:51:03',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the music on the upcoming show. It\'s going to be a lot of punk rock, which is very loud and fast and dirty. The music starts off in southern Ontario, then moves to Wisconsin, California, and finally to Cambridge, Ontario. The band Chachion Acid is coming up, followed by a band called None Left Standing, then another called Puff and Toss, then a group called Dead Friend Collective, then an album by a Montreal band called kingpins with one more day, and then a band from New Jersey called 9 Will Die. The last band is called Kid with Man Head with First Time, then Laina Lovich with Lucky Number, then Sting with Present Tense',NULL,NULL),(64855,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/03/Rainbow Country - October 3, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-03 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 13:29:27',NULL,'This week on the Rainbow Country show, we\'re introduced to the listeners of the local CFRU FM station, who are listening to the program on their local radio dial. They\'re also introduced to a new feature of the station, which is a web-based version of the program.\n\nSo the listeners can listen to all of the weekly program guides, see the latest music charts, listen to live performances, and even make a donation to help keep the station going. The program begins with a high energy song to get the body moving, and then goes into a slow and dreamy version of music. This is called \"Rainbow Country,\" and it\'s hosted by a cop named Danielle Botno. He\'s also known as \"LGBT cop\" because he\'s got a partner named Mark Tara, who\'s a DJ.\n\nThe two of them are on a tour of \"Rainbow country,\" where they\'re going to play music from all kinds of different kinds of music genres. The first song is from the original \"Batman\" movie, and the second is from \"Eartha Kit,\" the famous music video from that show. The next song is \"Jigger Daddy,\" a song about a man named Jigger. And where\'s my man? That\'s it for this week\'s show.',NULL,NULL),(64856,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/03/Rainbow Country - October 3, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-03 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 13:08:06',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64857,13298,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/03/CFRU Selector - October 3, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-03 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-03 13:49:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64867,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fjxnuh/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Oct_4_2023_podcastasu27.mp3','2023-10-03 10:47:21',277222921,'2023-12-03 12:47:37',NULL,'The next morning, Owen opens the program by thanking everyone who made a donation during the fall campaign to keep the station alive. He also notes that this is the first time that truth and reconciliation has been celebrated in Ontario.\n\nHe then talks about the music and the news of the day. He says that the weekend was national for truth, but not for Ontario, and that coinciding with this was \"Indian Summer\", a time when the sounds of music were heard. The music that was heard was mostly from the United States and Canada, and it was all done by artists from Canada. The news that day was that the Trump family was awarded the Nobel Peace prize for fraud. Owen also talks about how the music in the States is so different from the music that is heard in Canada.',NULL,NULL),(64868,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/03/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 3, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-03 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 12:27:29',NULL,'The song begins with a shout-out to Thomas King. He\'s just returned from his first day at the office, and he\'s feeling a little bummed out. But he says he\'ll be fine. He says he loves his mom, and she\'s been holding him close ever since. He tells her to come to him and kiss him goodnight.',NULL,NULL),(64869,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/02/Back in the USSR - October 2, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-02 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-03 12:12:33',NULL,'In this chapter, we\'re going to learn a little bit more about the National Day of Truth and Reconciliation and how it\'s celebrated in Canada. We\'re also going to hear the story of a woman named Phyllis Webstad who was forced to attend a boarding school when she was a child. She was taken away from her family and given an orange shirt as a symbol of her own worthlessness. Her story is told in her first-hand account, and we\'ll link to her story on the Ups and Ups Facebook page.',NULL,NULL),(64870,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/03/CFRU Playlist - October 3, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-03 06:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-03 14:06:18',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64880,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/03/Solipsistic Retreat - October 3, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-03 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-03 11:47:45',NULL,'The talk shifts to the upcoming Guelph Comedy Festival, celebrating its 10 year anniversary. The program begins with some music from a local band called Kids Street.\n\nThe group\'s debut album was released in 1993 and they have been making music ever since. They have a song called Penny Candy, which has been recorded for a local music video company called Ed Video, which is a reference to a famous song from the movie The Princess