 of other works that have the same number of parts as an opus. This is because we\'re all supposed to be in the spring, and we\'ve been since the beginning of time. The work is called \"Opus 34\" and it\'s composed by two contemporary classical guitarists. The duo is named \"Denando Karuli\" and \"Fernando sore\" , which means \"friend\" or \"brother\" in Latin.',NULL,NULL),(65472,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Clan Na Gael - October 8, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 12:32:49',NULL,'This program is all about organ donation. The organ recipient is Mike Willis, who is a very grateful recipient. The program starts off with a look at some of the things that are on the program. First up is a song by a family from Cape Breton called the Cotters. Next up is an Irish song called \"Bottom Macneil\" by David Agnew. Then there\'s a whistle from David, an instrumental from Lanygan Wall. And then there\'sa song by Charlotte Church called \"The Welsh Angel\" and another one by Roger Whittaker called \"Mexican Whistler\" . The rest of the program is about music.',NULL,NULL),(65473,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Clan Na Gael - October 8, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 12:14:34',NULL,'The host of the program introduces himself and tells his listeners that he will be playing some Spanish music on Thanksgiving. He says that he has family over for the day and will be going to the States the next day to attend a family wedding. The host then tells them about some of the artists who played on the first set. The first song is from Linda Ronstad, who is Mexican.\n\nShe was born in the U.S. in Arizona and her father was from Mexico. She played violin and played the drums. She also loves the bagpipes. She says that there is a lot of Celtic music in northern Spain. She tells listeners that Christopher Columbus was in the area and that he probably came there because he wanted