ng the folk-rock sound in the late 1960s. The group\'s version of Now Be Thankful was written by Dave Swarbrick and Richard Thompson, who were among the original members of the group.',NULL,NULL),(65481,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/09/This Night Wounds Time - October 9, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-09 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 10:30:30',NULL,'On the second hour, the show shifts its focus to a musician from the era of the psychedelia, a man named Kubero \"Diaz.\" He was a member of a band called \"La Cofradia del la Flor Solar.\" This band was based out of Nagoya, in the province of Entre Rios in Argentina. This man is a musician, singer, and poet. The first track on his album is called \"Palermo Viejo.\" The second track is from his forthcoming release \"Kubiero Diaz y La Pasada.\" This man\'s name is Jorge \"Mieli\" Mendez. He is from Parana, in this province, and he has an album called \"Ramos anel Oceano.\" This album is divided into four parts and five parts.',NULL,NULL),(65482,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/09/This Night Wounds Time - October 9, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-09 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 10:14:35',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the music on the program. The first track is a Canadian artist Ritesh Das\'s \"King Doll\" and the second is a track from the album \"To Begin With\" by the same artist. The third track is \"Hidden Orchestra\" and \"Skylarks\" from \"To Dream Is to Forget\" by \"Tristan Deliej\" versus \"Jamal X Jamal\". The program ends with \"Close the Paper and \"Play\" by Peripheral Vision. The program returns to the \"Geographic Spotlights\" section of the program, where they have been covering the largest countries by area.\n\nThey started with Russia, and then went on to China, India, the United States, Australia, Brazil, Canada, and finally Russia. They then went through each country in descending order and each country\'s internal parts. They have also gone through each of the countries by internal component. They are now at the Sakha republic in Canada.',NULL,NULL),(65483,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/This Night Wounds Time - October 8, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-01 09:49:28',NULL,'The program begins with the host, Christopher Curry, talking about a show called \"This Night-Wounds Time,\" which is devoted to music that is \"off the beaten track\" . The show will begin with music by artists that are \"off-center nature\" , which means that they are not part of the normal mainstream.\n\nFor the first hour, however, the program will focus on music that sounds off the beaten path. The program will then begin to focus on artists from a \"particular province of Argentina\" on the program. This program will also be a \"recommencing\" of a program that was \"temporarily halted earlier this year.\" The program\'s geographical spotlight section will resume when all is said and done. The first hour of this program will be dedicated to music \"of a somewhat overly very off-centered nature.\n\n\" The Atlantis Jazz Ensemble has just released an album called Celestial Suite, which was inspired by the music of John Coltrane, who died in 1967. The first track on the album is \"Blessings,\" which sounds like it is coming from Coltrane\'s \"Bliss.\" The show ends with music from another release in the new release collection, Ritesh Das\' \"To Begin With.\"',NULL,NULL),(65493,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/09/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 9, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-09 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 09:11:40',NULL,'This is a short introductory interview with Lee Fields, the host of CFRU\'s Morning Soul Shaker and Rare Soul R&B. In the interview, Fields explains that he\'s going to shoot for the university\'s 93.3 FM station.\n\nHe\'s looking for people to host events for the community, to record short public service announcements for the station, and to play music on the station. The station is also looking for musicians to play for free on Monday nights. If you\'re into music, then this is the place for you. You can listen to the station on CFRU.org or on 93.3 CFRU, or listen to it on your phone.',NULL,NULL),(65494,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/09/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 9, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-09 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-09 06:04:59',NULL,'The next day, the program begins with a description of the wind turbines. The narrator explains that the project was supposed to connect the plants to the grid, but Ford destroyed the plants and claimed that it saved the province money. The program then turns to lawsuits. The first question the program asks is whether there will be lawsuits against the government. The second question is whether the government will lose money from lawsuits. According to the narrator, the loss of three billion dollars in tax revenue is a small price to pay. The third question concerns lawsuits. In 2005, the government sued the Green Belt for protecting the Oakridge moraine. The government lost, but the government received a penalty. The next question is about the White Pines wind project. The project was almost completed when it was discovered that the government was going to destroy the plants. The province\'s cabinet minister was involved in the decision. The county\'s natural resources were against the project because it would destroy the Blanding family\'s turtle. The minister had a good working relationship with the natural resources because of the turtle\'s presence in the area. But when the car roads and the fields were opposing the project, the naturals were against it.',NULL,'The White Pines Wind Project (13 minute read): The First Day of the World\'s Most Expensive Project (14 minute read'),(65495,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/09/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 9, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-09 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-09 05:51:51',NULL,'The meeting starts with an acknowledgement of the City of Green Gables by the Mayor, then a statement of gratitude from the City to all of the residents of the city. The Mayor also reminds everyone of the recent election in Manitoba, where the first person with native heritage was elected as the new premier. The election is a step in moving towards reconciliation and the City can hold willingly the uncovering of tragic burial grounds in a land that was built in Winnipeg. The mayor also welcomes Mike Markalongos appearance and he tells everyone about his involvement in the Green Belt and his campaign to keep it as green as possible',NULL,'The Mayor of Green Gables is hosting a community meeting to discuss the future of the City of Winnipeg '),(65496,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/09/Here Today - October 9, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-09 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 08:55:11',NULL,'On this episode of Hear Today, Aaron Badgley opens the show with a song about being thankful for Thanksgiving. The song is from a new album from the Church of Trees, called Transience, which will be released in 2024.\n\nThe band also has two new songs on their new record, one from Bernard Frazier and one from Art Bergman. The first song is called Jagged One, which is an ode to Bergman\'s late wife, Sheri, who died unexpectedly in March of 2022. The second song is a classical piece written by Deborah Fialkovic, called Orange. The third song is by a local band called Orange Starr, which has just released a new EP.',NULL,NULL),(65497,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/09/Democracy Now - October 9, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-09 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 08:37:05',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(65499,158,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/rgcsxj/October_3_2023_Radical_Reverend_1_8jmt7.mp3','2023-10-09 17:23:15',143961989,'2023-12-01 08:11:04',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(65508,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/09