507648,'2023-11-29 11:13:05',NULL,'In this short speech, Lauren Stein, a long-time resident of Guelph, Israel, gives a rallying cry for her fellow citizens in Canada. She urges them to make today a day of love and unity. She tells them to reach out to people they haven\'t seen in a while, to talk to people who they don\'t usually agree with, and to visit their Jewish friends. She encourages them to show up at one of the local Jewish organizations and listen to what they have to say.',NULL,NULL),(66012,1627,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Jitterbuggin - October 14, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 10:52:07',NULL,'Welcome to the Jitterbagin\' show, a music show hosted by Adrian Jay. The show starts at midnight, and the DJ says he\'s set his time as midnight.\n\nHe says he sets his time according to the time he gets up. He tells us he\'ll be playing some songs that he has been promoting, like \"Daddy Long Legs\" and \"Savage Kicks Vol 2.\" He\'s also going to be playing a bunch of music that he doesn\'t know what to play. He wants to play music more than talk. He gives us a triple header: \"Let It Rock,\" \"Barrett Strong,\" and \"Money and Blues Brother.\" He also tells us that it\'s a 106-mile trip to Chicago to play the music.\n\nSo, don\'t worry about moving your dial, because it\'ll just scold you. The DJ also tells listeners that he and Adrian have been back in town for a while, so they\'re back on the air. The first mistake he made was playing \"College Girl,\" which he thinks is a new CD he burned onto the DJ\'s old car. He also says that he didn\'t have a good time playing college girl, though.',NULL,NULL),(66059,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/A Dog’s Breakfast - October 14, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 10:31:13',NULL,'The host of the \"Cyber-licious Gothic Castle\" on CFRU, the station\'s music program, welcomes listeners to the show and asks them to \"sleep into the cyberlicious gothic castle\" every Tuesday at midnight. He also tells them that they can \"experience the darker side\" of synth, \"outrun\" and \"ambient, dungeon, and cyberpunk\" while listening to the program. The guests include DJ Apostrophe, the founder of the International Institute of Critical Studies and Improvisers, and Diamond Schmidt, the director of the new ImprovLab building at the university.',NULL,NULL),(66060,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Beautiful Druid - October 14, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 10:08:47',NULL,'The show opens with a welcome from Alden Hadwen, the host of Beautiful Druid. He tells us that the show is being aired live from the university in Guelph, Canada.\n\nHe says he\'s glad to be a part of it. He introduces himself as Alden and says he will be the host for the show. He\'ll be playing songs that relate to houses and how people feel about them. For example, the first song he\'ll play is called \"The House Song\" by Peter Paul and Mary. The song goes something like this: \"Peter, Paul, and Mary\" refers to houses, and the second song he plays is called The Spirit of The West.\n\nThe first song is \"One Less Set of Feet,\" by Jim Croce. The second song is Willie Nelson\'s \"Essential Willie Nelson Album\" . The third song is by Alison Croce and \"Union Station\" referring to a ghost in a house. The fourth song is from Eric Bibb\'s short piece \"Church\" , which is a little slice of country music. The show ends with a song by Joshua Redmond.',NULL,NULL),(66070,257,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fynfsc/October_12_2023_Psychedelic_Stoner_Rockaou6l.mp3','2023-10-14 16:56:08',287962512,'2023-11-29 09:45:08',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66071,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/zcg5d9/October_13_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow8cauv.mp3','2023-10-14 16:57:16',287962512,'2023-11-29 09:27:07',NULL,'Ken Stauer joins Lydia to talk about the latest developments in sound recording. He explains that they are using a tape machine to record samples of music. There is no sound on the end of the machine, so there is no system noise, and there are no hiss, in case of a certain. They can make the music clear as possible, and that\'s why they only need two tracks to record the music. He says that the feeling that is everywhere, is actually the possible arrival of time. He then explains how they can use the technology to re-create the present tense and what it would mean to create a new beginning in the future',NULL,NULL),(66072,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Sound Magic - October 14, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 09:08:54',NULL,'The program opens with a description of Sound Magic, a three-hour program of classical music. The program is comprised of three main sections: 1) Classic Art Music, 2) Orchestral Music, and 3) Other Music.\n\nThe first section is devoted to classical music, and the second section consists of other music. Sound Magic kicks off with a piano concerto from Anton Rubinstein, one of the most important Russian composers of the nineteenth century. Rubinstein wrote symphonies and was the critic of Tchaikovskys piano concerto, which he completely trashes. He also wrote a few other piano concertos, including a work for the Scottish Symphony Orchestra. The second section has a recording of Marc-Andréi Hamelin playing the piano.\n\nThe third section introduces the entire Russian pianists, along with the other piano works. The fourth section introduces us to all the other musical developments that took place in the Russian territories during the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.',NULL,NULL),(66082,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Sound Magic - October 14, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 08:49:16',NULL,'The final piece of the program is a Russian composer named Nikolai Kapuskin. He was born in1937 and died as recently in 2020 . He had an eye-opener in his life because of his jazz sensibility. He did a lot of chamber music, mostly with a piano.\n\nThe piano is the instrument of the composer, so he had a very individual style. He is known for his chamber symphony Op 57 from 19. The conductor is Alek Skarnna, who is also the conductor of the chamber symphony from earlier in the program. The program ends with a volunteer at the university, a singer-songwriter named Lauren, who volunteers to play on the university\'s experimental music station.',NULL,NULL),(66083,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Sound Magic - October 14, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 08:27:05',NULL,'In this episode of Sound Magic, Michael Doleszell discusses the latest recording of the famous Russian Second Symphony by the Philadelphia Orchestra, conducted by Yannick Neshikenou. The symphony was composed in the early 1900s and has been played many times, but the recording is the most complete and complete recording to date. The Philadelphia Orchestra\'s music director, Janek Janek, has recorded the entire symphony, which is about an hour long and full of repetition. It is a masterpiece, and Doleschell raves about it all day.',NULL,NULL),(66093,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Bel Araby with CAWA - October 14, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 08:08:42',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66094,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Caribbean Anthology - October 14, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 07:06:13',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66104,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Caribbean Anthology - October 14, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 06:51:16',NULL,'In this interview with Darnay, Darnay speaks of the importance of unity in the music industry. He explains that he, like many other artists, has had personal 