he people he works for, and for the chance to perform at the Mermac every year. He\'s also happy to be a part of a big production called Queen. He tells us that he and his partner are going to be in town for three days. He hopes that everyone is enjoying the music that he has prepared for them, and he hopes that they\'re happy with it.',NULL,NULL),(66455,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/Tuesday at 5 - October 17, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 08:07:59',NULL,'This is the hour of the show where Mac Dee introduces himself and welcomes everyone to the show. He also introduces us to some of the other guests who are also on the show, including Jesse Cook, Melissa McClellan, and Bob Dylan.\n\nThe program starts with a history lesson on the War of 1812. In this chapter, we learn that Isaac Brock was killed by a cannonball at Queenston Heights during the battle on October 13th, 1812. John Macdonald, a lieutenant colonel in the York Militia, was also killed in the battle. We learn that John was a lawyer and that he had little military experience. We also learn that he was wounded in the back and died the next day',NULL,NULL),(66456,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/Down the Rabbit Hole - October 17, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 07:09:02',NULL,'In this program, the host tells his audience about his upcoming show at the underground music venue, Down the Rabbit hole. He describes the show as \"a crazy show\" ahead of him. He tells listeners that it\'s getting colder, and that he\'s worried about the ghosts haunting the audience.\n\nThe host says that he hopes everyone is doing well. He says he saw an art exhibit at the museum in Toronto that explores contemporary black life. He doesn\'t know enough words to describe what is there, but he thinks it is cool. One of the pieces in the exhibit is a collection of art by a man named Kenneth Montague. He calls it \"the Wedge Collection.\" The Wedge Collection is one of Canada\'s largest collections of contemporary art.\n\nIt explores different works \"that talk\" about contemporary African American life. The pieces include works by artists like Alice Coltrane, Pharoah Sander, Grace Jones and Sun Ra. The host says he knows a lot about these artists, but that he has no idea how to describe them. He plays some songs from each of these artists\' albums. He also says that they\'re all good. He ends the show by playing some tennis. He wants to make sure that everyone gets home safely.',NULL,NULL),(66466,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/Let’s Get Lost - October 17, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 06:46:47',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the Scandinavian band Grimsta, who are playing at the upcoming improv festival in New York City. The band has a new album out called Grimsta and they\'re playing a bunch of new music. They\'re also playing an old track by Molly O\'Brien from her last album. She\'ll be performing at the improv festival, which starts Friday night and runs through Saturday. The other performers include Vijay Iyer, Leo Smith, and Wada Leo.',NULL,NULL),(66467,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/New or Never - October 17, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 06:35:38',NULL,'This is the second track from the new album by Adrian Hoad Reddick. It is called \"New or Never\" and it is a meditation on the nature of time.\n\nIt begins with a scene in which a young man opens a mail box and finds a postcard addressed to his dead father. He reads the postcard and finds that the address is Julianne. He writes a letter to his father, saying that a strange man stopped him on the street recently and asked him if he had the wrong woman. He then walked away like \"a lonely ghost\". The next day he wakes up to find that his arms and legs are turned to \"old growth forest\" and