 quick rundown of the show. He\'s going to start off by playing a song called \"Soulful Gospel,\" which is a kind of sappy, bubblegum pop song from the early \'50s. Then he\'ll play \"Savage Kicks\" , which is another kind of rock \'n roll song. And finally, he\'s also going to play \"Back to Back\" .\n\nThis is a reference to the host\'s studio where he works, which can get pretty noisy if you\'re not careful. So he tries to keep things light and to play less. He also says that if anyone wants to check out his past shows, they can go to his website, cfu.com, and find out all his past performances. And if they want to listen to his other shows, he doesn\'t mind if they\'re on the same day as his show.\n\nSo long as they\'ve got the time and the energy to listen, he says. He gives us ten minutes, and then he goes on to say that there\'s some really good music on the show and that if you come out and hear it, you can have a good time.',NULL,NULL),(66873,30061,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/IF 2023 - October 21, 2023 at 05:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 05:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 15:07:36',NULL,'In this short program, the organizers of the International Festival of Improvisation, also known as IF 2023, tell us about some of the other performances they\'re bringing to the festival. The first one is a performance by Matilda, and it\'s co-presented by the Sonic Arts Centre at Queen University in Belfast. The second one is by Gyoza, which was originally performed at the CHAPA Experimental Music Festival in Singapore. The third performance is by Nico, the guys from Silence, and they\'ve also been invited to perform at the festival as well.',NULL,NULL),(66892,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/A Dog’s Breakfast - October 21, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 14:51:00',NULL,'The next week, a festival is going to take place in Guelph. It\'ll be called the International Festival of Improvised Art. It will be held in the new ImprovLab building at the International Institute of Critical Studies. The festival is free, but it\'s limited in size.',NULL,NULL),(66893,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Beautiful Druid - October 21, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 14:31:43',NULL,'The first song on the program is called \"The House Song\" and it\'s from Peter, Paul, and Mary\'s 1700 album. The second song is \"The Spirit of The West\" and the third song is about when someone is missing from the house.\n\nThe first songs are Jim Croce\'s \"One Less Set Of Footsteps\" and Willie Nelson\'s essential recording \"Hello Walls.\" The next song is Alison Krause\'s and Union Station\'s live album \"Disc One,\" and the last song is by Eric Biddle. The show ends with Joshua Redman\'s new recording \"Where We Are\" and \"I Left My Heart In San Francisco.\"',NULL,NULL),(66903,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Sound Magic - October 21, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 14:09:27',NULL,'In this week\'s Sound Magic program, Michael Dolesch discusses two new recordings: a new recording of a concerto by violinist Max Bruch and a recording by the Philadelphia Orchestra of the same concerto by another violinist named Randall Goosbye. The first recording is for Florence Price, and the second for Florence. The second recording will be released later in the fall.',NULL,NULL),(66913,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Sound Magic - October 21, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 13:52:08',NULL,'The program opens with a lecture on the composer Walter Braunfels, who was a member of the Essen Symphony. He is a Jewish man who was forced to live in a walled town called Theresienstade, which the Nazis planned to use as a concentration camp for Jews.\n\nAfter the war, he moved to a quiet place in Cologne, Germany, and continued to compose music. He was awarded the Order of the Arrow by the Emperor of Germany for his services to the German cause. In the late 50s and early 60s, he became the first person to hold the rank of Chancellor of the Emperor\'s German Empire. He played the piano in the royal court and became a well-known composer in Germany. He has been awarded many prizes for his work.',NULL,NULL),(66914,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Sound Magic - October 21, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 13:28:58',NULL,'In this program, Michael discusses the history of German composers and how they influenced Beethoven, Mozart, and Schubert. He discusses the first symphony written by a German composer, Fritz Folbach who lived from 1861 to 1940. The first symphony is a large scale work, with beautiful contrasts. The second symphony, written in 1908, is a late work influenced by Beethoven. The third symphony is the first recording of a work by a composer not in the catalogs at all, a composer named Max Reger. The work is for two pianos and it is a masterpiece.',NULL,NULL),(66924,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Bel Araby with CAWA - October 21, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 13:12:32',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66925,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Caribbean Anthology - October 21, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 12:47:39',NULL,'The show is a celebration of the 10th anniversary of the comedy festival. The Alzheimer\'s Society of Waterloo-Wellington is looking for music makers to help them create playlists for people with dementia. They\'re also looking for listeners to give them iPods. The listeners can donate money, gift cards, or iPods for the project. The program ends with a shout-out to everyone who has been supporting the festival.',NULL,NULL),(66935,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Caribbean Anthology - October 21, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 12:33:01',NULL,'The first half of the second half of this interview is with the founder of the Guelph Comedy Festival. The festival, which is a non-profit organization, is looking for ways to promote cultural events in the community.\n\nThe idea, according to the founder, is to find a venue that will allow such events. The first place to look for a venue is Royal City Studios in Guelph. The studio is a place where musicians, artists, and comedians can record their work and then perform it live. The organization also has a stage where artists can perform their work. The only problem is that the studio needs to raise enough money to keep going.\n\nThe founder says there are many people in the Guelph community who would like to see a place like this exist. What the studio was for the festival was to give everyone access to the related types of music. They brought a wide variety of music to the studio, including reggae, hip hop, dancehall, Soka, and dancehall. They also planned to do a Halloween event there, but now they\'re moving to another venue.',NULL,NULL),(66936,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Alternativa Latinoamericana - October 21, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-22 00:07:08',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(66946,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Alternativa Latinoamericana - October 21, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-22 02:06:59',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(66947,142,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Tiempo de Mujeres - October 21, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-22 02:07:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(66957,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Mach Vibe Radio - October 21, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 12:05:46',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66958,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Mach Vibe Radio - October 21, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 11:53:57',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66968,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/The Underground - October 22, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 11:25:22',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66969,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/The Underground - October 21, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 14:09:51',NULL,'The University of Guelph\'s news station, CFRU, has a spooky event planned for October 31. There will be free treats, trick-or-treating, and a costume contest. In addition, the station will be showing off its new production of \"The Dark Side of Sin,\" a horror film set in a gothic castle.\n\nThe University also has a great festival coming up called the Guelph Film Fest.',NULL,NULL),(67006,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Visions fugitives - October 22, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 10:53:34',NULL,'The narrator opens this show by introducing himself as \"Visions Zoom fugitives\" . He explains that he co-hosts the show with Fangwei, but the show is being recorded over different locations.\n\nThe narrator explains that this is because they haven\'t been able to record their show together. Each week they pick a number of music pieces to play for the audience, and the next week they choose a different piece of music based on the theme chosen the previous week . This is a music show, and it\'s called \"Axios and the Tortoise\" , which means \"Achilles and the tortoise\" in Greek. The show is set to run on October 8, 2023, and this is a brand new episode. Fangwei sent the narrator a list of music tracks and a specific script for the music tracks.\n\nThe music tracks are based on animals that go through a process called \"acedivation,\" which is basically a hibernation period. The animals featured in the music show are a salamander and a tortoise. The title of the music piece is \"Ants Achilles and The Tortoise,\" and it refers to the \"Paradox of Zeno,\" which says that Achilles can never overtake a tortoise in a race because',NULL,NULL),(67016,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Visions fugitives - October 22, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 10:29:13',NULL,'The show opens with Christopher Curry, who introduces himself as the host. He and Fangwei have been working on a script together, and he\'s decided to shift the focus of the show to the autumn season.\n\nHe notes that the heat wave has passed, and that the temperatures have returned to normal. In other words, the heat is gone, and the weather is cooler than it was in September. He\'s going to play some music from the fall, including a work by the Canadian composer, Alice Ping Yi-HO, who wrote a work called Woman Singular runs with Wolves, which was a big hit when it was first published in the mid-1990s. The music is performed by the percussionist Beverly Johnston, who also plays the part of the wolf.\n\nThe show has doubled in size in the past few years, and it\'s time to move up to 51, so that it\'ll be more like the seasons. There\'s also an album in the collection, called Together, by Julian Bream, and John Williams, who both play classical guitar.',NULL,NULL),(67017,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - October 22, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-08 14:49:54',NULL,'The Cuckoo\'s Bananas hosts a lunchtime program called \"The Variety Hour\" in which they play music from various sources. The program starts with a party song about food, followed by a party classic, \"Ice Cream and Cake,\" which is a song about cake.','Cuckoo Bananas Variety Hour on CFRU FM in Guelph, Canada, is a weekly radio show. The program is hosted by DJ Tamil. This week\'s show includes a rap song about food and a party tune about food.','Cuckoo Bananas Variety Hour (Radio Show)'),(67027,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Clan Na Gael - October 22, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 10:12:08',NULL,'The next song on the bill is a bartom MacNail song from a Canadian band called Bartom McNails. Next up is a song called \"Great Big C\" from a Road Rage CD. The band then plays a mummer song from Ireland, a dance song from Scotland, and a song by an American singer named Esalen Deison. The song is called \"The Dance You Choose\" and is a piece of music from her CD. Next, the band plays a song from Patty Gordon from her \"20 Golden Irish Ballad\" CD. It is a bit of a mouthful, but it\'s true. Next is another song from the Canadian band \"Glass Tiger\" who are just getting inducted into the Hall of Fame.\n\nFinally, they play a song that they found in the trash bin from a station years ago. The tune is \"Biscuity Star\" and they play some bagpipes. They play another song by a Newfoundland musician named Rong Lidster. He finds a lot of songs that are sad and happy. He says that the Celts are a \"race where all wars are happy\" and all the sad songs are sad',NULL,NULL),(67037,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Seems Like Old Times - October 22, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 09:53:25',NULL,'This is the second hour of the program. It\'s the first half of the show and it\'s all about music from the 30s and 40s. It starts off with Gunsmoke and ends with a song called \"The Western Action\" from Gunsmoke. Then it goes on to the 40s and 50s with \"Sweet Home Alabama\" and \"The Miss.\" Then it gets back to the 60s and 70s with the Dean Martin Quartet and \"Dean Martin, Cab Calloway\" and more. The program ends with the second song from the program, \"The Tatum for You\" from March 21, 1938.',NULL,NULL),(67038,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Clan Na Gael - October 22, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 09:10:10',NULL,'This is the first song in the program, and it\'s called \"The Storm\" by the narrator. The song is about a storm that\'s about to hit the coast of Nova Scotia, and the narrator has decided to sing it. He says the storm is called Babette, which means \"beyond the shelter\" . The narrator tells us that this song was written by a guy named Robbie Smith, who used to live in Nova Scotia with his aunt and uncle.\n\nHe used to play music and make a lot of money writing songs. He\'s also a bit of a folk legend, because he played in a band named Killik and wrote songs like \"I Have the Condor\" and \"The Fury Brothers\" , which are about whales. He also plays a song called Maggie, which is actually a Canadian song. It was originally a poem written by an English teacher in the 19 century.\n\nThe teacher fell for Maggie and wrote a poem called Nora, which was later used by a musician named Nora Creed, who wrote a version of the song called \"Nora.\" The narrator also tells us about the \"Stormy Weather Boys,\" a collection of songs by Helen Creighton. Helen was a friend of the narrator\'s',NULL,NULL),(67048,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Seems Like Old Times - October 22, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 08:55:44',NULL,'Kitty asks Matt if there is anything he can do to help her. He says he understands, but that he hasn\'t been feeling well all week.\n\nHe tells her that life is never all good. He also says that he has a job more than a job and that sometimes you get to wonder what\'s going on. He asks her if she knows about the eviction of the Blakes. She says she does, and then she tells him to let her know if he finds out about it. She tells him that she always thought he was on his way to the jail, but he tells her he stopped by to check on the family. He told her that they were supposed to have vacated by sundown. He said that he would prefer to discuss business elsewhere than at the presence of the eviction.\n\nHe apologizes to Kitty, and says that Finnegan should have thrown some water on her. Kitty says that she doesn\'t think he should apologize, and that he had it coming, too. He will do everything he could to hurt her now. He may also take it on the other family, too, she says. He plans to see her later. Matt reminds her that he saved her life, and she reminds him that',NULL,NULL),(67049,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/La Buena Onda - October 22, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-22 22:07:16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67058,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/hdk5td/October_22_2023_Across_the_Universebo1a5.mp3','2023-10-23 00:03:04',431961989,'2023-11-21 23:04:53',NULL,'',NULL,'The 50th anniversary of hip hop in Canada is on CIUT 99.5 — and the 50th-anniversary event'),(67059,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/veez37/Karibuni_Oct_22-2023bu5xm.mp3','2023-10-23 04:08:46',287962512,'2023-11-21 22:52:16',NULL,'The band\'s new album, called Migration, will be released on November 1, and they\'re planning a party in celebration of it. The band has been hard at work on the album and has been writing new songs for the last year or so.\n\nThey\'re also going to perform some of the songs in the album, which is titled \"Migration.\" The band also has a new track coming out from another artist named Adam Solomon, who has released an album called Bocati, which they\'ll play during the show. They also have a new song coming out that they\'ve never played before. They don\'t know which song it is yet, but they plan to play it anyway because they want people to come out and see the new music. The show will be on December 2, and the band will be releasing the new album the following December.',NULL,NULL),(67061,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/hst3ym/October_20_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow95bk3.mp3','2023-10-22 23:17:39',287962512,'2023-11-21 22:26:03',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67062,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Wind-Down - October 22, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 08:30:59',NULL,'The program starts off with Say She Humans with their song \"Astral Plain\" from their latest album \"Silver\". It\'s followed by Bibio with \"A Matter of Fact\", Teen Ravine with \"Friend of a Friend\", Little Dragon with \"Lily\'s Call\" from \"Slugs of Love\", Kaja Bone with her single \"For You\", Men i Trust with \"Serendipity of Water\", La Force with \"Exoskeleton\", Abby Sage with \"Milk\", and Elisa P with \"Time After Time\" from her \"Anuktituk\" set. After the program ends, the program goes to \"Playlux\" on the program and then to \"Mirror Mirror\" with \"Imaginary Friend\" and \"Elise P\" on \"Time after Time\" . And then it\'s time to go home.',NULL,NULL),(67063,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/La Buena Onda - October 22, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-23 10:07:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67064,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Zombie Jamboree - October 22, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 08:08:53',NULL,'On the second day of the festival, Bruce tells the audience that they can expect to hear music all day. As the festival draws to a close, the audience can still hear the music and enjoy the fall colors. Bruce explains that the festival is a celebration of fall and that it is a festival of color. He tells the crowd that they should stick around for the second hour because there is still time to dance.',NULL,NULL),(67065,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Zombie Jamboree - October 22, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 07:51:52',NULL,'Bruce, the tour guide for the Toronto Zombie Jamboree, tells the audience that they are in the middle of fall colors. He tells them that two groups have been performing together. They are called Uh-Huh and Lamping, and they seem to come from a place called Lamping. He plays a song called Reciprocat and follows it with After The Sun Sets. He also tells them they are on a local radio station, CFRU 99.3, and that they all go by the name of Tarafta-Haiduk. They perform Bride in a red dress. For the other two groups, he plays some authentic flamenco and plays it for them.\n\nIt is called Alegria and it is a song by Trini de La ila and Pete Townsend. They also play a tribute to fall colorama with Bell and his disappointment with red leaves. They were preceded by a subsonic by Bruce who performs performative. So they are nearing the end of the first hour of their festival of fall colour but you can still keep on dancing.',NULL,NULL),(67066,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Through the Looking Glass - October 22, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 07:14:35',NULL,'The first song on tonight\'s program is from a band called Squids from Canada. The second song is from the latest version of the swing band Stylin A Prophrine, which is performed by Emily Roald Deggers, a burlesque performer who came from Vancouver. Emily is the one who met the original members of the band, the \"Sazeracs,\" at a Berlin burlesque festival. She is also the person who hosts burlesque shows in her hometown of Vancouver.',NULL,NULL),(67067,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/This Night Wounds Time - October 23, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 06:49:07',NULL,'This is a short program from the CFRU radio program \"Cfru 93.3\" about the death of the late artist Carla Blay. The program begins with a tribute to Blay and a song from her album, \"Carla Blay Live.\" The program ends with a track from the same album, called \"Blunt Object.\n\n\" Blay grew up in a religious family, and this next track suggests that she is influenced by the \"Gospel music\" of her youth. The next track on the program is a cover of Sextet, a Blay album released in 1987. The program concludes with an album called \"The Carla blay big band goes to church.\" This album is \"not more Gospel infused material,\" but rather it is a reference to \"the fact\" that it was actually recorded.',NULL,NULL),(67068,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/This Night Wounds Time - October 23, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 06:38:11',NULL,'The narrator opens the show by introducing us to the jazz composer, the late Carla Blay. Blay died at the age of 87, and she was a role model of independent music.\n\nShe was a jazz composer who created a body of work that was emotional, intellectual, and musical. Her name is Lovella Borg, and though she used her stage name, she was actually born Lovella Anderson. Her mother died when she was eight years old, and her father was a musician. She played and sang in church as a child, but she was self taught on piano. She heard Lionel Hampton\'s Lionel Hampton and was blown away by it. She married the Canadian musician Paul Blay in 1957, and their marriage yielded the jazz label Escalator Over The Hill and a distribution service for experimental music',NULL,NULL),(67069,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Backtracks - October 22, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 06:12:58',NULL,'The show opens with a track from the first album of singer songwriter Donovan, \"Colors.\" The theme for the show is \"linchpin\" . The songs are all \"intangible\" , so they\'re all about the theme. The first track is from Jesse Collin, the former lead singer of Youngbloods. The second track is a live version of the song, \"Blue on Blue.\" The third track is an early demo from Joni. The fourth track is one from a Canadian band called Mother Tucker\' Yellow Duck. The fifth track is \"True Blue\" from a singer songwriter named Elza. She\'s on her way there too.',NULL,NULL),(67070,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/This Night Wounds Time - October 22, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 05:53:11',NULL,'This is another new episode for the show. It\'s a \"rebroadcast\" of the previous episode. It doesn\'t have the latest edition of the \"Geographic Spotlight\" series, but it does have some music. The music for tonight is a little too \"off-center\" . The show starts with some music from Saint Abdullah and his band, \"Saint-Abdullah & Iomak.\" The music is from their new album, \"Chasing Stateless,\" which is on a label called \"Planet Mu MU Records.\" The name of the album is a good thing, but the band\'s name is not. Then they hear some more music from James Brandon Lewis\' \"World Turned Into Light,\" a collection of contemporary art songs.\n\nThe songs are from the 21st century, and the lyrics are from Leonard Cohen. The lyrics come from \"EJP,\" a song by the poet. The song is from \"Dancing With Love,\" a release by the singer/songwriter Afarin Mansuri. All of the albums featured on the show are new releases from the new batch of students at the university. This is a track called \"Epilogue Resilience.\" The show is now on CFRU 93.3 in Guelph, and',NULL,NULL),(67080,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 23, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 05:09:11',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67081,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Here Today - October 23, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-07 06:27:31',NULL,'The host of the Here Today show, Aaron, tells his listeners about some of the music he\'s been listening to recently. First up is the band Backstab, whose new album is called This Burning House. The band is from Toronto, and the members of the band said, \"Well, is it a full-length or an EP?\" Aaron says that he thinks anything from four songs to an entire album. Next up is James Clark, the founder of James Clark Institutes, who\'s going to be on the show in November, and he\'ll be releasing an EP called Rewind Forward. He\'ll have four tracks on it, including a song by Paul McCartney, who wrote it and produced it. And then there\'s a song called Pet Sematary by the band Church of Trees. It\'ll come out on an upcoming album, Transience, in 2024. Aaron says he\'d like to invite Bernard to play the show, so he could have him take over the role of host. Before that happens, Aaron mentions a singer named Debra Fyak, who is from England. She\'s from the Ottawa valley area in Ontario, and Aaron plays her every week. And if you want to support artists',NULL,'The host of Here Today tells us what he\'s been listening to recently '),(67091,206,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/pjx25z/October_21st_2023_The_Minx_Sessions68zub.mp3','2023-10-23 14:52:26',287962512,'2023-11-21 22:05:17',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67092,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/v88bxs/October_20_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillowbgmyw.mp3','2023-10-23 15:03:55',287962512,'2023-11-21 21:45:52',NULL,'The next morning, the narrator of this story goes to a party. He\'s dressed in black. He doesn\'t know that he\'s there to be a shadow. He just wants to hang out. It\'s the same party every year.',NULL,NULL),(67093,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 23, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-09 05:04:04',NULL,'The narrator of this story is a young man named Charlie. He\'s an orphan who grew up in a small town in Iowa. He went to college in Nebraska and now lives in the town of Prairie du Chien. He has a wife named Becky who is a real estate agent. He and his wife get married on the first day of every month. The narrator is a great guy. He goes to the movies, plays the piano, and generally has a good time.',NULL,'Charlie is an orphan in Iowa. He lives in Prairie du Chien. He gets married on the first day of every month '),(67094,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 23, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-09 04:50:56',NULL,'This week\'s edition of the \"Breezy Breakfast\" takes place in the House of Commons in Ottawa. The host welcomes Longfeld, a Member of Parliament from Guelph, who is visiting from the city. Longfeld gives an update on the political situation in Canada. He says that since the House rose in June, there has been a new crisis every week. This week, the crisis has been \"the rise of right wing authoritarianism\" and the \"treachery of the Hamas\" and \"the breakdown of governance\" . He also says that there are live discussions about how Parliament works in Canada',NULL,'The \"Breezy Breakfast\" in the House of Commons (11 minute read)'),(67104,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Democracy Now - October 23, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 04:50:58',NULL,'The United Nations calls for an immediate cease-fire in the Gaza Strip, where more than 5,000 people have been killed and more than 14,000 injured in the past 17 days. Two humanitarian aid convoys have started trickling into the Strip, but more aid is needed. The co-founder and editor of the Gaza-based company AIM Media, Roshti Suraj, has been killed by an Israeli strike. At least 23 other journalists have also been killed since Israel launched its offensive in mid-October. The United Nation\'s UNRWA agency reports 29 staff members of the organization have been murdered in the last two weeks.',NULL,NULL),(67105,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Worst Responders - October 23, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 04:33:23',NULL,'The show starts off with a discussion between two students, Charissa and Renee. They\'re discussing the latest developments in the world of social media. The students are discussing the state of the world and what people are doing on the web. Charissa says that he and the other students are talking about problems people are having on social media and giving them advice and hot takes.\n\nThis is an improvised comedy show, which is why the students don\'t talk about the opinions of the professors at the university. We learn that the university is in mid-October, which means that people are in their mid-thirties. It is also the time of year when people start getting depressed. The two students explain that they\'re talking about the same topics. The student says that when he\'s talking to the other student, he and she are making hard eye contact and making little mistakes.\n\nThey talk about how the two of them are using the same technology, like chat, and how they can\'t really type into the search engines. They also discuss the upcoming reading week at their university. It\'ll be in October, which will mean that students won\'t have to go to class during the holidays.',NULL,NULL),(67115,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/CFRU Playlist - October 23, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-23 20:06:23',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67125,216,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/cx532a/RAW102023.mp3','2023-10-23 20:50:51',287962512,'2023-11-21 21:26:38',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67126,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - October 23, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 04:14:23',NULL,'In this chapter, we\'ll look at progressive and alternative forms of music that exist outside of Canada. We\'ll also pay tribute to the Indigenous communities that live on Turo Island, and to the Black community that has contributed to the current wave of experimental music.\n\nWe start off with prog music from the North Carolina singer-songwriter, Jennifer Reiser. Then we hear new tracks from Beverly and Hylios and another from Lawrence Ann. Finally, we hear a track called Finally from another artist named Ramshi. We head back in time to the beginning of the session, where we hear grime from Vancouver, Beverly\'s new album, and his own new album. We then hear some new tracks by Helios, a new project from Kenneth, and a new track by LawrenceAnn.',NULL,NULL),(67136,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/to know the land - October 23, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-30 15:40:24',NULL,'The narrator continues his discussion of the walnut maggot, regalitas sua virescens, by explaining that the walnut husk pupa is a small, white, transparent maggot that emerges from the husks in mid-July. The pupa lasts for about a month and then the adults emerge. The narrator explains that females usually emerge in mid July and males emerge in late July. When the females emerge, they eat the insects that feed on them, and the females then mate with the males. The males then mate again and hatch their eggs.',NULL,'The regalitas sua virescens husk pupa is a white maggot that emerges from the'),(67137,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Blues Around the Block - October 23, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 03:06:54',NULL,'Blues Around the block is back and this time it\'s hosted by David Gogo. He gives us a shout-out to the band that\'s been playing in the background, the Yawn-Spear-Band. The Yawn Spear-Band is the band playing the blues.',NULL,NULL),(67138,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Blues Around the Block - October 23, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 06:06:29',NULL,'Mac Dee is a new guy on the block. He\'s got his own little show called \"Blues Around the Block\" and he\'s a musician. He starts off by thanking everyone for tuning in. He also gives a little rundown of what\'s been going on with the show.',NULL,NULL),(67139,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Big Sis Radio - October 23, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 02:30:23',NULL,'The crew is excited to kick off their show with some new music from Winnipeg. This time it\'s from a band called The Drums, who\'s got a new track called \"Comedy by Sasha Kaye\" for the show.\n\nThen they hear two tracks from Johnny, the latest from the drums. The first track on Johnny is \"I\'m still scared and i select\" and the second track is \"Inhospitable\" and \"So are we\" from Mitzki. The third track is called \"I can\'t find anyone by ecstasy\" and they also hear two songs off the drums latest record, \"I am Still Scared and i Select\". The crew also hears a song from Hemlock called \"Carriage\" and a song called \"A Little History\" from the band Holorado, who released their first album in a bag and came out with a track called Juliet that reached gold status.\n\nThis is a big deal because the band was the first band to play a concert in a vinyl format and it was a big hit. So the crew went to a store called Elsie\'s to get two copies of Juliet. And then Meno, the lead singer of Holorado came in to chat with the crew. He',NULL,NULL),(67149,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/The Deep House Project - October 23, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-31 05:10:19',NULL,'In this episode of the Deep House project, host Scott Brown and his crew set out to raise money for Silence Sounds, a local organization dedicated to preserving the arts in the community. They invite listeners to pledge $10 a month to the organization for a year. Scott introduces them to the program, which runs every Tuesday at 8pm on the CFRU 93.3 FM station. The program begins with a dance track by a German artist named Levenmankind. The song begins by saying, \"It\'s not about you, and me, so hold on, wait for a day /To feel out where its gonna be.\" The song goes on to say, \"The luck is with Me, the world still stops hidden, I still breathe there\'s something to your eyes / Oh no I know it\'s for so long.\" The artist then says, \"I\'ve got to get you up and move on.\" He tells the listeners that he has a crush on them and he wants to show them how much he wants them to love him. The music starts off with a remix of Milk & Bones\' \"P-Back\" by Blue Hawaii, and then the band Moose and The Scarf comes out with their song \"Won\'t',NULL,'Deep House project host Scott Brown pledges $10 a month to Silence Sounds, a local arts organization'),(67150,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Ripcord Radio - October 23, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 02:10:27',NULL,'The show starts off with a bunch of music from the past. It\'s mostly from bands that once played in the same city. The first song is from a band called MFD, who played in Washington, DC in the late \'80s. Next, it\'s from the band Government Issue, who disbanded in 1989.\n\nThe band\'s last song was \"I See Your Face On Rainy Days\" from their 2006 album. The band also released an EP called Storm in the fall of last year. The EP was produced by Tom Lyle, who was a member of Government Issue. The other songs are from bands like the Jaw Box, Wasted Age, Goat Boy, Drunk, and the Tarlex.\n\nThe next song is a demo from a compilation called Invading The Border, which was released in August. The third song is an album called Across the Pond, which came out in August of this year. Finally, the fourth song is the song from a 1981 compilation called OY Chart. Vol. 2. It comes from London. The song comes from Infaryt, who recently played a show in Guelph, Ont., with Nice and the Essential Letdowns. The show closes with some music from Jesus and',NULL,NULL),(67160,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Back in the USSR - October 23, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 01:46:38',NULL,'In this program, Seigfried discusses the situation in the Middle East and the recent events in the Gaza Strip. He has been a frequent guest on the program and he explains that he has covered the situation many times, but he feels that he is not very well-informed about the current situation. He turns to some prominent commentators, including Zoe Prashad, Alexander Crowder, and Vijay Prasad, to give an overview of the current events.\n\nHe explains that the conflict in Gaza has been going on for 90 years, and that it is not just about the conflict between Israel and the Palestinians, but also about the situation between the Muslims and Christians in the region. It goes back to the expulsion of the Muslims from their homes in the Ottoman Empire and the subsequent dispossession by European powers. It has been this way for at least 70 years.',NULL,NULL),(67161,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Rainbow Country - October 24, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 01:27:43',NULL,'This is the second episode of Rainbow Country, a Canadian-based gay radio show produced by and hosted by Mark Tara. The first episode featured a conversation between Alexander McGregor, a British filmmaker, and Denny Torrey, a New York Times bestselling author. This second episode features music from independent artists, LGBT artists, and voices that we come to know, and love, in classic disco. On this episode, Denny and Mary-John discuss the new film The Latent, a horror film about a lonely drifter who arrives at the door of a cabin.\n\nIn addition, they discuss Patrick Horrigan\'s novel, American Scholar, about a man driven by love, but afraid of knowing the truth about his past and present loves. In this chapter, they also discuss James Fitzgerald\'s collection of his records, papers, and other things, which he kept in his spare room. All of this material belonged to him.',NULL,NULL),(67172,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Rainbow Country - October 24, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 01:05:34',NULL,'In this first part of the show, the host, Mark Tara, describes the music that he is bringing to listeners. He says that he hopes that listeners stay with him and listen to the music, because he wants them to be able to experience the music in his house. He also tells listeners that the show is coming to an end and asks them to follow him on social media to keep up with the latest news.',NULL,NULL),(67182,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ztigut/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Oct_25_2023_podcast69weg.mp3','2023-10-24 09:43:29',286504750,'2023-11-21 21:07:31',NULL,'In this chapter, we find out that we\'re going to need to raise a ton of money in order to continue to be a credible news organization. So, we\'ve got to figure out how to get people to donate to our cause. One of the ways to do that is to find out what kinds of things people want to hear. And that\'s what we did. We found out that the most popular songs in the audience were all about fear, revenge, anger, and intolerance . So maybe we\'ll be able to get more listeners to donate if we focus on those things.',NULL,NULL),(67192,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/CFRU Playlist - October 24, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 06:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-24 12:06:31',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67202,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 24, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 00:47:24',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67212,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Solipsistic Retreat - October 24, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 00:31:14',NULL,'The first song that pops into your head is from Temple Inay. The second song is from Doom 64. The third is from Roush by the Fall. The fourth is from Solops Aestic Retreat. The fifth is from Crab.',NULL,NULL),(67213,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Solipsistic Retreat - October 24, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 00:11:20',NULL,'This is the first of a series of two half-hour segments in which the Solipsistics, a band of underground musicians, present their live performances. The first half of the program is devoted to discussing the music that the band is playing, which includes songs by Mondo Mondo, Animal Collective, and three songs by Negative Approach.\n\nThe second half is dedicated to the music of Death Grips, including songs from their latest album, Total Recall, and their seven-inch ten-song EP. The audience is then introduced to the host of the show, Nicole Ferrero. She is a student at the University of Guelph and has not been able to participate in the recent season of the CFRU show because she was out of town for a long time and she is in her fourth year of college. She says that her favorite song from the show is \"Free Heatwave,\" which she has sent to many people. She also mentions that she saw Death Grip Live in Toronto two weeks ago. She describes the line for the show and how she was pushed into the front of the first row. The show was described as \"ten out of ten\" by the host. He adds that it was a \"great experience\" to see Death Grip',NULL,NULL),(67223,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Bridging The Social Distance - October 24, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-22 23:07:44',NULL,'This program is produced by Jenny Mitchell, a social worker at the University of Guelph. She has started the program in response to a pandemic, and she continues it as a means to connect with her community. Today\'s guest is Lillian, a long-term resident at Riverside Glen. Lillian has been there for two years, and her husband for three years. Lillian says that she misses her husband so much that she had to move out of her husband\'s room. She says that with her husband, she has no problem, but that she has had a few visitors, including Pearl, who has come to stay with her.\n\nThen, her husband had a stroke, and now has dementia. Lillian tells Jenny that her last guest had aphasia from the stroke. She explains that she never needs to apologize for her voice, because she has a variety of experiences and voices. Jenny says that this is very sweet that she and her family have had to deal with hardship, and that they have been very kind to each other.',NULL,NULL),(67224,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Democracy Now - October 24, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 22:47:15',NULL,'As the number of dead in the 18-day Israel-Hamas conflict in the Gaza Strip continues to rise, the situation in the war-ravaged territory is becoming even worse. An official from the United Nations says nearly 42 percent of the housing stock in Gaza has been destroyed or damaged, and the only source of fuel for many of the health centers is running out. Meanwhile, Israel has been unable to bring in enough humanitarian aid to alleviate the suffering of the people of the blockaded territory. In response, Hamas has agreed to release two elderly Israeli civilians, Yoavit and Nurit Cooper, who were held hostage by the Islamic militant group.',NULL,NULL),(67234,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - October 24, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 22:26:49',NULL,'This is a very brief introduction to the various acts that we\'re going to hear here. The first act is from the rock band Double Live, who released their first album in 1997.\n\nThe second act is by English experimental rockers Radiohead from their fourth album, Kid A, released in 2000. The third act is a Canadian band called Fur Trade, whose song is called \"Signature Moves\" from their latest release, Dark Celebration. The fourth act is also from a South Korean rock band called Walking After You. The fifth act is an English band called Radiohead, who\'s got a song called \"Morning Bell\" off of their 2000 album Kid A.',NULL,NULL),(67