film called Never Say Never again. Then there\'s also a tribute to John Williams, who wrote the score for both of these films.',NULL,NULL),(67246,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/A Multilingual Affair - October 24, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 12:54:05',NULL,'This is the first part of a two-part interview with Teta Chiese, a singer and a music producer who is a member of the Underground Railroad. She is also known as the Underground Man and she is a great advocate of women\'s rights. She speaks in both English and Spanish. She says that she wants people to believe that no matter what happens in their lives, they can always rise above their circumstances. She encourages people to be strong and courageous even in the face of adversity.',NULL,NULL),(67256,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Tuesday at 5 - October 24, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 12:38:25',NULL,'Mac Dee hosts the show and introduces the guests. The first guest is Joey Wright, who is known for his work on R&B and soul. The next guest is Orchestra Beobar, a band from Dakar, Senegal. The group is made up of a singer, two guitarists, a drummer, a congas player, and a bass player.\n\nThey have been together since 1970. The group has released 20 albums and won two awards at the 2003 3 World Music awards. The band has continued to tour and has released several studio albums. The last guest is Colin Colburn, who has released his latest work Fearing The Unconquered Past. Stephen Fearing has also released a work called The Ballad of Julian Taylor. Mac Dee then takes us on a tour of Canada.',NULL,NULL),(67257,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Down the Rabbit Hole - October 24, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 12:27:38',NULL,'The next song is called \"Down the Rabbit Hole\" and it\'ll be a song from the album \"Places and Spaces\" by Harvey Mason.\n\nThe narrator says that the song is \"one of my favorites\" and that it\'s very \"vibratory\" . He goes on to say that the album is a \"daytime album\" and has a drummer named Harvey Mason playing on it. He also mentions that the singer \"Kim Jong Mi\" is one of his favorite artists and that he\'s been reading about her in a book called \"Crying in the H Mart\" , which is about a woman named Kim Jong Mi\'s mother and her aunt who used to listen very much to her. The song \"Kim Mi\" reminds the narrator of Kim\'s mom and aunt and how they used to \"listen to\" her all the time and now they\'re all listening to her music together.\n\nThey also have a Brazilian artist named Valle and a guitar player named Jeff Parker. They\'re going to go listen to the last song, \"Go Away,\" which is a song about a guy named \"Jeff Parker\" who plays drums. He says that this song is very \"fun to play on',NULL,NULL),(67267,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Let’s Get Lost - October 24, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 12:14:02',NULL,'This week\'s program begins with a description of the program. The program is a mixture of jazz and contemporary music. It begins with an introduction by Scott, who explains that the program is all about listening to music that he loves. The music featured on the program varies from genre to genre. For example, we hear music from Morris Luca, who has been playing with Sam Shalab for many years.\n\nHis latest solo album is called Moonshine. Also featured on this program is the IPA band, which is based in Scandinavia. They are led by Magnus Brunh and his wife Atle Nemo, who are songwriters and musicians. They have a trumpet player named Ingrid Hulker Flauten on their latest album, Grimsta. The band also includes Matthias Stahl on soprano sax. They play a song called New Coming from the album The Sixth Decade From Paris to Paris, which describes the coming of new things in the contemporary world. We also hear a track called Burned Gray from the CD of the same name by Jamie Branch, who passed away earlier in the year. We hear from Peripheral Vision, a band based in Toronto, who have released their second live album, We\'ve got Nothing. They also play the track The Mask Has become the',NULL,NULL),(67268,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/New or Never - October 24, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 12:02:45',NULL,'The show starts off with a bunch of new music, including Corinne Bailey Ray\'s fourth studio album, Black Rainbows, which is full of unexpected sounds. The first song is a prayer. The second is a punk rock song called Need I am Adrian, Hoad Reddick, and I have twelve friends. The third is a folk song called The Spell, a Prayer. The fourth is a new song by Corinne, called Obar Desoir. The fifth is a song by Drew, a member of the Broken Social Scene, who is also on his new album.',NULL,NULL),(67278,280,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/wmahrc/Hungary.mp3','2023-10-25 02:01:00',22590372,'2023-11-18 11:51:51',NULL,'Seth Martosh is the host of the show \"From Abroad\" at the University Of Toronto. He and his co-host, Alex Stroxel, travel around the world to visit students, professors, and musicians.\n\nThis week\'s guest is Dorothy Kiss, a student at the university from Hungary. She is a world champion in the Kung Fu art form. They talk about her goal setting, her professional and academic life, and her interest in the field of outer space architecture, among other things. Seth tells us that he and his friend, Alex, went to Budapest, Hungary, to build a wooden UFO for a builder\'s summit. They met many people from all over the world, including people from the United Kingdom, Brazil, and Hong Kong. Seth says that his upbringing was international, and that prepared him to study abroad in Canada. He also tells us about his friend Amun, who is studying architecture,environmental studies, and visual studies at the U of T. He says that since he was 12, he has been fascinated with the coordinate system.',NULL,NULL),(67279,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Let’s Get Lost - October 24, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 11:35:14',NULL,'Josh Cole and his crew are back on the program again, this time to talk about Kind Mine, an album by the band. They\'ve been hearing a lot of music from this program, but they\'ve also heard that the band is going to be touring the country next month. So, they\'re back to talking about music again. The program also has some news about organ donation, which is a great opportunity for people to save a huge number of lives. It\'s also a great time to donate tissue for future generations. The show starts off by playing a song from Panda Bear\'s Reset In Dub album.\n\nIt turns out that the song is called Getting To The Point Dub. Then they hear a bunch of other tracks from that album, including Dubmatics, International Dub, Audrey Ochoa, The Con Artist, Apollo Suns, Amonnaut, Hole In The Ground, Mocha Only, Mocha Alone, All Bones, Honest Proposal, and Worm Worms.',NULL,NULL),(67280,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Humanoid Radio - October 24, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 11:24:38',NULL,'The Humanoid Radio crew plays a bunch of new music this evening. We\'re starting with a track called Source of Denial, which sounds like it\'s from a movie about a guy who\'s just trying to get to the bottom of a big, bad existential crisis.\n\nThen we hear a bunch more new stuff: Babe Terror, Igeoma, the Syndicate, and I, Weird Al, a remix of WYLTK\'s EP, and a song called Bata Bing. You can listen to all of these new tracks by going to HumanoidRadio.com. The show starts off with a short overview of the latest music available on the radio. It sounds like aliens are using the radio to communicate with each other. The key is to use the technology to make contac