 one of the tracks from a new',NULL,'The Underground Man Listens to Some of His Favorite Releases '),(67344,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/The Stillness & The Dancing - October 25, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-07 14:43:46',NULL,'The Stillness and the Dancing begins with a spooky music track. The music is from Caixin, a Japanese label. The theme is \"a somewhat spectral theme\" . The release is called \"If only you knew what you claimed to\" and the music is by Richard Skelton, an artist who has spent much of his career creating ambient and lo-fi music.',NULL,'The Stillness and the Dancing (Sponsor), a new Japanese release by Richard Skelton '),(67346,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/y678iv/DrMouth_CIUTshow_oct24_fullshow.mp3','2023-10-25 17:23:52',287154368,'2023-11-18 10:13:41',NULL,'Dr. Mouse and his band get ready to head out for lunch, and Dr. Mice is psyched to be on board. He\'s impressed with how progressive and loud the band is. They\'ve heard a lot of prog from the past, and now they\'re psyched to hear some new stuff. They hear some of the latest music from a band called Nash the Slash, and they\'ll be playing some of their stuff at a Halloween party the next week.\n\nThis is cool, because this is the time of year when you\'re really into music. The band also plays some of James Brown\'s \"Funk Power,\" which is one of the most important songs in rock. They also play a song called \"Soul Motivators,\" which sounds like it was written by a guy named Bobby Bird.',NULL,NULL),(67354,195,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/g8rikh/Dementia13RadioShow_23_10_24.mp3','2023-10-25 15:41:01',287962512,'2023-11-18 10:01:45',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the character of the narrator, who is described as \"not a good girl\" . The narrator describes the girl as being a \"not-a-good\" person, who \"is not a good\" girl. He compares her to a girl who is not good, but not a bad girl.',NULL,NULL),(67356,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - October 25, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 09:50:22',NULL,'This is a short program of the music program on CFRU 93.2 FM. It\'s called \"We Know Some Stuff.\" This program is all about science and technology. It starts off with a little history lesson about how life on earth was very different than it is today. It was one time that civilization gave life to the world, and then it was destroyed. The program ends with a discussion about bread.\n\nThis is about how bread is a universal thing, and all different regions of the world have different bread. The bread from India is different from the bread from the West, and so on. The only difference is that it\'s more delicate. The whole thing is that the food industry works on people\'s preferences, so it makes sense that they\'re going to make the best bread possible.',NULL,NULL),(67357,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/Democracy Now - October 25, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 09:37:15',NULL,'The war in the Gaza Strip continues. The death toll is now 6,500, and the number of people displaced has reached 1.4 million, according to the United Nations. Israel\'s army chief has said it is ready for ground attack. The U-S has sent military officials to Washington.',NULL,NULL),(67360,158,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/gqubcb/radical_rev_11am_24th_oct7jtz1.mp3','2023-10-25 18:48:39',143961989,'2023-11-18 09:28:18',NULL,'The Radical Reverend hosts a conversation with Ren Jansen, president of the Ontario English Catholic teachers\' union, and Yvonne Runstetter, the union\'s assistant vice president. Ren tells the Radical Reverend that the government has wasted a year negotiating with the union. The union has been trying to get the government to come to the bargaining table with a renewed commitment to negotiate a fair deal for teachers. Ren adds that Minister Lecce is frequently asked about the state of the education system, and always says that the spending on education is higher than any other government in the world.',NULL,NULL),(67362,156,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/5k6fnb/pp_22nd7a1mn.mp3','2023-10-25 19:41:53',287962512,'2023-10-25 20:05:26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67364,169,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/3h88r4/iw_23rd90xrb.mp3','2023-10-25 19:04:42',143961989,'2023-11-18 09:16:10',NULL,'On this edition of the show, Jenny Blackbird talks about some of the events she\'s been working on for the show. The show starts off with a song called \"Mi\'kmaq Song,\" which is based on a traditional Mi-kmaq song. This song is performed by a young Mi\'kmak man named Morgan Toney, and a dance is also performed by his mom, who is a teacher. Also, she has a young friend, Aluk, who has done a segment for the CBC Kids about a traditional dance.\n\nShe also talks about the upcoming week, called Indigenous Education Week, which will take place from October 30 to November 3. There will be workshops, lectures, and other events. If you are a student, staff, or faculty member at the University of Toronto, you can find out more about it on CLNX, the U of T\'s social media platform. There\'s also a traditional teaching with Jane Merrigal, who teaches from a Haudenosaune lens, on October 25th. There are also monthly fires at the house, which are open to the public.',NULL,NULL),(67370,209,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/iu2fw5/to_25th61ajo.mp3','2023-10-25 19:37:39',143961989,'2023-11-18 09:02:11',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with dance pioneer and founding curator of DanceWorks, Mimi Beck. The first part of the interview is devoted to describing her career, which has spanned more than 40 years. The second part is dedicated to describing the last time she and Nicole were on the same show, which was in 2019.',NULL,NULL),(67371,218,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/emf764/taylor_report_23rd781hk.mp3','2023-10-25 19:39:39',143961989,'2023-11-18 08:52:51',NULL,'The Taylor Report is hosted by Phil Taylor and consists of a series of short interviews with independent critics of the Bush administration. The first interview is about the recent demonstrations in the U.S. against the war in Syria. The second is about a demonstration in Toronto, organized by World Against War. The third is about how the Bush Administration is attempting to control the news. The fourth is about why they are trying to speak to David Mivis, a prominent Jewish rabbi in Canada, about the demonstrations in Washington.',NULL,NULL),(67372,217,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/pppvj9/CIUTOct24.mp3','2023-10-25 18:22:17',143961989,'2023-11-18 08:43:27',NULL,'This episode opens with a conversation between David Jaden, the proprietor of a popular dance hall, and a host of other music industry types. They discuss the various music acts that they perform each year for the Halloween season. The first of the two specials that David does each year is called \"The Late, Late lamented Transylvania.\" The other is \"Dead Bulls.\" They plan to continue the theme of \"The Bloodshot Bill\" with their \"Evil and Swing Breakers\" and \"Neck Breakers Adventures.\" They will also include \"The Coyote\'s Whale from the Dark Shoulder\" and a \"Voodoo trucker.\"',NULL,NULL),(67374,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/Volunteer Playlist - October 25, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 08:34:09',NULL,'The University of Guelph\'s School of Fine Arts and Music presents a concert at noon on Thursday, November 1st. The concert is entitled \"At Noon Concert.\" The program will include a performance of \"The Ribbon of Extreme,\" a new work by Professor James Hord-Harley and Philippe \"Hopp.\" The concert ends with a performance by Scott Thompson and Ken \"Aultcroft\" Aultcroft.',NULL,NULL),(67384,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/End Credits - October 25, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 08:26:01',NULL,'The two discuss the films that were nominated for the Oscar for best picture in the 1970\'s. The first was George Romero\'s \"The Crazies\" and the second was William Friedkin\'s The Exorcist. They also discuss \"Don t Look Now\" and \"The Wicca Man\" .',NULL,NULL),(67385,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - October 25, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 08:17:48',NULL,'Another episode of the Gryphon Sports Report. Taylor tells us that he was at a Bob Dylan concert. He says that Dylan played a cover of the Grateful Dead song \"Stella Blue\" and that the band lost track of Dylan when he was playing badly.\n\nThe show starts with some music. They\'ve got some songs from their records at the station, some from Dredd\'s cricket beat at CFRU, some reggae tracks, and some ska tracks to get them ready for the show. Finally, they head over to \"Boss Taylor\" to tell him that they\'ve added a new show called \"Griffin\'s Best of All the Pick\'s\" to their schedule. It\'s a weekly show that updates the listeners on the Griffin family. If you\'re a fan of sports and want to be a part of the show, then you can send an email to terro15@ sepacre.com with the subject line \"Griffin Sports.\"',NULL,NULL),(67395,1321,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/Hong Kong Student Radio Association - October 25, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-26 00:07:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67396,13298,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/CFRU Selector - October 25, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-26 00:07:45',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67406,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/B Siide Radio - October 25, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 08:04:11',NULL,'The program is hosted by Karen, who is the host of the volunteer-run Guelph community station, CFRU 93. The program has news about a number of interesting events happening in the community, including the opening of a new makerspace and the release of the debut album of a singer-songwriter, The Lost Art Of Pulling Through Ballads.',NULL,NULL),(67407,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/Trail Mix - October 25, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 20:00:00',86507776,'2023-11-18 07:54:43',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67417,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/Tone Zone - October 25, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 07:47:01',NULL,'The Tone Zone returns to its annual Halloween special, this one hosted by Matt White, who is dressed as M White, the DJ. The first song of the special is a song called \"Jack the Ripper\" from a band called \"The One Way Street\" from Ohio.\n\nThe second song is \"Meet is Me\" from Norma Tanega\'s 1966 album \"Walking My Cat-Nameed Dog\" and the third song is from John Carpenter\'s \"Synth Distant Dream\" from his \"Lost Themes 2\" album. The fourth song is a punk song from The Units and \"I-Night\" from 1980. The fifth song is the \"Dincentive Dimension\" from the album \"Somebody Down there Likes Me\" by the band \"One Way Street\".\n\nThe sixth song is another from Norma\'s album \"Walkin\' my cat-named dog\" and \"You\'re dead\" from her 1966 \"Walking my Cat-named Dog\" album and the seventh song is also a punk tune from \"The Black Album\" by John Carpenter.',NULL,NULL),(67427,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Wild Combination - October 26, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 07:35:58',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67437,189,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/tqnjre/vftc_petestsmp9o1go.mp3','2023-10-26 07:34:10',283368000,'2023-11-18 07:23:29',NULL,'The show is called \"Vinyl from the Crypt\" and it\'s the place where you can come and listen to music that means a lot to you. The program is hosted by Sean Mitchell, who is the host of the program. This week, he brings along Peter Stamp, a friend of his.\n\nStamp is a veteran of the music scene, and he and Andrew Hall are both old friends. They\'ve both been listeners of the station for a long time, and they\'re excited to be back together. Andrew will be playing the first set, followed by Peter. The first song is \"Painted Ladies\" by Joni Mitchell, and it is a classic rock song from the early 70s. Peter is a big fan of the song, so he\'s happy to share it with us.',NULL,NULL),(67438,219,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/3ppwqm/ES231025.mp3','2023-10-26 06:01:38',141444790,'2023-10-29 05:42:26',NULL,'James Bailey: The Music Works New Edition comes out every three months. The deadline to enter the electroacoustic music composition contest has been extended to November the 15th. James will play a bunch of things from the CD, probably a bit from every track, because it\'s less than an hour long.',NULL,'James Bailey: The Music Works New Edition comes out every three months, and the deadline to enter is extended to November 15th'),(67439,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Wild Combination - October 26, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 07:10:49',NULL,'This is the first in a series of short interstitials. The first is a promo for Silence Radio, a non-profit organization dedicated to preserving the magic of silence. The organization asks listeners to pledge $10 a month to support the arts for a year. If you can\'t commit, then you can still support Silence by sharing a picture of yourself and encouraging others to do the same. The narrator and the rest of the cast of Silence are psyched to be at Fountains on February 1, 2023 to speak to the Swahili community about the organization\'s work',NULL,NULL),(67463,182,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/35te7e/Oct_25_20238owjj.mp3','2023-10-26 12:19:04',149544750,'2023-11-18 07:02:48',NULL,'This week on No Beat Radio, host Vanesh will be playing music from a variety of different artists. The first track is called \"A Fall With Ghost In My House\" by Nurse With Wound. The second track is \"The Land of No\" by Steve Schiffman. The third track is from \"Psychedelic Asylum\" by Gillaband. The fourth track is by \"She Knees Open\" by Animal Collective. The fifth track is a collaboration between Chad Van Galen and Amaya from Sleeps of the Ice. The sixth track is Joseph Shabinson.',NULL,NULL),(67469,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 26, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 06:54:31',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67470,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Here Today - October 26, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-07 06:14:53',NULL,'Aaron Badgley sits down to listen to some music. He starts off by saying that he doesn\'t drink because he\'s so consumed by the idea that he can do anything he wants. But then he thinks about the fact that he has a special sauce that makes him feel better when he drinks, and he realizes that he needs it. He thinks about how all his hopes of romance have been shattered, and now he realizes why it matters. He decides that he\'ll never be able to have a romantic relationship with another human being, and that\'s why he keeps drinking. He talks about an artist named Marcella Detroit who once was known as MarcyLevy. She put out an album called Gold Demos and she\'s been a successful musician since then. She co wrote a song with Eric Clapton called Lay Down Sally, and she also co-wrote a song called Pet cemetery for a movie called The King\'s Pet. Aaron also talks about a singer named Joe Jackson who has released an album of his own songs called What a Racket. And another artist named Jenna Nation who is based in Toronto. Aaron says that she has a new song out called \"Introspection\".',NULL,'How I Drink and I Want to Have a Romantic Relationship (27 minute read)'),(67480,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/FoodFarm Talk - October 26, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 06:45:54',NULL,'In this interview, Martin explains how he got his current job at the university. He got a Ph.D. in agronomy from the university and worked in industry for four years. He then got his undergraduate degree and then his master\'s degree. He\'s a pioneer in this field.\n\nHe tells Tim that he\'s been interested in how farming systems work and how farmers adapt to changes in the environment. He says that he learned from Wes Jackson at the Land Institute and that\'s how he came to the university in the first place. He also says that when he first started at university, he was interested in improving the efficiency of the production system. He adds that he has been training students in this area for over 30 years. After that, he says, he just wanted to do what he wanted.\n\nHe thanks Tim for his kind words and thanks him again for his job title. Tim asks Martin if there are any definitions for what he calls \"regenerative agriculture\" and Martin says that there are many different definitions. He explains that what they\'re really talking about is principles that have been around for a long, long time. They\'ve been used for many years. If you look at a cover crop,',NULL,NULL),(67481,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Tales from the Bridge - October 26, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 06:32:51',NULL,'Tales from the bridge. Tommo and Jim are psyched to have a Canadian on the show, and this time they\'re psyched to talk to someone who\'s Canadian. They\'re talking about science fiction author, Andy Weir. He has a new book out called Project Hail Mary that\'s being adapted into a movie.\n\nHe\'ll be starring in the movie with Mr. Abs. Jim is psyched to see him, since he thinks he\'s totally Canadian. He starts off by saying that his accent is stereotypical, since people always call him by his first name. Jim says that he wants him to tell everyone in Canada that he\'d like them to call him an American.',NULL,NULL),(67483,173,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/j5rr3i/Club_Ned_Oct_29_2023_Podcastanfdh.mp3','2023-10-26 17:22:49',565712978,'2023-11-18 06:21:22',NULL,'This section consists of a series of photographs, which illustrate the various effects of drugs on the soldiers. The first photograph depicts the burning butt of an uncured butt, which contains a small amount of fine uncured marijuana. The second photograph depicts a large, uncured bomb crater. The third photograph depicts smoke from a small pot, which is used to smoke hashish. The fourth photograph shows a wooden foil with a hole in it, which has been punctured to let in smoke.\n\nThe fifth photograph shows tinfoil foil, which can be used as a smoking block. The sixth photograph depicts what appears to be a group of men trying to find Kook headquarters. The section commander is unable to locate the location of his men, and the other men are unable to communicate with him. The troop commander gives up and laughs.',NULL,NULL),(67492,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Bridging The Social Distance - October 26, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 06:07:07',NULL,'This episode of Bridging the Social Distance is produced by Jenny Mitchell, who started the show in response to a pandemic. She continues it because it is very valuable to her to share stories and experiences with her listeners.\n\nThis interview is recorded on October 17, 2023. Lillian Parker is a long-term resident in the Village of the Riverside Glen. She has been there for two years and her husband has been with her for three years. Lillian\'s first husband was very sick and she missed him terribly, so she was forced to move into a room with her husband. Her second husband had a stroke and she has been living with him ever since. He has dementia and is very bad. She says that she had Pearl before, but now she has Pearl and then her husband and she had no problem with him. He had a bleed and then he had dementia. She had no problems walking and then she had a bleeding.\n\nThen she had another stroke and he had a dementia. He is now really bad and he has aphasia. She only speaks because she is coming to talk to people with different histories and experiences, and she never needs to apologize for her voice or any difference there. She explains that one of her reasons for coming to the village',NULL,NULL),(67493,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Democracy Now - October 26, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 05:57:02',NULL,'The war in the Gaza Strip has reached a new crisis point as fuel and water run out at the Laxamanders Hospital. An Israeli airstrike has killed the family of one of the most prominent journalists in the area, Wael Dadduh.\n\nHe reports that the situation in the besieged area is dire. He adds that there is no place safe in the whole of the territory, and that no one can be safe from the violence of the occupation and the aggression of Israel. Amy Goodman reports on the latest developments in the war and peace report. Israel has invaded the northern part of the Strip overnight and is continuing to bombard the entire Gaza Strip.\n\nThe death tolls have reached 7,000, including 3,000 children. UNRWA, the United Nations agency for Palestinian refugees, says it has been sharing its dwindling supplies of food with UNRWA. Oxfam accuses Israel intentionally starving the entire population of the strip. Wael\'s family was killed in an airstrike by an aerial attack. They had fled the area to seek shelter at the Nusarat Refugee Camp in central Gaza. The family\'s youngest son was seriously wounded in the attack. The attack was as Axios reports.',NULL,NULL),(67503,289,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/49wtyz/The_Next_Stop_1228yhw8.mp3','2023-10-26 17:49:42',270715658,'2023-11-18 05:47:13',NULL,'The Next Stop is a live music show from the Canadian Broadcasting Union that airs on CIIT 89.5 FM in Toronto. It\'s hosted by Sage Ranaldo, and it\'s all about music. The program starts off with a track called \"Beach Theme\" from the 1981 movie \"Thief,\" which was directed by Michael Mantell and was released in the United States in 1981. The music featured on the show is all from the \'80s and \'80s, and many of the tracks were influenced by Tangerine Dream.\n\nYou can find the music from this show at the nextstop.com. The show gets underway with \"The Next Stop,\" which is a mix of tracks from various artists from different parts of the world. It starts with the 1981 crime film \"Tide,\" which has a music score by German electronic music group Tangerine Dream, but it also contains a lot of \'80s-influenced music, like \"Echo Chamber,\" \"Ganymede,\" \"Babazi Konate,\" \"Titi-Bacorda,\" \"Ude-Mill,\" \"Spook Mutombo,\" \"Kasia-Gammaya,\" \"I-found-you,\" and \"Ladia,\" to name a few.',NULL,NULL),(67504,205,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dghiwh/October_26th_2023_Music_at_High_Noon7rhhe.mp3','2023-10-26 18:01:53',226663168,'2023-11-18 05:35:24',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the music on the program. It\'s all done by Mike Tadros, the host of the program, who is in charge of selecting the music for the program each week. This week, the program starts with Junior Parker and Sarah Vaughan doing a cover of Fool On the Hill. They also hear from the EZ Star All-Stars with \"The Great Gig In the Sky\" and \"Tisan Chin\" and from Carl Harvey with \"Wild My Guitar Gently\" and the Linels with \"Tomorrow Keep Alive\". The program ends with the song \"Coming Home\" by Slackwax and the song by EZ.',NULL,NULL),(67505,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Android’s Dungeon - October 26, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 05:25:15',NULL,'This is the first time we\'ve heard Jack discuss his relationship with his partner, Joel. Jack says that sometimes he\'s joined by someone else, but usually they\'re together just for fun. This time, Jack and his partner are discussing the West Coast of Canada, which is the worst part of the world.\n\nIt\'s the place where the San Andreas fault is supposed to break. The West Coast is going to sink into the ocean. The good news is that it\'s a better place than the bad. The bad news is, the West coast is actually better than the south of Canada. The point is, though, that you take the bad with the good. Jack and the partner talk about everything from books to movies to games to music.\n\nThey\'re both in the middle of a yoga ball in the studio so they have to glue things on the desk. The two of them talk about what happened to them as they walked into the building. They talk about how they\'ve been working on the show for the past few weeks. The first thing they talk about is the new cultic game, which was the best game ever made. They also talk about some of their favorite scary board games. They don',NULL,NULL),(67506,13307,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Eclectic Selections - October 26, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 05:11:18',NULL,'In this episode, the CFRU crew continues to explore the complexities of Africa\'s music scene through the use of the theme of \"Time, as Victims is Over.\n\n\" The first song on the program is \"Confessions,\" a song from the book \"The Jungle Book.\" The song was performed by Bria Stoenberg, a jazz trumpeter and singer. The other two songs are from the works of artists who started out with the letter \"B.\" Next, the crew moves to \"Shift the Tempo a Little Bit.\" The theme of the music is \"The Whole Idea about Your Environment Must Be represented in the Music and the Arts.\" The music, according to the host, must be representative of the time and place in which it is being played, because \"music cannot be For enjoyment.\n\n\" The other guests on the show include Fela Kist with \"Look and Laugh\" and Yusuf Nadour with \"Africa Dream Again.\" The program ends with \"We Will Take Our Execution.\" This is a song originally recorded by Moby in the early 2000s, which was subsequently re-recorded by Greg and Andis. The song is about being executed, and the narrator of the song says that he will no longer \"ask for justice.\" Instead,',NULL,NULL),(67516,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/RadiOPIRG - October 26, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 04:57:03',NULL,'On the next episode, the host discusses two documentaries he\'s just listened to on Talking Radical Radio. One from 2016 and one from 2022. The first is from the year 2022 and the second is from 2016. The first interview is with Scott and the host talking about the work they\'re doing in Palestine. The second is with the host discussing the work he and Scott are doing on the women\'s boat to Gaza campaign. The women are traveling to the Gaza Strip to bring humanitarian supplies to the blockaded area.',NULL,NULL),(67517,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/T.K.O. - October 26, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 04:47:52',NULL,'This is the second episode of the show. It\'s called \"The Wake Up Call,\" and it\'ll be the third time we\'ve heard it. The first time we heard it was back in the day, when the show was called \"T.K. O. Live.\" The second time around, we heard the name of the program, \"Mixed Martial Arts.\" The third time, we hear the name \"MMA.\" As we\'re about to learn, the program is all about mixed martial arts.\n\nThis is a big deal for us, because we\'d never heard of it before. We get to hear the story of how Janan woke up early one morning to get blood work done, then went to the doctor\'s office to get his blood drawn, and then came home to record his own blood work. That was a h