ing with the loss of theirs.',NULL,NULL),(67697,1627,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/28/Jitterbuggin - October 28, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-28 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-17 23:37:14',NULL,'This is the second of two parts of a new interview with Adrian St. James. The first part of the interview takes place at his studio in Mississauga and the second part takes place in his apartment.\n\nHe explains that he is coming out to his studio at midnight on the night of the show. He is prerecording his shows and then playing them live. He says that he can give you local news, but he can\'t because he is not at home. He also says that if you visit his website at cfru.ca, you will see an agreement of his upcoming show and you can ask him to play for him. He then gives a rundown of the shows he has lined up for the day.\n\nHe mentions that he has an album from his band the Collins Kids, which he describes as \"cheesy, sickly sweet suckery type.\" He also mentions that there is a Canadian girl in his gallery who he hopes will soon be Canadian. He ends the interview by saying that he\'s running out of shoes.',NULL,NULL),(67730,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/w7b3rc/CriticsCircle_28102023bjm77.mp3','2023-10-28 14:01:43',NULL,'2023-11-17 23:20:44',NULL,'The show begins with Phil Taylor, the host of the Cairns Critics Circle, introducing a special guest: Eric Wolf, an actor, playwright and artistic director of the Eldridge Theatre, a magician, and theater administrator and coordinator of the Red Sandscastle Theatre. Wolf is currently in his play, \"Doc-Wuther-Glooms-Here-There-Be-Monsters,\" which he calls \"a cautionary tale of \'monsters\' with \'magic, mayhem, and ghoulish tendencies\'.\" Wolf describes the play as a \"tale of monsters with \'weird tendencies\'\" and says that he loved it.\n\nHe explains that his first show was a one-man show, \"The Strange and Eeerie Memoirs\" about Billy-Werther-Gulliver, which was a \"supernatural\" play about puberty. At the time, Rod Beattie was a well-known playwright in the area and he was a good actor, so he wanted to do his own play. He had no idea about puppetry, and so he built all of the characters out of them. In the audience feedback, he found that the puppet enhanced the horror of the play, making it \"a horror play in ways he hadn\'t intended.\"',NULL,NULL),(67745,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/28/A Dog’s Breakfast - October 28, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-28 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-17 23:10:37',NULL,'The listeners are introduced to a new artist named Marianne Trudel, who is best known for her work with the likes of Rezonon, John Hollenbaugh, and Hot Chip. The group then moves on to two other artists who recently played at a festival in the city of Guelph: Ajay Bomsenwan, who played from his \"fractions and blood,\" and Hafez Modushtein, who came in as an \"absentee\" from the badada. The program ends with a visit to Oliver Schroer, who had recorded street sounds from his pilgrimage through Spain. The show closes with a shout-out to everyone who has been a part of the program.',NULL,NULL),(67746,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/28/Beautiful Druid - October 28, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-28 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-17 22:58:15',NULL,'The program begins with a description of the music that will be played on the program. It is a mix of songs, songs about the upcoming lunar eclipse, and poetry. The program is being produced by a student at the university named Alden Hat. He will be the host of the program for an hour. The music will be about the moon, the eclipse itself, and love. He tells the listeners that the program is produced by the university\'s community radio station, CFRU.\n\nThe theme of this week\'s program is \"a loosely woven theme\" . He explains that he is recording on the eve of the lunar eclipse. He says that he will play three songs that relate to the moon. The first song is Lynn Miles\'s \"Tumble Weedy World\" and the second song is Bonnie Tyler\'s original \"Total Eclipse of Heart\". The third song is Andrew Hamilton\'s song \"Fur Elise\" , and the fourth song is Gordon Lightfoot\'s album \"Leaves of Grass\". The program ends with two reflective songs, one by Walt Whitman and one by Gordon Lightfoot. The second song, \"Ribbon of Darkness\", is about the civil war in the United states. Alden says that the',NULL,NULL),(67756,35978,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/28/CFRU Live from 10C! - October 28, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-28 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-17 22:45:57',NULL,'The conversation continues as the women discuss the concept of \"art of hosting.\" This is a term used to describe a process in which people intentionally gather together to address issues. There are many different ways to do this, but the most effective is through a three-day training.',NULL,NULL),(67757,35978,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/28/CFRU Live from 10C! - October 28, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-28 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-17 22:33:52',NULL,'The two talk about the upcoming celebration of the 15th anniversary of the Arrow Food and Arts Institute. The two also talk about meeting each other when they were working on the Mohawk Show and the Crash Show respectively. They\'ve also met up at the Tree Walk and the Tree Festival. Jenny and Kareem are both excited about the celebration, and they\'re glad to be able to help spread the word about it.',NULL,NULL),(67767,35978,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/28/CFRU Live from 10C! - October 28, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-28 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-17 18:59:06',NULL,'This chapter is a continuation of the conversation between Rosa and Esther. In this chapter, Esther tries to understand her position as a white artist, and as a transfeminine artist. She says that the fulfillment of her work doesn\'t come from a vacuum, but comes from the contributions of others. She i