all over the city. They start off with IBO, who\'s called Asterekeow. Then we hear from DeVito, who did For The Road, from Wale, Wale who did The Road and from Prudence who did \"Nana 2-4\" . And then it\'s all about the Greenbelt Land, which is a big deal. It turns out that Ford had meetings with some of the people who were going to be paid off by the land deal, and he\'d have to pay off all of them in cash.',NULL,NULL),(68286,219,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/w5nzsq/ES231101.mp3','2023-11-02 14:38:25',139549345,'2023-11-13 23:42:54',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the music that will be on the show. The first track is called \"Light Machine\" and the second track is \"Infinity Plus One\" by Jennifer Wilson. The third track is from a group called Sick Boss, which includes Peggy Lee and Josh Zubat, and is described as an \"ornithopter\" .',NULL,NULL),(68287,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/02/Tales from the Bridge - November 2, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-02 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-13 23:29:52',NULL,'In this episode, Sam and Tristan discuss what they read this summer. They also discuss the science fiction they\'ve been reading, including a book by Stanislau Lem, Solaris. Sam also reads some of the books in the Expansive series.',NULL,NULL),(68288,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/02/FoodFarm Talk - November 2, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-02 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 23:18:34',NULL,'In this episode of the Canadian Food Focus podcast, host Clinton Machuck talks with nutritionist, Erin McGregor, about how to recognize food misinformation. In particular, he discusses how to spot false and misleading information on food labels, social media, and other sources of information. She explains that she has worked as a dietician for over 15 years and has done many other interesting things as well. She previously worked in a nutrition communications company where she wrote a cookbook for Canadians. Her goal was to encourage people to cook and prepare their own food and to make informed decisions about food, rather than fear it. She also works to help people recognize what is true, what is not, and what is an exaggeration about food.',NULL,NULL),(68298,195,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/kvdkdi/Dementia13RadioShow_23_10_31.mp3','2023-11-02 17:58:12',287962512,'2023-11-13 23:04:23',NULL,'This is the first of a series of short stories that will appear in the next two volumes of the novel. The first part of the story is set in the early 20th century, and it tells the story of a young man who falls in love with a woman who is the mother of his cousin. The young woman, Mary Day, is the wife of the man who is his lover, and the young man is the father of his child. The narrator explains that Mary Day is a witch, and that she is the only woman who has ever loved a man as her lover.',NULL,NULL),(68299,296,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/aztb3w/3rd_Face_21_oct_2023ae8yt.mp3','2023-11-02 17:47:47',143961989,'2023-11-13 22:49:55',NULL,'The third face on the show is screaming out to everyone on the ship. He\'s sure it\'s from Shakespeare, but he\'s also sure that there\'s a witch who has to make a soup for a maiden like he always does. The narrator is a bit worried about the fact that everyone says he\'ll always be another number. The tide\'s on unsteady legs, and the boy invited to a christening is a little wet with mercury. The Mad Hatter is a bed wetter. The fingerless wonder is a name and a reason to call home. The next song is about an ear strike. He can visualize the cold. He imagines that it\'ll come out at night, and he sees flashes of light. He gets the atlas tattooed on his back. He wishes he knew it like he knew his face. The sailors have been napping and everyone is heading down to the ship, and they\'ve got a name for it.',NULL,NULL),(68300,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/02/Bridging The Social Distance - November 2, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-02 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 22:37:08',NULL,'The interview is with Jenny Mitchell, a volunteer and studio coordinator at CFRU, who is a part of the Guelph Neighborhoods Support Coalition, which runs a weekly market in the North End of town called the NorthEnd Harvest Market. It offers free fresh produce to those in need. It also has a resource fair every year where other organizations can come and set up a booth. Jenny encourages listeners to visit the GuelphNeighborhoodsSupportCoalition.org to learn more about the market and to get more information. The interview ends with Chelsea, a community engagement coordinator with the Guelph Wellington Poverty Elimination Task Force. She is a member of the task force and works in the City of Guelph and the Counties of Wellington and Guelph. The task force works to eliminate poverty in Wellington County by advocating for resources and solutions at a systemic level. In other words, they advocate for a system-based approach to poverty elimination.',NULL,NULL),(68301,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/02/Democracy Now - November 2, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-02 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 22:26:05',NULL,'On this week\'s program, we hear more about the humanitarian crisis in the war-ravaged Gaza Strip. In the last few days, Israel has killed 195 Palestinians, including a hundred and twenty-two who are feared dead. A school run by the United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East has also been hit. The only hospital in the besieged territory has closed, and the only fuel it has is running on is running out. Meanwhile, Israel\'s troops and tanks have been advancing deeper into the territory. Vice President Joe Biden has spoken out for a humanitarian pause in the fighting. In Minneapolis, a Jewish rabbi interrupts a speech by a local council on American Islamic Relations leader and calls for a ceasefire. When she asks for a pause, the vice president says he supports a pause. In Minnesota, a chapter of the Council of American-Islamic relations holds protests demanding a ceasefire, while in Rhode Island peace activists hold a rally outside the office of Senator Jack Reed urging him not to send more money to Israel.',NULL,NULL),(68304,169,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/awk76d/IW_30th_Oct67yaf.mp3','2023-11-02 19:19:12',143961989,'2023-11-13 22:15:29',NULL,'This is the first time we\'ve heard the name \"Indigenous Waves\" on the show, and it\'s because we\'re talking about one territory. Yup, the Yup\'it territory of Canada. We\'ll get to that in a second. This time, we\'ll talk about the different aspects of the show: the show is called \"Indigenous Indigenous Waves\" and it airs on CIUT. It\'s a student-run station, so all of the students are listening to the show. The show is hosted by Jenny Blackbird, who\'s not really a student. She\'s just a friend of the station. She says she likes the show because it doesn\'t require her to be a student to listen to the program. We get to talk about some of the other things that are going on at the school: the U of T\'s annual Indigenous Fashion Week, which is being held this week, and a workshop with an Inuk beauty named Amanda. She was the one who created all the makeup for the pandemic, and she did a lot of the Inuk\'s tick box. The students watched some creepy videos about the Inuit fear of getting eaten or tickled, and then listened to her',NULL,NULL),(68305,171,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/untikw/podbean_version8207k.mp3','2023-11-02 18:17:03',186748977,'2023-11-13 21:58:27',NULL,'The narrator describes a family tradition. His name is Brad, and he and the overseer are sitting in the chair of the overseer at five oclock listening to an alternative radio. The narrator says that it is nearing the time of winter, and that the animals are gathering for the winter season. He says that a song is playing in the background, and then he is gone. The moon is gone, and the dust is brittle. It turns to ash and brittlestaccato dust',NULL,NULL),(68306,158,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/6bhsnh/The_Radical_Rev_31_octazttt.mp3','2023-11-02 19:14:16',143961989,'2023-11-13 21:48:02',NULL,'The Radical Reverends show welcomes a second guest, Reverend Christine Smallwood. She is a minister who has been doing funerals for many years. She tells a story about a funeral she had to attend where the casket fit on her lap. She also tells about her favorite funeral, which was the one of Johnny Cash. She explains that funerals are one of the most meaningful ministry in a minister\'s life because they allow people to be vulnerable and share their deepest thoughts. She says she has refused to play a particular song during a funeral when someone requested \"Highway to Hell\" because she has never considered it a sentiment, but she says she could not condone such a sentiment. The show ends with a discussion of the idea that people condemn one another to hell.',NULL,NULL),(68314,189,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/92umzu/VFTC_Nov19k1ru.mp3','2023-11-02 18:37:47',281111040,'2023-11-13 21:36:36',NULL,'The host of the underground show Vinyl from the strontium welcomes his listeners to a new live show. He thanks Peter and Andrew for coming to his show last week and thanks Philip for another episode of his show. The host also thanks his listeners for their continued support of the station. He says that he now comes up with a new theme for the live show, but he doesn\'t yet know what it is. He\'s going to let the listeners hang around and figure it out. There are three great progressive bands starting tonight. The first band is Blue Oyster Cult, the second is Metallica, and the third is Yes. The show starts with a veteran of psychic warfare on CIUT 99.5 FM. The veteran is Kirk Hammett. The band\'s latest album is called Too Far Gone. The song is called Lucky Man. The lead singer of Lucky Man was Greg Lake. The ELP song was called Lucky Woman. The drummer of Lucky Woman was Karl