r describes the first Pet Sematary, which he thinks is a Stephen King novel. He says that he has never seen it before, but that he thinks it\'s a rip-off of the original. He adds that the original version includes the wife of the neighbor\'s sister, but the remake cuts out the sister\'s name. The narrator was eight or nine years old when he first saw the story. He remembers his first novel was The Shining, which was like the same book as the story he saw. He also remembers the description of an old woman in the bath error his dreams. He thinks that people don, though, because King is a \"schlocky\" writer. He still writes good stories, though. He agrees that the director cut of The Shining is even better than the original, because it includes some of the director cuts. He loves Rebecca Ferguson and the villain Rose the Hat. He talks about Mike Flanagan, who\'s directing a new House of Usher movie. He has seen the other two movies and says they\'re all good. He hasn\'t seen the third one, which is called Bligh Manor, because he\'s waiting to see what the story is all about. The',NULL,NULL),(68319,13307,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/02/Eclectic Selections - November 2, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-02 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 18:39:55',NULL,'In this edition of Eclectic Selections, we hear some new music from the likes of Belgium\'s Di Melanie Biazio, Brian Jackson and his band, Adrian Yann, Nancy Wilson, the project known as \"Jazz is Dead,\" and Virginia\'s \"I Can Say to you.\" We also hear some familiar music from Bri Webb and his crew. The show also includes some music from Thievery Corporation, a Lebanese-Lebanese artist. The program ends with a discussion about the upcoming 12th International Film Festival. The festival will feature a number of documentaries, including one about July Talk, a satirical band that played the Stardust drive in the original Broadway production of Beauty and the Beast back in the early 2000s.',NULL,NULL),(68324,182,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/sgbyih/NBR_Nov_1_202384rgg.mp3','2023-11-02 21:26:58',144160391,'2023-11-13 18:26:21',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of No Beat Radio, host Minesh introduces the show and announces that he hopes listeners will sign up to be a member of the Canadian Institution for the Untied. He also announces that a band called Offworld will be playing a show in Toronto this week. The show will also feature a band from London called Mono Negatives. The band will also be playing at a club called Strewdattari on November 4th. The only thing left to do is to check out nobeatradio.com, the Facebook page, and the Soundcloud page.',NULL,NULL),(68330,289,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/edqh74/The_Next_Stop_1239y95k.mp3','2023-11-02 21:02:06',272565842,'2023-11-13 18:15:15',NULL,'The Next Stop On Ciut.FM The next stop on this Halloween special edition is the next station. This is where we\'re going to hear three tracks from the horror film The Thing, composer John Carpenter\'s first foray into the genre, and the haunting music of legendary composer and horror film maker N. E.O.Morricone. The third track is a song from the Carpenter film To Max Shaq, written by John Carpenter, his son Cody, and his godson Daniel. It\'s from the movie The Thing. Next up is Flatline from DJ Roswell, followed by the Witches from Bengal, Sam the Sham from the Pharaohs, the Sonics and the Witch from the Witchboard, Susie from the Banshees, Round Robin from the Wolfman, and David Bowie from Scary Monsters and the Super Creeps. And finally, Jim Blazer and John Harrison from the 1985 film Day Of The Dead. The show ends with the classic \"It\'s homage\" theme from the \"Simpsons Halloween special\" .',NULL,NULL),(68331,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/02/RadiOPIRG - November 2, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-02 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-13 18:01:03',NULL,'Oprah Guelph is now accepting applications for the Rebel Knowledge 2024 Symposium. This year\'s theme will be \"food and housing insecurity\", and the organization is looking for people to help organize the event. If you\'re looking for a position, check out the organization\'s website for details. Or, if you\'d like to help with the planning of the event, apply to be the external coordinator of the conference. The deadline for applications is November 6th, so if you know someone who\'d be interested in applying, you can let them know through either of the organizations\' mailing lists. Finally, Oprah Guelph announces that there are still spaces available for the next Rebel Knowledge Symposium, which will be held in 2024. In the meantime, there are lots of great jobs out there for people who want to help people in Guelph and beyond.',NULL,NULL),(68332,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/02/T.K.O. - November 2, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-02 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 17:51:12',NULL,'The guys discuss the past week, which has been full of activity. The guys also give a shout-out to a friend, Karen Tran, who hosted a party for the weekend. The girls talk about how they\'re going to dress up for Halloween, what they\'ll do with themselves, and whether or not they should get some candy. Karen also explains that she went to the store to pick up some candy for the kids in her neighborhood, but everything was gone, so she only had two packets of stuff. She\'s sorry she couldn\'t give more candy to the kids, but she\'ll still give out treats to her family and friends.',NULL,NULL),(68342,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/02/Open Sources Guelph - November 2, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-02 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 17:37:09',NULL,'On this week\'s Open Source, Scott Hertz, the host of the CFRU 98.3 FM show, and Adam Donaldson, host of CFRU.tv\'s Political and Current Affairs Discussion Show, discuss Mariah Carey\'s announcement that the season is here, and how she plans to break out of her \"cryogenic chamber\" and announce