versity. She is a female stand up comic who performs in a small, intimate theatre. She performs on a small stage. She and her fellow performers are asked to act as if they are on stage, and they are given the opportunity to act in front of a live audience. She tells them that they are only acting because they feel that they have to act. She says that she and Georgette have become very close in the past few years. They have become friends, and that they communicate with each other through the use of a \"chat\" system. When they are talking, they are',NULL,NULL),(69291,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/CFRU Playlist - November 13, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 21:06:01',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(69292,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - November 13, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 06:10:30',NULL,'In this chapter, Nicholas Cooper, the founder and host of the North American version of the live music show, the Sentinel, describes the scope of the show and its relationship to Turtle Island. He also acknowledges the contributions of the Black community to the music scene, and he thanks the listeners for their continued support of him. The show begins with a performance by Chris Squire, the legendary bassist from the Yes band. The rest of the session consists of new music from progressive artists including Jennifer Reiser of North Carolina, Pentayo of California, Suffer Fools of British Columbia and Callie Horse of Texas.',NULL,NULL),(69293,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Big Sis Radio - November 13, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 05:54:58',NULL,'This week on Big Sis, we hear tracks from two new albums. First, we listen to a track from the new album All Around You by Singaporean band SubSonic Eye. The band is inspired by the natural world and encourages the listener to sit with their complex emotions. The next track is a song by Arlo Parks called Brewzeless. It\'s an anti-war song. We also hear a song called What\'s The Holy Nobel Today from the voice of Bache-Prat. The last song we heard was Incidental Boogie from US Girls. This week\'s music picks are inspired by anger and sadness, and music is the medium for people to express their voices. It empowers people to gather and share ideas. It provides a space for people in the world to speak out against oppression. This is the weekly reminder that the world is going to be okay. In the second track, we learn about a school in Italy called Rondin. It teaches students the power to resolve conflict through reconciliation and is a unique institution. The school pairs students from different ethnic groups and encourages them to look at each other as different people. This approach encourages students to break the trance of seeing people as one another. This shows that when we',NULL,NULL),(69294,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/to know the land - November 13, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 05:38:58',NULL,'The conversation opens with a discussion about how to teach people in the U.S. how to live in harmony with the land, and what can be done to support that. David is particularly interested in the idea of teaching people how to be in good relationships with land and with each other, and how to not destroy the land. He talks about his long-time friend, Lisa, who works in the field of nature connection and teaches people about the land as well as how to develop good relationship with land. The conversation ends with a question and answer session, in which David asks Lisa how the ideas of nature education came into her life, and she answers that she grew up in cities, and that her innate desire to roam and be part of nature made her want to be outdoors.',NULL,NULL),(69295,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Blues Around the Block