00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 06:36:05','2023-11-14 05:06:10','This week\'s show will feature music from a number of different bands, including bands from Canada, the United States, Pennsylvania, and California.  The first track on the show is from Fashion Faux Paw, a band that\'s best known for their standoff with fashion faux-paw from their debut 2007 album Be Excited .\n\nThe band also includes some members of bands like New Day, Spread the disease, and Amenostra.  The second track is from Johnny Hanson, a singer who\'s also a member of Dead Bob and other underground acts.  The third track is a song from Native Nod, which is best known as one of the bands that cancelled a cross-country tour in the early 90s.  It\'s called Back to Mimmsy.  The fourth and final track is called Red Cross with iHateMySchool, which was part of the group\'s first self-titled EP.  The fifth track is The Hated With Somewhere, a collection of songs that was released in 1985.  The sixth track is Dave Buschmeyer\'s band, which includes members of New Day.',NULL,NULL),(69299,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Back in the USSR - November 13, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 14:46:31','2023-11-14 07:06:41','On this edition of the CFRU program, we continue our program on the situation in the Middle East. More than 10,400 Palestinians have been killed in the recent conflict in the Gaza Strip.\n\nMany countries have severed diplomatic ties with Israel and many ambassadors have been withdrawn from the Jewish state. The one member of the US House of Representatives, a Palestinian woman named Rashida, has been censored by Congress for speaking out against the war in the occupied territories. The interview with Prashad takes place on the second day of the largest mass demonstration in the United States for the support of the people of the Occupied Territories. It was attended by over three million people. The demonstration reminded Prashard of the struggle to end apartheid in South Africa in the late 1980s. It reminded him of the way public opinion changed when the South African government turned against the apartheid government and a crusade and global crusade led to the end of the apartheid system. At the very same time, there is a member of Congress who cheated to leave and is being censored because she dares to speak out against Israel.',NULL,NULL),(69300,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Rainbow Country - November 14, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-14 14:31:41','2023-11-14 07:07:52','In this special edition of the show, host and producer Mark Tara introduces his new show, \"Rainbow Country,\" and explains that it is a \"little gay radio show\" that works to \"give voice to the lesbian community and beyond.\n\n\" The show is produced and hosted by Mark Tara, who is also the producer and host of the program. The show begins with a brief introduction to the show and then segues into the life of the \'80s, where the \"gay community was actually getting noticed.\" The police had never liked the decriminalization of homosexuality that was passed by the Trudeau government in 1969, but they began arresting gay men in the early \'80s. The most famous raid was the one in Toronto on February 5, 1981, when the police arrested 300 men in connection with the prostitution of men in public baths.',NULL,NULL),(69301,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Rainbow Country - November 14, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 14:19:47','2023-11-14 09:07:20','',NULL,NULL),(69302,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/CFRU Playlist - November 14, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 06:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 13:06:26','2023-11-14 13:06:26',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69303,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - November 14, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 18:31:10','2023-11-14 15:06:22','',NULL,NULL),(69304,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Here Today - November 14, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-16 10:12:51','2023-11-14 15:06:49','In this special edition of the Here Today program, Aaron plays new music from a number of artists, including a new single from The Beatles, a new album from the band Men Of North Country, a re-release of the band\'s classic albums, and more. He also plays a song from Paul Manchin\'s latest album, Master. The show ends with a special appearance by Aaron\'s wife, Deborah, who has new music to share.',NULL,NULL),(69305,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Solipsistic Retreat - November 14, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-14 18:21:44','2023-11-14 17:07:53','Solipsistic enters and announces that he\'s listening to the music on CFRU, which is a community radio station. The music is so good that he can\'t wait to hear it. He also announces that the station has a great website with all the latest news and information about the station. You can listen to all of the shows on the air, as well as watch live performances and listen to the latest music news. You also have the option of making a donation to the station if you\'d like.',NULL,NULL),(69306,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Solipsistic Retreat - November 14, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 18:10:00','2023-11-14 17:07:54','Solipsistic retreat is back on the air. This time, the host welcomes potential listeners to the show. He doesn\'t need to know much, he just wants them to know that he\'s a cool guy. He invites listeners to listen to his show and they\'ll understand his philosophy overnight.\n\nHe also mentions that he recently played a song by a Canadian artist called Rec Center. The song cycle is called industry plant one: part one and part two: part three. The second part of the song is self-released by the artist. The show is going to hear about a country goddess named Jacqueline. She\'s from Tennessee. The listeners will hear about her in the new album, but they won\'t hear about the older one. So we\'ll hear about this country goddess from Tennessee, but not about the younger one, because there\'s still a mystery about her whereabouts.',NULL,NULL),(69307,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Bridging The Social Distance - November 14, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 21:06:35','2023-11-14 19:06:15','In this episode, Jenny Mitchell, the host of Bridging the Social Distance, introduces her guest, Francois Daucourt who is a long-term resident at Riverside Glen. The interview is recorded on November 7th, 2023. He tells Jenny about his childhood in Ontario.\n\nHe learned English when he was a student at a school called Wellman. He also learned French when he went to school in Ontario and when he moved to the town of Wellman at the age of sixteen. He says that he likes his younger years because it breaks his shyness. He talks about how he was \"boy crazy\" when he turned 17 and how he learned to behave himself when he celebrated his birthday.',NULL,NULL),(69308,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Democracy Now - November 14, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 20:57:31','2023-11-14 19:07:22','The United Nations warns that the largest hospital in the Gaza Strip is in danger of becoming a cemetery. Anthony Lowenstein reports that Israel is exporting the technology of its occupation to the rest of the world.\n\nA London-based journalist, Ahmed Al-Nawba, has been forced to resign after signing a letter criticizing Israel, and another journalist, Jamie Kalis, has also been forced out of the New York Times after signing the same letter. The war grinds on. The UN says that no fuel will be allowed into the besieged territory by Wednesday. Meanwhile, the president of the United States, Joe Biden, has called on the Israeli military to stop its attacks on civilians. Biden\'s remarks came after doctors Without Borders reported that Israeli troops fired at medical teams and ambulances to the hospital. Others reported that they\'d also been hit by gunfire from drones. Israel says it has a command structure below the hospital but denies that it exists.',NULL,NULL),(69317,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - November 14, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-16 08:26:24','2023-11-14 21:07:20','This week on the Power Up program, the listeners are treated to some of the best music from Canada, Australia, the Philippines, Norway, and the U.S. We start off by hearing a song from Chester, then we hear a song called \"Fire\" from the Australian band Wild Ride, then a song by Celia Carlson, then from the Norwegians we hear \"I Don\'t care if you\'re beautiful\" from her \"Beauty for the Blind\" EP, and finally from the Filipinos we hear another song by the band Tribe. The song is called \"The Way you Make Me Feel.\" Then we hear the song \"Where it Begins\" from \"Voodoo Tribe.\n\n\" Finally, we hear Adrian Raso\'s song \"Revenge of Ganesh,\" which is a long piece that\'s been recorded over the past 20 years. This is from his debut album SuperSonic Music Man, which was released in 1999. Now we hear Atilane\'s songs, starting with \"Telegramma,\" from her latest EP MeidoEmor Iveda, then \"The Doves,\" an English band that was active from 1998-2010.',NULL,NULL),(69318,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Under the Needle - November 14, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-16 08:13:00','2023-11-14 21:08:03','The show is called \"Live on KEXP\" and it\'ll be the second time it\'s been called that. It\'s this time, we\'re talking about a band called \"Spirit Award.\" They\'re a band that\'s making a lot of noise in the Seattle music scene. The band\'s lead singer, Daniel Lyon, is a singer-guitarist, songwriter, and producer. He\'s also a member of the band, and they\'re releasing their latest album, \"The Fear,\" on Share It. The first album was called \"Never Ending\" because it took so long to finish. The second album was a little different, though, called \"The Lunatic House,\" because it wasn\'t going to be as depressing as the first one.\n\nIt was more like a \"release of pent up emotion and energy\" . KEXP\'s DJ, Cheryl Waters, asks about the new album. The new album is like a release, and it feels like you\'ve let the past go, and you\'re opening new doors and new opportunities. He tells her that the new record is kind of like letting it come and go, like he has a little bit of a trance-',NULL,NULL),(69319,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Silver Screen Dream Machine - November 14, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-16 03:44:41','2023-11-14 23:07:57','The show opens with a tribute to Canadian music icon Robbie Robertson. He was one of Martin Scorsese\'s most trusted collaborators, and he composed the music for many of his films. The show starts off with a piece from his score for the upcoming film, Killers Of The Flower Moon.\n\nIt is called \"From the Soundtrack To Season 2 of The Run The World TV Soundtrack series released this yr that was Rob Glasper with \"What Love Can Do Featuring vocals by EmilyKing\" and \"Shame On Us\" . Next we hear music from the Canadian drama Sleeping Giants screenplay, a score from Chris Thornborough, and music from Sin City, a 2005 anthology film that was based on a comic book series.\n\nFrom the 2004 comedy Shaun Of The Dead, a film starring English duo Simon and Nick Frost, and Ash, a song from Coldplay, we hear the music of the pop stars.',NULL,NULL),(69320,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/A Multilingual Affair - November 14, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-15 15:53:13','2023-11-14 23:08:23','The speaker begins by saying that she\'s here to inspire. She\'s talking about ego and love, which she describes as a \"self-reflection\" exercise. The speaker says that people should know that they\'re beautiful and that they don\'t have to do anything for the world to be a good place to be.\n\nShe says that she doesn\'t care if people think they have the right to live in the world, but that when they\'ve had a bad experience, she\'ll take responsibility for it and apologize. She also says that the music will help inspire the listeners. She has a good cry before the show, so she hopes that the listeners will be able to see her and then help her to heal from her experience. She then says that Charlotte de Panda is approaching.',NULL,NULL),(69321,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Tuesday at 5 - November 14, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-15 15:40:06','2023-11-15 01:06:34','On Tuesday at 5pm, you can listen to this program or stream it from the CFRU archives. The program opens with James Gordon\'s \"Love Is our best chance from his when I stayed home album\" and Stephen Fearing\'s song \"Something\'s Shoes\" from his \"Viposie album\" . Then, the program shifts to the Frank Ryan studio at the university of Guelph and the program starts with a folk opera called \"You Have Been Waiting\" by David Archibald. That\'s from Archibald\'s folk opera, \"Wind on the Prairie.\" The program then shifts to Lou Ariel\'s treason trial, which took place in Regina. The government moved the trial to Regina when it learned that a Manitoba juror could be half-Métis.\n\nThe Prime Minister decided to charge the Métis leader with high treason, based on an obscure law dating from the year 1332. This law carried \"the death penalty,\" whereas the Canada-\'s-treason law didn\'t. The trial lasts four days, during which Riel addresses the court and outlines his vision of a diverse society, but the jury comes up with a guilty verdict and sentences him to death. The judge ignored the pleas of the',NULL,NULL),(69322,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Down the Rabbit Hole - November 14, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-15 15:26:24','2023-11-15 01:07:37','In this edition of the Underground Man, the UM opens the show with a song by Ben Stager. He then introduces a few other songs by musicians, including Kamasi Washington , Youth of Days , Manu Dubango , New Jordan , and Charlotte A Wilson . The Underground Man then goes on to talk about his day, which included a walk outside and a class. He says that he\'s warmed up just a bit before the show starts. The next song on the program is by Yusef Day , a drummer from South London.\n\nHe was a member of Tom Mish\'s band, which released a record called Black Focus. It\'d been a long time since the UM heard of him, so he asks if you know him. He tells us that he studied with Billy Cobham at the age of 10. The UM is psyched to hear this music, because he thinks it\'s cool and eclectic. He also says that if you like his style of drumming, this is exactly what you\'re going to hear. He doesn\'t know what he\'ll say next, but he does say that he wishes he had more innovation in his music. But if you enjoy his music, he says,',NULL,NULL),(69323,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Let’s Get Lost - November 14, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-15 15:13:58','2023-11-15 03:06:20','The show begins with a discussion of the music being played on the 93.3 FM show. The show starts with a description of the band and the music they\'re playing. They\'re all playing a particular track from the album Beyond Dragons by Angelica Neischer, who\'s an artist from Germany. The band also plays a song from an album by El Cat, an artists from Israel. Then they play a brand new disc from Romper Sod, a trumpet player from Halifax. The disc is called Saudade, and it\'s his first solo release.',NULL,NULL),(69324,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/New or Never - November 14, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-15 15:00:16','2023-11-15 03:07:22','',NULL,NULL),(69325,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Let’s Get Lost - November 14, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-15 14:50:49','2023-11-15 05:06:09','The Humanoids discuss the latest releases from various artists on various labels. They include Kate Gentile\'s latest disc, Babel 17 on Aum-Fidelity Records, Kim Kass\'s new disc, In Casks on Find Letter X on Pi Records and the brand new album from Nicole Ramposaed on Ansible Editions. They also discuss Scott\'s Name Let\'s Go Get Lost, a new project from Bernie Wolrd and his band. They discuss Spherical, an album from The Talking Heads\' Sphyrical.',NULL,NULL),(69326,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Humanoid Radio - November 14, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-15 14:40:20','2023-11-15 05:06:11','The Humanoid Radio team begins their program with Josh Cole\'s \"Kind Mind\" album track, followed by \"Horses,\" \"Apollo Sons,\" \"Hit Piece,\" \"Virgo,\" \"The Poke and I. G. Oma,\" \"Hey Busty Pochie,\" \"All Gorilla Bones,\" \"Revenge Volume 2,\" \"You Ain\'t The One,\" \"Mocha Only,\" and \"In Tandem Radio and Out.\" The program concludes with a \"Signal is detected from Outer Space, apparently from Alien Source.\" The key to contact, the program concludes, is the technology of the radio.',NULL,NULL),(69327,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - November 14, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-15 14:50:14','2023-11-15 07:06:35','',NULL,NULL),(69328,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/15/Radia - November 15, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-15 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-16 07:59:53','2023-11-15 07:06:47','This is a special edition of the Radia show, where we catch up with the guy from Air France, Donald Trump. He\'s been on a mission to get to the bottom of the mystery of the Golden Girls, and he\'s found out that they\'re a sex toy company. He wants to know what\'s up with that. He also learns that Donald is a big fan of music, and wants to hear more about it.',NULL,NULL),(69329,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/15/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - November 15, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-15 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-16 07:45:45','2023-11-15 15:05:55','This is a special edition of Morning Soul Shake Up. It\'s all about the music and it\'s hosted by Withmad. Withmad starts off by telling us that he still likes to see our faces when we\'re sad. He says that he sees a pretty face and he hopes you can see it when you\'re happy. He tells us that when big people lose, they\'re not shouting about it. Plus, nobody\'s talking about it when it comes to gambling. So, you can be happy when you lose and sad when you make a lot of money. That\'s the message From The Responsible Gambling Council.',NULL,NULL),(69330,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/15/CFRU Playlist - November 15, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-15 07:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-15 15:06:09','2023-11-15 15:06:09',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69331,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ka8nx2/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Nov_15_2023_podcast6ij61.mp3','2023-11-15 15:04:08',289494203,'2023-11-16 07:34:51','2023-11-15 17:05:56','The program begins with the former programming director of the station, DB, talking about how important it is that the station continues to exist. He says that back when the station was known as CKLN and CRY, it was a part of the team, but now it is a full-fledged independent station.\n\nHe explains that they are trying to convince listeners to make a donation of $4 to help them continue their work. They have 26,300 favorite shows on the station and that means that every one of those listeners would reach their goal. If every person who listens to the station donated $4, they would reach the goal. Now that sounds impossible, but it\'s actually possible.\n\nIf you\'re a member of the organization, you can donate $89.50. If you listen to the program on the air, you\'ll hear a special guest: Michael Stor, who\'s also a fan of the program. He thanks the station for being a big supporter of the festival, and he thanks the listeners for supporting the station. The last song is a call to confidence.',NULL,NULL),(69332,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/15/The Stillness & The Dancing - November 15, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-15 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-16 07:23:05','2023-11-15 17:06:37','The show starts off with two pieces of music: one by M. Crook, another by Oxherding and a third by John Swank. The first piece is a collaboration between the two artists. The second is a new release from John Swank, called Sounding and Fathoms, which is out on lighten-up sounds. The third piece is from Adrian Lane, who\'s been friends with the show for a long time. Adrian has released a new collection of music on his label, Cheetra Records.\n\nThe show opens with a new track from Adrian, called AFamiliar Journey. Then it\'s time for a tour of some of the new music releases on the label, Outgrowth, Illumina, Lost Tribe Sound, and Skyphone. This is all from artists who have released their latest albums in the past few days. A lot of artists do listening parties where they invite listeners to chat with them about their latest releases.',NULL,NULL),(69333,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/15/The Stillness & The Dancing - November 15, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-15 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-16 07:10:27','2023-11-15 17:06:38','In this program, we hear from the host of the underground music show The Stillness and the Dancing, Joel Cuthbert. He\'s been through some medical treatments i