omeone asks why, he says, there are too many syllables, and if they ask someone else, he points out that if they decide not to call the park a national park but want a park nonetheless, it gives them a lot of freedom.','fix',NULL),(69436,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Democracy Now - November 20, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 19:46:41','2023-11-20 19:07:49','The war in Gaza has reached a crisis point, according to a new report from the United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East. At least 13,000 Palestinians have been killed in the conflict, and the number of wounded has nearly doubled. The report also points to the death of an Israeli peace activist, Vivian Silver, whose remains have been identified. The war will not bring peace, says the report, and it is time for the world to stop being taught that war will bring about peace.',NULL,NULL),(69437,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Worst Responders - November 20, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-20 19:27:05','2023-11-20 19:07:50','This is a very short and very funny comedy show. It is called Worst Responders and it is about two stand up comedians dealing with problems that people have on the internet. It starts off with two students, Charissa and Renee, who talk about how they are currently mid-October and how they think that September is crazy. They discuss how they used to be able to communicate with each other but now it\'s much more difficult because of the way that they use the internet and their inability to communicate using words like \"chat\" and \"chat. The students also discuss the upcoming reading week at the university and how it is not a good idea because they want to end their term early.',NULL,NULL),(69438,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/CFRU Playlist - November 20, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 21:06:16','2023-11-20 21:06:16',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69439,174,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ux2ggb/November_15_2023_Global_Rhythms94rc7.mp3','2023-11-20 21:15:49',431961989,'2023-11-21 01:47:42','2023-11-20 23:05:22','Ken Stowar, the founder and president of the Rhythm Club, gives a speech on the history of the club and its mission. He talks about how the club was founded and how its members came to be. He also talks about his father and his grandfather who were influential in the club\'s history.\n\nKen says that his grandfather was a very important man, and he is proud of his family\'s heritage. He adds that his father was a good listener and taught him how to play the piano. He says his grandfather taught him to read and write. His father was very important to him, and his mother taught him piano.\n\nHis grandfather was very strict with him and he was very good at it. His mother is very religious, and it is her opinion that people should not be allowed to sing or dance. She is very strict in her beliefs. Her father, who was very religious and very strict, died when Ken was a young man. He is very proud of him. Ken and his father are very close. They have a very close relationship.',NULL,NULL),(69440,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/s26cwr/November_19_2023_Across_the_Universeaqfej.mp3','2023-11-20 21:10:51',431961989,'2023-11-21 01:49:51','2023-11-20 23:05:37','The sound of your City fundraising campaign. The last day of On-Air Campaign. The Host of CIUT.fm announces that it is the final day of the campaign. He hopes listeners will come in and donate. He also invites listeners to listen more than they usually do.\n\nHe explains that the station is a unique, free, and open format and that he wants listeners to value what they hear on the station. He adds that they should call and donate at CIUT and listen to the music.\n\nThe Basement freaks are going to perform a track called \"Hit the Flame\" as they get to the end of the show. He asks listeners to call and give. He thanks all the listeners who have already donated. He then thanks Neil Pratt and Graham Benfield for their financial contribution.',NULL,NULL),(69441,257,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ag49k5/November_16_2023_Psychedelic_Stoner_Rocka17bo.mp3','2023-11-20 21:12:49',287962512,'2023-11-21 01:50:47','2023-11-20 23:05:50','The next Thursday night program is heard, and the host is Lee Ronaldo\'s son, Sage. Ken says he\'s a huge fan of the program, and he tells us that it\'s going to be a big hit.\n\nHe also says that they\'re doing a big tour of the building during the fall fundraiser, and that they need your help. They\'re asking listeners to give them a call or go to their website, where they can donate.Ken then announces the program\'s start time. He starts off by playing the track \"Sergeant Taurus on Poke\" and then proceeds to play \"The Space Huns.\" Ken says they need the phone donation lines and the donation site to be really busy right now.',NULL,NULL),(69442,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/rcumdw/November_17_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow9gy4h.mp3','2023-11-20 21:08:44',287962512,'2023-11-21 01:51:52','2023-11-20 23:05:51','Lydia presents her program, \"The Cool Side of The Pillow,\"  every week and asks listeners to donate to the cause. Lydia herself has also come to the station to promote the program. The next program is a meditation program called \"Meditation Relaxation Chill,\" which was developed by Lydia after listening to Paul Horn\'s program in the Taj Mahal. The program has since evolved into the \"Cool Side of the pillow,\" which Lydia calls \"Moroccan spirit.\" The program will be expanded to include more music, and Lydia says that she is planning to add more \"lively\" music in the future.',NULL,NULL),(69443,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - November 20, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 23:30:44','2023-11-20 23:06:09','Part 1 of the Future of Progressive Fusion and Alternative Music series begins with a conversation between Nicholas Cooper, the creator of the Sound of Turtle Island, and the artist and curator of the series. He begins by stating that he wants to pay respect to Indigenous territories and local communities, as well as Black communities. He says that he would like to recognize that their music is being played on Turtle Island from treaty lands, and that many of the sounds are adaptations of Black culture. He also says that the majority in the music featured originated from Black culture, which was initially created under circumstances of oppression. He thanks the Black community for their contributions to the popular alternative of the Sentinels marvelous kaleidoscope',NULL,NULL),(69444,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Big Sis Radio - November 20, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 01:54:03','2023-11-21 01:06:02','The narrator opens this show by talking about the Big Sis Radio show. The narrator explains that the show is from the treaty territories of the Mississauga-Credit Union. The show is a mix of music from the province of Alberta. He talks about the silent film, Sherlock Jr.\n\n, which was released in 1924. The silent film has some of the most famous stunts in the film, including one in which the window of a house is cut open by the side of it. The music for the show starts with Hay Major, an elegant rock band. It\'s one of Cece\'s favorite things to do. One of his favorite things about music is that it makes him feel infinite.',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO `episodes` VALUES (69445,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/to know the land - November 20, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 01:46:35','2023-11-21 01:06:04','In this episode, Byron talks about his show, \"How we defend the land,\" which is a podcast about how people interact with and defend the natural world.Byron\'s name is Byron, and he has an affinity for storytelling about the land, whether it\'s through scientific journals, or through storytelling in first person, or storytelling in both first person and in the form of mythology.\n\nByron also talks about the importance of October, the time of year when people tend to spend a lot of time reading books and collecting things. He finds that the stories and folklore that he reads often trace back to pre-Christian traditions of direct relationship between humans and the land. He thinks that the origins of all life, all nourishment, and all things are often traced back to those traditions.\n\nByron thinks that in these stories, there are often interspecies communication, that the plants and animals can communicate with the humans, and sometimes there are wood-spirits or sea spirits, and that there is a different kind of way of looking about the world that he thinks especially in the western identities and Western notions, which become rationalistic and rationalistic, and also Christian. And often, we start looking toward often like indigenous practices or practices of connection with the',NULL,NULL),(69446,157,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/uty6t4/509-33-45-78-nov20-23.mp3','2023-11-21 02:58:04',288228940,'2023-11-21 04:18:37','2023-11-21 03:05:21','The first song we hear is from Black and the King, a song written by Tom Wilson and Stephen Fury. This song is called \"Better When I\'m Stoned\" and it was released in 2003.\n\nThe song was originally recorded by the band The Searchers in the late \'50s and early \'60s. The band was called \"The Searchers\" after the 1956 movie \"TheSearchers\" and the band disbanded in March of 2019. The band\'s songs include Sex Pistols \"Not Your Steppin Stones\" and \"Squindle,\" John Mills \"Blues Breakers,\" Eddie Kirkland\'s \"Man of Stone,\" Mick Taylor\'s Crusade album, Sly and the Stone Family Stone, and Stoned Woman. The Stones \"Heart of Stone\" and Brian Jones\' \"Low Tune Guitar\" were the first songs we heard in the \'50\'s and the \'60\'s.\n\nManza \"B.B.\" Sisoko\'s song was also released in the \'60s and he was one of the featured artists on the guitar.',NULL,NULL),(69447,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Blues Around the Block - November 20, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 03:51:55','2023-11-21 03:05:54','Mac Dee is the host of the show and he tells the story of James Thunderbird Davis who wants a girlfriend to come by and his wife is with their mothers. He is lonely and the coast is clear and then the Chicago Rhythm Kings and he has a girlfriend and a woman and he is going to get caught. The girls who are listening to the show have sent a message for the boys and they want to hear the music from Crystal Schawanda, Irma Thomas, Don Tyler Watson, and Ben Racine. They want to listen to the music and come get it.',NULL,NULL),(69448,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Blues Around the Block - November 20, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 04:12:46','2023-11-21 03:05:55','He says that he\'ll be playing the same songs over and over again. For example, he starts off with a band from Steve Kozak\'s \"It\'s Time\" album, followed by the Smoke Wagon band from their \"Ballad of Albert Johnson\" album and Donald Ray Johnson from his \"Stay from the best\" album. He then goes on to play some more with Deb Reimer, Dilbert Mcclintock, James and the \"Little Big Band,\" and Kenny Blues Boss from his Go \"Just Do It\" album',NULL,NULL),(69449,219,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/qshvcc/ES231115.mp3','2023-11-21 03:44:00',139938047,'2023-11-21 15:47:38','2023-11-21 05:05:53','The program\'s narrator is excited when he realizes that he\'s a part of a community that\'s been around for a long time. He wonders if there are people out there who remember when Fabian was alive. The narrator says he\'d like to turn the volume down a bit so that people don\'t have to listen to the program at all. That way, they can hear the voice of the station. The program raises money, but it doesn\'t always have enough money to keep the program going. It\'s not always easy to raise money. The station used to be partners in crime with another station, but now it\'s very difficult.\n\nThey\'re always trying to make something new and different to appeal to people. The only way they can do that is to give people incentives to give. There\'s no grand prize money this year, which is a big deal. The listeners who donate money are not expected to get a grand prize, but they are expected to give back to the station in a way that is meaningful to them. They can give a dollar to the show if they donate a dollar for food or a dollar if they give up a beer for a week. ',NULL,NULL),(69450,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/The Deep House Project - November 20, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 05:50:13','2023-11-21 05:06:13','This week on the Deep House Project, the hosts discuss Black Friday, a holiday weekend in the South. They\'ll play some of the latest tracks from Bentley, including a collab with Habitat, as well as some of their own favorites. The show closes with a special guest, Chris Malinch\'s \"So Good to Me.\"',NULL,NULL),(69451,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Ripcord Radio - November 20, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 05:36:49','2023-11-21 05:06:13','This week\'s show is all about punk rock. It starts off with a bunch of classic songs from the past. We\'ll start with a band called the Tombs, who\'s got a song called Young, Loud, and Snotty from their first album. Next, we\'ll hear a song from another band called The Goolies called Little Medusa from their 2001 album Freaks on parade. And then we hear another song called The Suck\'s song called Cult of the FONZ from their split 7\" with Johnny and The Bad Lieutenants. Finally, we hear a track called Romantic Rites from Death from Above 1979, who\'ll be playing a concert in Guelph on October 15.',NULL,NULL),(69452,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Back in the USSR - November 20, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 07:47:44','2023-11-21 07:06:26','In this program, CFRU\'s political scientist, Professor Seigfried, discusses the situation in the Middle East. He explains that the latest round of violence between Israel and the Palestinians has been going on for a long time. He says that there is a growing international condemnation of Israel\'s treatment of the Palestinians, and the United Nations Security Council is close to passing a resolution for a humanitarian pause in the conflict. Israel has been running a trade surplus with the rest of the world, but the international community has started to isolate Israel.',NULL,NULL),(69453,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Rainbow Country - November 21, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 07:27:00','2023-11-21 07:07:27','This is the first episode of a new program called \"Rainbow Country\" hosted by Carol Pope, author of \"Boy Erased\" and \"Memoirs\" and co-host of \"Gay Radio Show\" with Lorraine Segato and Mark Tara. The show is a daily hour-long show that focuses on Canadian films and is produced by Mark and hosted by Mark. In this show, Carol and her co-hosts discuss the films \"I Am Surat\" from Oscar nominated Deepa Mehta and \"Red Lights,\" a short film from the Toronto International Film festival. In addition, they discuss \"An Evening Out,\" a powerful indigenous feature.',NULL,NULL),(69454,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Rainbow Country - November 21, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-21 09:25:41','2023-11-21 09:07:24','',NULL,NULL),(69455,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/CFRU Playlist - November 21, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 06:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-21 13:06:00','2023-11-21 13:06:00',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69456,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ka8ag4/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Nov_22_2023_podcastabc6r.mp3','2023-11-21 14:54:23',283265566,'2023-11-21 16:11:01','2023-11-21 15:05:46','The narrator and his wife are in their mid-forties and they\'re starting to get ready for the holidays. They\'re getting ready for Christmas meals, shopping, and all the other things that come with being a parent. But now that winter is upon us, the narrator says, the only thing that will keep them warm is for them to become criminals. He goes on to say that criminals will be arrested for a variety of crimes in the coming weeks, so it\'s really important to be nasty to the police.',NULL,NULL),(69457,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - November 21, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 15:47:00','2023-11-21 15:06:00','',NULL,NULL),(69458,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Here Today - November 21, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 15:25:56','2023-11-21 15:06:31','',NULL,NULL),(69459,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Bridging The Social Distance - November 21, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-22 14:12:00','2023-11-21 23:06:20','Guests today are Ed Miller and his wife, Sheila Miller. They moved to Guelph from Hamilton. The couple has two sons and one is in Kitchener. Jenny asks about the city and the people of it.\n\nShe asks if they were born in Hamilton before they moved to the village. The answer is yes. Both of them were born and raised in the city of Hamilton. They are both about the same age. They say that they met when they were working as tool makers at Barbara Guy casting. They lived together for a time and then met later in life.',NULL,NULL),(69460,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - November 21, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 10:29:54','2023-11-21 23:06:55','The program opens with a brief introduction to the music on the air. It\'s a mix of progressive rock, country, blues, jazz, and folk. The program starts off with a quick rundown of the bands on the program: Jackal is a progressive rock band from 1969 to 1974, from their only studio album Awake in 1973.\n\nThe Townsman is a 60s Ottawa band from the 60s with a live version of Backyards on a compilation called We\'re Fine Doing the Anthology. And then Linda Perry is an American singer songwriter and musician who fronted a band called Better, Bigger Faster that made only one studio album. She\'s also made three solo albums since then, starting with In Flight in 1996.',NULL,NULL),(69461,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/19/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - November 19, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-19 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 10:16:35','2023-11-21 23:07:23','The group begins with a song about how happy it is to be alive. The song is named On the Sunny Side of the Street, sung by Harry Richmond, who is 89 years old. Then they hear a song by Stevie Wonder who is 13 years old and who is singing this song in 1963. The group then moves on to some more songs about how happiness is made. The first song is about a famous actress and singer named Annette, who was on the Mickey Mouse Show. The second song is called Happy Feeling, and the third song is a song called Sugar Town. The group is then invited to interview two friends named Scarlett and Claire, who were schoolmates.',NULL,NULL),(69462,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/19/Visions fugitives - November 19, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-19 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 09:48:26','2023-11-21 23:07:24','The show opens with a description of the music on the show and the composer, Fangwei, who is in charge of selecting the music for the show. The music is from Greece and it was composed by Carl Nilsson in 1903. The program ends with a short piece by Sarah-Devaki. The show is now available on the CFRU website and live on the air.',NULL,NULL),(69463,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/19/Visions fugitives - November 19, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-19 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 14:09:39','2023-11-21 23:07:24','In this show, Fangwei recommends a piece by Anna Sokolovic entitled \"Dawn Always Begins In the Bones,\" which involves apples. Since they\'ve been thinking about apples, he says, he\'ll take inspiration from \"the most infamous apple\" of all time: the \"most infamous apple.\" This is a reference to the story of the Partakers of the Forbidden Fruit, where Eve tempts Adam to eat both of them at the same time. This is one of two candidates for the role of the \"Most Infamous Apple.\" The other candidate is the \"golden apple,\" which is said to have come from Eris the goddess of',NULL,NULL),(69464,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/19/Clan Na Gael - November 19, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-19 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 09:12:52','2023-11-21 23:07:25','The band starts out with a guy named Dargil from the Classic Irish Folk collection. Dargil used to live in a seaside town called Bray, about 12-15 miles from Dublin. He used to go there on Sundays, but the poor people couldn\'t go there because the town was too far away.\n\nThey went to the waxy\'s dargil, which is called Dollybrook. The word Dollybrook is from the song \"Dollybrook\" by the Dollybrooks. The band then goes on to play some songs from their CD collection. They start with Billy Cowe from \"Best of Scottish Folk\" and then they go on to a song called \"I\'m Not a Good Guy\" by Lorena McKinnon. Then they go back to Johnny McAvoy from \"Classic Irish Folk Machine\" .',NULL,NULL),(69465,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/19/Clan Na Gael - November 19, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-19 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 08:46:09','2023-11-21 23:07:26','The song is called \"Donna,\" and it\'s about a girl falling in love with a boy. It\'s one of the Irish songs, which is sad, according to the song\'s narrator. But the narrator thinks that the song will appeal to everyone, so he\'s going to sing it anyway. The song begins with a simple melody and moves to a more complex song about love.',NULL,NULL),(69466,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Democracy Now - November 21, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 08:28:58','2023-11-21 23:07:34','Israel\'s war on the Gaza Strip has taken a toll on journalists, with more than 50 of them detained and missing. In addition, Netanyahu has asked the Palestinians to leave the besieged territory. Meanwhile, the World Health Organization says all hospitals are out of service, and hundreds of patients are trapped in medical facilities that have effectively ceased to function.\n\nThe United Nations Secretary General calls for an immediate ceasefire, saying that thousands of children have been killed in the last few weeks. The U.N\'s chief spokesman says that the killing of civilians is \"unprecedented\" in any conflict, and that the death of the head of the Gaza Press House, Belal Jadah, is particularly significant.\n\nA woman named Ayat Khuddur has been killed with her family in an airstrike. She is one of the last of her kind to report.',NULL,NULL),(69467,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Silver Screen Dream Machine - November 21, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 15