hat\'s going on behind the scenes. He also mentions that there are phone lines to talk to people who want to donate, so listeners can call to talk with someone.',NULL,NULL),(69502,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/23/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - November 23, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-23 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 15:47:00','2023-11-23 15:06:01','',NULL,NULL),(69503,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/23/Here Today - November 23, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-23 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 15:30:13','2023-11-23 15:06:35','Aaron Badgley is back on the program to talk about music. He tells us that he\'s just heard a new song from Deborah Fray alkovich. She\'s got a new Christmas song out called \"Sparkle from Daughters of the Industriouss\" and she\'s releasing it in February.\n\nHe also talks about the James Clark Institute releasing a new album called \"harmony and discord\" . The James Clark is a band that\'s been around since the early days of rock\'n\'roll. They\'ve come back with a brand new single from the new album. Aaron also points out that the new single is also on the re-issued version of the Beatles\' classic album \"Blue Album\" , which was released in 1967.\n\nThe band also has a new track called \"Now and Then\" on their new album, which is also included on the remixed version of \"1962 to 1966\" which was originally released in 1966. The other thing Aaron mentions is that music producer and composer Robbie Robertson has announced that he will be composing the soundtrack for Martin Scorsese\'s new film \"Killers of the Flowers Moon\" ! Aaron also tells us about a band called the Consititines who have released two more albums',NULL,NULL),(69504,173,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fycbay/Club_Ned_Nov_26_2023_podcast6xa70.mp3','2023-11-23 16:28:34',575003166,'2023-11-23 18:31:34','2023-11-23 17:05:21','The Morning Show is back with a new show. It\'s called \"Inhale some helium\" and it\'s all about the evolution of the voice. The program starts off with a song about a man who was kidnapped and turned into a prisoner of war.\n\nThe guy is a famous singer named Marvin Gaye. The song is called \"Pride and Joy\" and the narrator says it sounds like he\'s back in the day. We\'re sure you\'re listening to this program right now, but you probably haven\'t heard it before. The narrator says he doesn\'t really have a voice like the one we hear on the show today. He\'s got a voice that sounds like it was in the \'50s, but he can\'t breathe. So he starts by inhaling some helium and tells us what\'s been going down.\n\nThe first song is \"Pilgrimage and Joy.\" The narrator goes on to say that he feels like his backbone is starting to slip, so he wants to tell the guy that he\'ll be back soon. The show ends with the song \"He\'s SoFine.\" We\'ll hear more about this later.',NULL,NULL),(69505,219,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/tpeq2g/ES231122.mp3','2023-11-23 16:18:17',140167924,'2023-11-24 02:38:25','2023-11-23 17:05:51','',NULL,NULL),(69506,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/23/FoodFarm Talk - November 23, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-23 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 17:47:40','2023-11-23 17:06:34','The farmers discuss how they can better manage their land in the face of climate change. They talk about rotational grazing as an alternative to conventional farming, and cover crops as a way to increase crop yields without damaging soil health.\n\nThe farmers also discuss how much time they spend on research, and how they don\'t always spend enough time on it. The conversation ends with a question about how people should use the word apocalypse to describe their current situation. The narrator thinks that many people already know the meaning of the word, but he thinks that it\'s hard for them to understand what an apocalypse might mean. He wonders if the word itself loses its meaning when people use it so often.',NULL,NULL),(69507,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/arc