,143961989,'2023-11-24 02:43:17','2023-11-23 21:05:18','This show is different from other shows in that she will be interviewing two guests at once. It is her pleasure to have both guests, Mark Franklin founder of the career-cycles slash podcast and the co-host and leader of Career Buzz, and Dr. Rich. Mark says that he was thinking about a listener\'s question about how he always says keep moving forward, because forward is the \"way to go,\" and he suggests that this is the purpose of the show. He says that the way he fixed it was to keep moving \"forward productively.\" Dr. Feller will join the show in a minute. They start the show with a question about moving forward productively, and Mark says he\'s interested in the topic because he\'d like to talk about how people can use career stewardship to help them move forward.',NULL,NULL),(69512,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/esezrp/November_19_2023_Karibuni9rad0.mp3','2023-11-23 20:14:08',287962512,'2023-11-24 02:41:45','2023-11-23 21:05:42','This is the last show of the year. The station is looking for donations to support the teaching of African languages. The guests have come from all over the world to hear the music. The show has been very supportive of African musicians in general. The program ends with a shout-out to all the guests who have come through the studio in the past few years.',NULL,NULL),(69513,205,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/4y2ii5/November_23rd_2023_Music_at_High_Noona9v4p.mp3','2023-11-23 20:12:52',287962512,'2023-11-23 22:07:15','2023-11-23 21:05:43','This week on the program, host Mike Tadros thanks all of the listeners who supported the university\'s fall campaign. He also asks listeners to support the university if they haven\'t yet done so. He hopes listeners will tune in to the program and donate if they didn\'t have a chance to do so.',NULL,NULL),(69514,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/23/Android’s Dungeon - November 23, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-23 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 21:54:19','2023-11-23 21:06:24','The narrator explains that he has moved from his office to the basement of his wife\'s house, where he has a co-host named Troy. The cat is named Riker, and they are watching Star Trek together. The narrator describes the studio where the show is being recorded, saying that he and his wife have moved from their office. He says that he is unable to sit on his old, cumbersome desk, and he needs to find something else to occupy the space.\n\nThe show is going to be very music heavy, and the narrator says that his co-hosts have abandoned him. The reason he did the show was to do a \"dialogue, a chat\" with people. Most shows, he says, don\'t have guests, they just have one person talking to another person. He puts on more music because that is his crutch. As he walks, he crawls away from this earthly coil',NULL,NULL),(69515,13307,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/23/Eclectic Selections - November 23, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-23 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 21:30:29','2023-11-23 21:07:53','This is the 35th anniversary of the seminal album \"The Trinity Sessions\" by the legendary New York City band. It includes \"postcard blues\" by Lou Reed, \"cello song\" by Nick Drake, and \"some Lou Reed\" with New York \"man\" and \"Nick Drake\'s\" cello song. The program opens with Mosna, a Canadian artist hailing from a small Quebec village named Saluite.\n\nShe\'s the creator of a new album, \"A Little Time For Me,\" which covers everyone from the Rolling Stones and Cyndi Lauper to \"Metallica\" and even \"the worst interview ever\" by Metallica\'s Kirk Hammett. Mosna explains that listening to the band allowed her to \"dig into the darkness\" of her soul and \"feel good about it.\" She also got a gig reporting on Inuit culture as a journalist for a Canadian Inuit broadcaster, TNI. Her producer gave her an opportunity to interview Kirk Hammett and she says that it was \"likely the worst interview\" ever given, but in her son\'s eyes it was the \"coolest.\" The program closes with a look at \"colonization and assimilation\" by Mosna.',NULL,NULL),(69516,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/23/RadiOPIRG - November 23, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-23 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 23:47:44','2023-11-23 23:06:31','This week, November 20th is Trans Day, a day to honor and remember trans lives lost. This year, Tori emceed an event for GQE.\n\nShe was too late to get a recorded version of the event, but she does want to share a recording of one of her People\'s Historical Project researchers, Robin Blase Kuiper, who did a great job organizing Queer Clans in Guelph back then. The interview with Tori is very brief, but it\'s clear that she\'s very interested in what\'s going on in the world around her. She tells us that the biggest thing that happened in her life was getting shot in the back of the head during the Civil War. She adds that it was okay, but that it did get better after that. She also tells us about her work with ARCH, where she was recently promoted to the position of head of the Peer Team. She describes herself as having had a life-changing injury at work and needed to find a job that would allow her to give back to others. She had worked for a number of different charities, and eventually got to work for ARCH. Sounds like a great gig.',NULL,NULL),(69517,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/23/T.K.O. - November 23, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-23 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 23:27:11','2023-11-23 23:06:32','This is a short introductory speech by Teta, a \"woman of science.\" She says that she is a \"Hashtag woman in STEM\" and that she wants to use her platform to share what she has learned along the way.\n\nShe says, \"I feel like every path has its up and downs. I mean, every journey has challenges, but at the end, we can attest that you know that yeah there were ones that needed to be overcome, and here, we are. At the same time, Teta wants to share this message with the world so that people will know that she has been there, been through it, and knows what it\'s like to be in your shoes. She wants people to know that it is easier to be loved by another person than it is to try to tell yourself that you\'re not good enough. Teta feels that it takes practice for people to tell themselves that they\'re good enough, but here, she hopes it will reach the right audience.',NULL,NULL),(69518,189,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/xqwm4c/vftcnov22.mp3','2023-11-23 23:14:26',281761958,'2023-11-24 02:34:16','2023-11-24 01:05:31','The next time we see the show, it\'s going to be an extended version of the music that we heard last week. This time around, we\'re going to hear some of the best alternative music of all time. The music is going to come from the \'80s and the 70s.\n\nWe\'re also going to get a little musical history lesson. The first song we hear is from a band called The Cars, who released their debut album in the early 80s. They had six singles on that first album, but they disbanded after only six years. The second song is from another \'80s band called the Avenger, who covered this song before they ever released their album.',NULL,NULL),(69519,280,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/yhxkc3/Ep89_Ecuador_and_Argentina7u6bc.mp3','2023-11-23 23:02:58',84604816,'2023-11-24 02:06:00','2023-11-24 01:05:53','In this episode of the new show \"Tracks From Abroad,\" Seth Martosh, co-host, and Alex Troxel, the producer, sit down to talk about the show\'s South American guests. The first guest is an Ecuadorian cellist named Tomas Pena, who is studying at the university. He tells the story of how he fell in love with the cello and how he ended up attending one of the world\'s best music schools, the Collejo Mendor, in Quito, Ecuador.',NULL,NULL),(69520,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/23/Open Sources Guelph - November 23, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-23 17:00:00',8