'2023-12-04 05:06:39','This is a very brief introduction to Backtracks by the host, Walter Walter. Backtracks is a music program which deals primarily with lost and obscure music from the golden age of rock and roll.\n\nHe will often throw in some new material if the show calls for it, but usually the music is from a theme, such as weather. In this case, the theme will be weather. The first song on the program is a song by the garage rock gurus Blue Slow BlueSnow Night. The song was one of the earliest to incorporate Middle Eastern influences into their garage music. The next song is from the Cleveland garage band It\'s cold outside. The choir. The final song is a single from Kim Fowley\'s band The Bush. The Bush is considered a notorious figure of early rock and Roll and garage music, and the song To die alone is considered quite a sex offender.\n\nThe show closes with a tribute to the late Shane McGowan, a punk musician who was at the forefront of the Irish punk movement in the late 1920s and early 1930s. He was known for reinvigoration of interest in punk folk especially in Irish music in a time when bombs and bullets were used against punk folk. The program ends with a song from John Cale, a former Velvet Underground member.',NULL,NULL),(69756,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 07:51:50','2023-12-04 07:07:10','The program begins with a brief break and then moves into the geographical spotlight segment. The program then resumes with a description of the show, which is hosted by Christopher Curry. The show features music by artists from countries around the world. The music is performed in a spotlight on each of the seven largest countries on the map. This spotlighting of countries is done on a deeper level than just the country itself, and also on each province or territory in a country. The segments of the program can be found on the CFRU website.',NULL,NULL),(69757,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/03/This Night Wounds Time - December 3, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-03 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 07:31:04','2023-12-04 07:07:10','The show is called \"This Night-Wounds Time,\" and it\'s all about music that is \"somewhat off-center\" . The music will be from \"off the beaten track,\" as Curry puts it. The first hour of the show will be devoted to that, and the second hour will be dedicated to the \"Geographic Spotlight Series,\" which is a series of special music spotlights on certain geographical regions of the world. For example, this week, the spotlight will be on the capital city of a particular province in Argentina.\n\nThe second hour of \"Geographical Spotlight\" will also include a re-broadcast of the previous week\'s show, which was not recorded in the CFRU archives because of a technical problem. This week, he\'s going to play a second rebroadcast, this time from 2 to 4:30, and then he\'ll play the first one from 2 until midnight.',NULL,NULL),(69758,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 02:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 02:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 09:52:52','2023-12-04 09:07:02','The show is back on the air, and the Host explains that he\'s decided to re-run the show because the previous week\'s edition didn\'t make it into the archives.\n\nHe\'s also going to make sure that the music on the show is the same as the music that he originally planned to play. The Host then points out that this is a bit of a coincidence, since he originally wanted to play the music for the Michiones first, and then the music from Hohoe later. But then he realized that he was wrong, and decided that he should play the Hohoe first. This is the first time that the Host has played the music he originally thought he was going to play, and this is the second time that he has played it. He reminds listeners that he did play the last song of the show, which was originally intended for the provinces of Canada, but then realized that it was a mistake to play it first. He says he\'ll play it again tonight, and he also says that the show will be rebroadcast again tomorrow.\n\nSo the Host says that if you missed the previous show, you can go to Upscill\'s 4Work.ca and check out what the University of Guelph has to offer. The University offers a wide range of jobs, including music production, live events, public service announcements and ads, and even live streams of the shows on YouTube and Soundcloud. If you want to get involved, email the Host',NULL,NULL),(69759,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 09:31:40','2023-12-04 09:07:02','In this program, the host of a local radio station, Christopher Curry, gives an introduction to a local musician from his home province, Argentina. The artist is Ramn Ayella, who was born in nearby Garupa in 1927 and is still alive. He is known as one of South America\'s greatest artists. He was invited to perform in Cuba in 1962, and he met with a fellow Argentinian, Che Guevara, who advised Ayella that his song, El Menzel, had been performed in the region of Sierra Maestra during the revolution in Cuba. Ayella\'s song, Ama Nacer En Missiones, is an original composition, and he apologizes for any inappropriate lyrics.',NULL,NULL),(69760,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 04:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 04:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 11:50:37','2023-12-04 11:07:16','This week\'s show opens with a description of the program. It\'s called \"Music on the Bus\" and it\'s a live music radio show that airs every Saturday on CFRU, the Canadian Free Public Broadcasting station. The program starts off by describing what\'s happening on the program tonight. We\'re hearing music from the province of Buenos Aires, and we\'re also hearing tracks by an artist named Zamba Kiildor.\n\nNext, we\'ll hear music from an Andean musician named Uri Ramos. Uri Ramos is from Humahuaque, Argentina, and he plays the bamboo flute. So we\'ve got a little bit of an introduction to the guy. The guy is a noted musician and composer who lives in the province and is known for his music. So listen for the program\'s ending. If you\'re interested in a commercial or public service announcement for your local business or organization, there\'s an ad package at the station that can be used to run the ad on the air.\n\nThe station also has a great website that\'s easy to navigate. There are lots of features like live streaming of all of our shows, searchable audio archives, and a donation page.',NULL,NULL),(69761,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 03:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 03:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 11:31:14','2023-12-04 11:07:17','The show begins with a discussion of the show\'s geographical focus and the musicians that will be featured there. It turns out that the show will be a showcase of music from the region of Hohoe, Argentina. The music featured will be by an artist named Michaela Cienegui, a quilla flute player, dancer, composer, and teacher. She is from a quilera indigenous community in Salta province, Argentina, but she is also a musician, a teacher, and a luthier. She grew up in Tilcara, in Hohoe province, and she is one of the first indigenous women to play the flute.\n\nThe instrument is a male-only instrument. She has two albums, one of which is dedicated to the show. The other is dedicated specifically to a singer named Toms Lipan, a singer from the Aymara indigenous community. The song is called \"Coesta de Lipan,\" which means \"Covenant Slope. The name of the river is unknown, but it is thought to be a clearing between hills, \"more or less zigzagging.\" The name is also associated with National Route 52, a highway that runs through the area. The show concludes with a description of Lipan Slope.',NULL,NULL),(69762,162,'https://ciut.fm/wp-content/uploads/audio/gospelmusicmachine.mp3','2023-12-04 14:23:26',0,'2023-12-04 17:08:11','2023-12-04 15:05:10','This is the first of a series of live music videos on the Gospel Machine, a music device that allows listeners to listen to music without having to pay for it. The first of these videos is from Sister Carlin Davis, who\'s singing a song called \"There\'s a Highway to Heaven.\n\n\" Sister Carlin tells the listeners that they can worship God anytime they want, even if it\'s slow. Sister Carlin invites listeners to join her on a trip to Barbados with \"Promise From Out of Barbados.\" The group will be singing praise music and giving thanks to God for all the blessings they\'ve received.',NULL,NULL),(69766,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - December 4, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 15:47:08','2023-12-04 15:05:54','',NULL,NULL),(69767,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Here Today - December 4, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 15:29:17','2023-12-04 15:06:31','Aaron Badgley is back on the program to talk about some new music. He\'s going to start off with Fyokovich, who\'s putting out some great music. Then he\'s got Alan Doyle\'s band with St. Johns Waltz, from a tribute album to a Newfoundland artist named Ron Hines.\n\nThen there\'s a band called The Moons of Jupiter, who are from England. Aaron plays some songs from their EP and then he plays a song from their upcoming self-titled album. He also plays songs from the Beatles from Liverpool, Dirty Hurricane, and a song by a band from Toronto named The Gryphons. Aaron says he loves these bands because they\'re hard-driving, rock-and-roll. He says they\'ve got a new single out called Christmas Is Coming, which is a really great song. Then they have a new album out called Town, and he says it\'s good that Elliott Brood is back with it. Aaron also says he fell into the Gryphons\' music from the first song he heard on their debut album, Like Gary Newman.',NULL,NULL),(69768,164,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ijzf8d/BEYOND_UN_Dec_4th6qkqu.mp3','2023-12-04 16:07:41',37311353,'2023-12-04 18:10:06','2023-12-04 17:05:22','In this edition of Beyond The Headlines, host Kimberly Watata introduces you to a new program called Beyond the Headslines.\n\nIt\'s a weekly current affairs show that takes you \"beyond the headlines\" of your daily news. We\'re talking about the United Nations\' Sustainable Development Goals, or SDGs, which are ambitious goals to improve health and education and reduce inequality. The SDGs were agreed upon by 193 countries in 2015, and are supposed to be a blueprint for peace, prosperity, and economic growth. Now that they\'re 2023, the \"clock is ticking\" and the goal to 2030 is \"at its halfway point\" . The question is whether or not the goals are still within reach, or whether it\'s an impossible dream. This week, we\'ll hear from our young delegates at the High-Level Political Forum on SDGs, who answer the question. They\'re here to tell you that the SDGs still have time to achieve their goals. They also talk about the high-level political Forum, where they\'ve been invited to discuss the SDGs with other delegates from around the world.\n\nOur first speaker is Jo, who works for Deloitte as a consultant on human services for the public sector. He\'s here to chat about the SDGs and how Canada has been implementing them. Jo says that the Canadian delegation at the high level political forum presented their country\'s progress on many of these goals, and he was impressed by how honest they were about where they were',NULL,NULL),(69769,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Breezy Breakfast Radio - December 4, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 17:50:08','2023-12-04 17:06:05','The meeting ends with the announcement that there is a meeting of the Board of Trustees on Tuesday, December 25th. The meeting will be followed by a town hall style meeting. The next morning, the board will meet to discuss the report of the committee.\n\nThe report is critical of the government for failing to provide adequate food for the poor and vulnerable. The group will discuss how the government can improve access to food for all. The board will also discuss the creation of a food security committee, a committee that will consist of representatives from the government, the community, and non-profit organizations.',NULL,NULL),(69770,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Breezy Breakfast Radio - December 4, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 05:18:04','2023-12-04 17:06:06','Discussion on the need for food security. Guelph is blessed with a good number of food service providers. ',NULL,NULL),(69771,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Worst Responders - December 4, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 19:48:35','2023-12-04 19:07:29','',NULL,NULL),(69772,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Democracy Now - December 4, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 19:28:12','2023-12-04 19:07:30','',NULL,NULL),(69773,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fv8kn3/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Dec_6_2023_podcast8jlox.mp3','2023-12-04 19:10:28',275448684,'2023-12-04 21:29:00','2023-12-04 21:05:38','The narrator explains the concept of \"karma,\" or the \"effect\" of one\'s actions. He explains that if you treat someone well, they\'ll be more likely to do something nice than if they\'re treated poorly. So, if you give someone a bad vibe, they will be less likely to be nice to someone else. Even though there are lots of people, the social circle is much smaller when you\'re down to it.\n\nSo even though there may be thousands of people who get exposed to the \"chain reaction,\" they won\'t all be the same person for a long, long time. The narrator adds that this is why he tries to support farmers, because if you\'ve got a farm, you\'ll probably want to be a farmer.',NULL,NULL),(69774,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/CFRU Playlist - December 4, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 21:05:52','2023-12-04 21:05:52',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69775,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - December 4, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 23:31:15','2023-12-04 23:05:53','In this episode, we learn more about the music being played in the studio. The narrator says that he wants to acknowledge and respect the traditional territories and the local Indigenous communities from which the music is being played. He also acknowledges that many of the music elements featured originated from the Black community adapting elements of their own culture under circumstances of oppression over the centuries past and present time. He thanks the Black music community for their contribution to the popular alternative music sphere. He concludes by saying that he is feeling better after contracting a seasonal illness the last few days.\n\nHe says he wanted to finish a piece that he had to fade off in the previous live session. He finishes off the session by saying he is going to play a collaboration with a group called Dirty Projectors, followed by the group Shun Shun, the Gordy Gordon band, the Wu band, and the Laura Mish band. He is also joined by two other guests, Charity Cruz and Isaiah Farabahksh. They are both listeners to the Sentinels Marvelous Kaleidoscope, a program that airs on CFRU\'s 93.3FM in Guelph. The first track they play is from the album Bit Orca by the band. They begin their first grand set with the song.',NULL,NULL),(69776,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Big Sis Radio - December 4, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 04:32:16','2023-12-05 01:05:48','On this episode of Big Sis, Cece tells us that she wishes more people would actually keep their conversations with strangers real.\n\nShe tells us about a new article that suggests that when we\'re asked to predict the awkwardness of a conversation, we underestimate the happiness we\'ll feel when we actually have a genuine conversation with someone. And when we are asked to guess how much we care about a stranger, we tend to guess that they\'ll care less about us than they actually do. Brain Snack: This research article was published in 2022 and was titled \"Overly Shallow Miscalibrated expectations create a barrier to deeper conversation.\" In other words, when people predict how awkward it\'s going to be, they\'re guessing that they won\'t care about their own feelings, and that they will just think about how other people will react to their comments.\n\nSo when we engage in deeper conversation with people we know, the thinking goes, we feel more connected than we do when we talk about the \"usual, more shallow\" stuff. Cece then shows us the latest track from a band called Fontaine\'s Dc off their latest record, Skinty-Fya. The band\'s name means \"doomed deer\" in Irish. The album cover features a giant deer inside an ominous looking animal.',NULL,NULL),(69777,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/to know the land - December 4, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 04:40:45','2023-12-05 01:05:58','A decolonizing poet from the Chippewa First Nation in the Thames Valley and is an Ojibewa or Anishinabe man. He is an Irish man who honors both his native and his European ancestry. The first thing he says is that he\'s giving a workshop on \"decolonizing language\" at a Spoken Word Finals in Guelph.\n\nThe audience is listening, and the he has a few questions for them. First, he wants to know what it means to \"declassify\" our language. He says that it\'s an English question, and that\'s basically the way he and his audience use the word. The English language, he says, was stolen from the native people and the languages that were used by them.\n\nHe wants to talk about this for a second, because what happens if you steal someone else\'s language. Part of the way that language is developed is that it has to be established and developed in the context of the people who live and speak it. The people who have been in the colonial society can\'t believe that their language was stolen, but it can be \"dismantling or disorienting.\"',NULL,NULL),(69778,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Blues Around the Block - December 4, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 04:08:14','2023-12-05 03:06:07','The host of the show, named Dee Mac, welcomes listeners to the program and encourages them to share their thoughts on the show with him by sending him an e-mail at macdee@calf.\n\nca. The program begins with a description of the crime that has taken place in the city. The show\'s first listener, named Sylvia Dee, tells the story of how he pawned his clothes to pay his rent. Then he and another listener discuss the music that has been released in the wake of the crimes. They compare the various acts and hear from the band members that they have had a hard time keeping up with the latest news.',NULL,NULL),(69779,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Blues Around the Block - December 4, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 03:50:19','2023-12-05 03:06:08','Mac Dee, host of the popular program \"Blues Around the Block\" on CFRU.org, takes listeners on a tour of the best of the blues, beginning with a listen to the music of Mike Griffin and his band. He then switches gears to a selection of songs from the \"Durham County Poets,\" \"Girl of My Dreams,\" \"Hoot and Holler,\" \"The Hog Town All-Stars,\" \"Fats Domino,\" and \"Coal Mining Blues\" by Matt Anderson. Mac Dee concludes the show with two songs about coal mining, one by Esqua Wilson and Tom Wilson.',NULL,NULL),(69780,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Ripcord Radio - December 4, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 05:54:59','2023-12-05 05:05:47','This is the second hour of the program and it\'s called \"Punk Rock\" on the program. This time, the program is going to be all Canadian music.\n\nIt\'s going to start with a bunch of music outside of Canada, mostly from punk bands that formed in the United States and Europe during the same time period. The first band we\'re going to hear is called X with Revolution and the second band is called Aspirations. Aspirations is the name of the first band\'s first album and Aspirations was released in October of 1979, a few months before the first one was released. Next up is a band called Basque with Perks and the first single is from their new album, Pain without Hope of Healing. The band is named after the city of Kitchener in Ontario. They\'re also releasing an album called No Funeral Sound in the next few months.\n\nThe next band we hear is The Dominion and the latest single is called No Fate. The group is from Southern Ontario and their members are all spread out between Ajax, Guelph, Caledon, and Toronto. The last band we heard is called Reaper with Satanic Prophesies and they released their first full length album last year. Then we hear Blue Oil\'s song Celebration.',NULL,NULL),(69781,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/The Deep House Project - December 4, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 05:32:23','2023-12-05 05:05:53','In this week\'s show, the CFRU staff discusses the university\'s decision to close the VIS Gallery and the ways in which the university will respond to the public outcry. They also discuss some of the research they\'re doing on older adults and youth during the pandemic. The team is conducting a study of young and older adults\' experiences during the Co-Impacted Volcano Virus-19 pandemic.\n\nThey\'re looking for people who are 5 to 65 years old and want to participate in the study. If you want to learn more about this study, visit the University of Guelph\'s website slash Life in Co-Isolated Pandemic. The CFRU team also announces its Best of 2022 concert. They play a lot of songs from the year, including Bob Moses\'s \"Hanging On,\" Sunshine, \"Sons of Maria,\" \"Machiavellian Princess,\" \"Moxie,\" \"The Fool,\" \"Malabar Princess,\" and \"Sunshine,\" among others. The show closes with \"La Troz,\" a song by Murney, Sultan, and Shepherd.',NULL,NULL),(69782,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Back in the USSR - December 4, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 07:51:42','2023-12-05 07:06:31','This program is an hour-long program that airs on CFRU, the communist station in Canada, on the anniversary of the October 20th, 1956, Great Socialist Revolution.\n\nIt\'s a program about heroic people and their armed forces. The program opens with a long speech by a member of the Communist Party, praising the achievements of the revolutionary movement. The speaker then goes on to talk about the tragedy in the Middle East. He\'s talking about the war in the Gaza Strip, which has been going on for the past seven days. The ceasefire ended on Friday, and Israel is once again bombing the Gaza strip. There are hundreds of dead civilians in the war. This is horrifying. The narrator says that it\'s hard to believe that war crimes are piling up so quickly. He',NULL,NULL),(69783,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Rainbow Country - December 5, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 07:31:24','2023-12-05 07:07:45','Kinga joins host Mark Tara to share his story on Canada\'s first dance radio show, called Rainbow C