hat he discovered the blues in popular music when he listened to local bands like the Lighthouse and the Crowbar. He also mentions that Elton John was a big fan of the music, especially of his song \"Honky Chateau\" which was named after Long John Baldy. The music also includes a song by another local band called Blood, Sweat, and Tears.',NULL,NULL),(69790,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Solipsistic Retreat - December 5, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 17:49:42','2023-12-05 17:07:51','In this special edition of the host, the underground punk opens by thanking Bri Webb for her years of service to CFRU. He thanks her for her latest album, which is at number one in the CFRU music charts. He also thanks the station for bringing the show to the community.\n\nHe says that he\'s not even in Guelph, but he was born there and raised. He explains that everything in the city of Guelph is changing, just like the rest of the country. He compares this to Carl Marx\'s theory of constant improvement, which says that all that is solid dissolves into air. He adds that it\'s the \"frivolousness\" of an economy that is based on \"constant improvement\" . He argues that people are buying stuff that isn\'t actually there.\n\nThe only way to know that you\'re buying the right stuff is to vote for it. Bri doesn\'t want to ask for money, though, and says that it is important to give it to friends. He plays a song called \"Breakdown\" by the AP Buzzcocks, which he says is their best song, but it is not included on any of their other compilations. He thinks that the song is \"first class junk\" , which means that it was made by an English man. The song is one of many that the band uses to change the track listing of other songs so that when a band does something, it will appear on the next',NULL,NULL),(69791,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Solipsistic Retreat - December 5, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 09