23 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 21:30:17','2023-12-05 21:07:21','On this edition of Live On KEXP, the show celebrates the lineage of Black Belt Eagle scout, Catherine Paul or Catherine Paul. Catherine Paul is an artist who records in her native Swinomish language. Her latest album is called The Land, the Water, and the Sky.\n\nIt\'s her third full length album and her first album in a long time. Her songs are all about her return home after having spent time in Portland or in the ancestral homeland of the Chinook tribe or the Clackams tribe. KEXP\'s DJ, Cheryl Waters, asks Catherine Paul why she wanted to move home after the pandemic. Catherine says she always wanted to go on tour and then move back home. When her parents needed help during the pandemic, she decided to move back to her hometown. Her husband, her stepchildren, and her band decided they were going to move as well. Catherine explains that she spent a lot time outside during the time of the pandemic because she had a much closer connection to her home and to her community.',NULL,NULL),(69796,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fqd3ds/DrMouth_CIUTshow_dec4_2023_fullshow.mp3','2023-12-05 22:33:37',284290688,'2023-12-06 00:32:30','2023-12-05 23:05:20','Dr. Mouth, James Brown, and a bunch of other local musicians perform at a charity rock concert. The band starts off with a cover of a punk song by Saint, and then they start to do their own songs. Then James Clark finally drops his new album, Under the Lamp-shade. He plays the whole thing in its entirety, then plays some other songs, and it\'s clear that he\'s playing like a real rock star. The b side of one of his earlier albums is on this one, which is also on his new one.',NULL,NULL),(69797,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/kuctwd/December_1_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow88liz.mp3','2023-12-05 22:01:15',287962512,'2023-12-06 00:07:40','2023-12-05 23:05:43','',NULL,NULL),(69798,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/arc